{"title_page": "Chingachgook", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Chingachgook\n| series             = [[Leatherstocking Tales]]/[[The Last of the Mohicans]]\n| image              = Chingachgook-ASIN-B00005NFMB.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = [[Gojko Miti\u0107]] playing Chingachgook the Great Serpent, in an eponymous East German western film.\n| first              = ''[[The Pioneers (novel)|The Pioneers]]''\n| last               = ''[[The Deerslayer]]''\n| creator            = [[James Fenimore Cooper]]\n| alias              = Le Gros Serpent, Indian John, John Mohican\n| occupation         = Chief\n| spouse             = Wah-ta-Wah (wife)\n| gender             = Male\n| children           = Uncas (son)\n| religion           = Mahican tradition, Moravian convert\n| nationality        = [[Mahican]]\n}}\n'''Chingachgook''' is a [[fictional character]] in four of [[James Fenimore Cooper]]'s five [[Leatherstocking Tales]], including ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]''. Chingachgook was a lone [[Mohican]] chief and companion of the series' hero, [[Natty Bumppo]]. In ''[[The Deerslayer]]'', Chingachgook married Wah-ta-Wah, who bore him a son named Uncas, but died while she was still young. Uncas, who was at his birth \"last of the Mohicans\",<ref>\"Uncas will be the last pure-blooded Mohican because there are no pure-blooded Mohican women for him to marry.\" [http://coursesite.uhcl.edu/hsh/Whitec/LITR/4232/research/critics/mohicansassgn.htm Craig White, \"Guide to ''The Last of the Mohicans'' (1826) by James Fenimore Cooper (1789-1851)\", LITR 4232 coursesite, University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake]</ref> grew to manhood but was killed in a battle with the Huron warrior [[Magua]]. Chingachgook died as an old man in the novel ''[[The Pioneers (novel)|The Pioneers]]'', which makes him the actual \"last of the Mohicans,\" having outlived his son.\n\n== ''The Leatherstocking Tales'' ==\nIn the series ''[[Leatherstocking Tales|The Leatherstocking Tales]]'' by [[James Fenimore Cooper]], Chingachgook is the best friend and companion of the main character [[Natty Bumppo]], aka Hawkeye. He appears in ''[[The Deerslayer]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/3285/3285-h/3285-h.htm|title=The Deerslayer by James Fenimore Cooper|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]'',<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[The Pathfinder, or The Inland Sea|The Pathfinder]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/1880?msg=welcome_stranger|title=The Pathfinder; Or, The Inland Sea by James Fenimore Cooper|language=en-US}}</ref> and ''[[The Pioneers (novel)|The Pioneers]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/2275/2275-h/2275-h.htm|title=The Pioneers, by J. Fenimore Cooper|website=www.gutenberg.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> He is characterized by his skills as a warrior and forester, his bravery, his wisdom, and his pride for his tribe.\n\n==Etymology and pronunciation==\n\nChingachgook is said to have been modeled after a real-life wandering Mohican basket maker and hunter named Captain John. The fictional character, occasionally called John Mohegan in the series, was an idealized embodiment of the traditional [[noble savage]]. [[French people|The French]] often refer to Chingachgook as \"{{lang|fr|Le Gros Serpent}}\", the Great Snake, because he understands the winding ways of men's nature and he can strike a sudden, deadly blow.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://xroads.virginia.edu/~HYPER/HNS/Indians/last.html |title=Last of the Mohicans |publisher=Xroads.virginia.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe name is derived from the [[Lenape language]], which is closely related to the [[Mohican language]]. In Lenape, {{lang|del|xinkw-}} means 'big'<ref>{{cite web |title=xinkw- |url=http://talk-lenape.org/detail?id=14673 |work=Lenape Talking Dictionary |accessdate=2018-08-23 }}</ref> and {{lang|del|xkuk}} means 'snake'.<ref>{{cite web |title=xkuk |url=http://talk-lenape.org/detail?id=11642 |work=Lenape Talking Dictionary|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref> ''Chingachgook'' is derived from Lenape {{lang|del|xinkwi xkuk}}, 'big snake', pronounced {{IPA-all|\u00e7i\u014b\u0261wixkuk|}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=xinkwi xkuk |url=http://talk-lenape.org/detail?id=14537 |work=Lenape Talking Dictionary |accessdate=2018-08-23 |url-status=live }} This page includes an audio file of the words being pronounced by a native Lenape speaker.</ref> The digraph {{angle bracket|ch}} in the spelling used by [[John Heckewelder]], the source for the name, and the letter {{angle bracket|x}} in modern Lenape spelling both represent the [[voiceless velar fricative]] sound {{IPA|[x]}} (as in \"[[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]\") and the [[voiceless palatal fricative]] sound {{IPA|[\u00e7]}} (as in {{lang-de|Ich}}), not the [[voiceless palato-alveolar affricate]] {{IPA|[t\u0361\u0283]}} (as in \"church\").\n\nCooper got the name from Heckewelder's book ''History, Manners, and Customs of the Indian Nations who once inhabited Pennsylvania and the Neighboring States''<ref>{{cite book |last=Slotkin |first=Richard |title=The Fatal Environment: The Myth of the Frontier in the Age of Industrialization, 1800\u20131890 |year=1998 |publisher=University of Oklahoma Press |location=[[Norman, Oklahoma|Norman]] |isbn=0-8061-3030-X |pages=93\u201394 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tf2XVsLUBsoC&lpg=PA93&pg=PA93#v=onepage&q&f=false |authorlink=Richard Slotkin |accessdate=2012-10-28 }}</ref> (1818), which cited a Lenape word as \"{{lang|del|chingachgook}}\" (in Heckewelder's spelling which was influenced by [[German language|German]]), meaning \"a large snake\". He gave this word as such in the context of how to use the adjective {{lang|del|xinkwi}} (pronounced {{IPA-all|\u00e7i\u014b\u0261wi|}}) 'large', which Heckewelder spelled {{lang|del|chingue}}.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heckewelder |first=John |title=History, Manners, and Customs of the Indian Nations who once inhabited Pennsylvania and the Neighboring States |year=1876 |location=Philadelphia |publisher=[[Historical Society of Pennsylvania]] |url=https://archive.org/details/historymannersa01heckgoog |authorlink=John Heckewelder |accessdate=2012-10-28 |page=[https://archive.org/details/historymannersa01heckgoog/page/n438 431] }}</ref>\n\n==Portrayals in film and television==\n\nThe first film portrayal of Chingachgook was by [[Wallace Reid]] in a 1913 film version of ''The Deerslayer''.\n\n[[Bela Lugosi]] played Chingachgook in two German silent films, ''Lederstrumpf, 1. Teil: Der Wildt\u00f6ter und Chingachgook'' (''Leatherstocking 1: [[The Deerslayer and Chingachgook]]'') and ''Lederstrumpf, 2. Teil: Der Letzte der Mohikaner'' (''Leatherstocking 2: [[The Last of the Mohicans (1920 German film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]''), both filmed in 1920.\n\n[[Jay Silverheels]], best known for his role as [[Tonto]] on ''[[The Lone Ranger (TV series)|The Lone Ranger]]'', played Chingachgook in the 1953 film version of ''[[The Pathfinder (1952 film)|The Pathfinder]]''.\n\n[[Lon Chaney, Jr.]] played Chingachgook in the 1957 TV series ''[[Hawkeye and the Last of the Mohicans]]''.\n\nChingachgook, played by [[Gojko Miti\u0107]], was the main character of an [[East German]] [[Western (genre)|western]], ''Chingachgook the Great Serpent'' (1967), based on Cooper's novels.\n\nIn the [[BBC]] miniseries ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1971 series)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'' and ''The Pathfinder'', Chingachgook was played by [[John Abineri]].\n\nChingachgook was played by [[Ned Romero]] in the TV versions of ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1977 film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'' (1977) and ''The Deerslayer'' (1978), by [[Russell Means]] in the 1992 film adaptation of ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1992 film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'', by [[Rodney A. Grant]] in the 1994 TV series ''[[Hawkeye (1994 TV series)|Hawkeye]]'' and by [[Graham Greene (actor)|Graham Greene]] in the 1996 TV version of ''The Pathfinder''.\n\nMany films portray Chingachgook with long hair, braided or flowing. A notable exception is [[The Last of the Mohicans (1920 American film)|the 1920 adaptation]] which faithfully represents him with a tuft on his shaved head, according to the novel.\n\n==In Boy Scout legend==\nIn the Ordeal Ceremony of the [[Order of the Arrow]], a program of the [[Boy Scouts of America]], the Legend of the Order refers to an imaginary [[Lenni Lenape]] chief named Chingachgook. In the legend, Chingachgook's son, Uncas, is the original propagator of the Order. Chingachgook wanted to create a band of volunteers from all the nations of the [[Delaware River]] valley to support and protect their collective interests. Uncas volunteered to be the first member of such a group, and thus the Order of the Arrow was founded.\n\nAccording to the Boy Scouts of America's Ordeal Ceremony, the correct pronunciation of the name is ching-gatch-gook.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boy Scouts of America|title=Order of the Arrow Ordeal Ceremony Pamphlet|url=http://oaceremonies.org/Documents/Training/pronunciation_guide.html|publisher=Boy Scouts of America|accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref> Professor William A. Starna, of SUNY Oneonta, says the initial \"ch\" sound would be pronounced more like the German guttural \"h\" than an English \"ch\". Chingachgook is an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] word meaning big (ching) snake (achgook); hence the references to the character in the book as The Great Serpent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Starna|first=William|title=Cooper's Indians: A Critique|url=http://external.oneonta.edu/cooper/articles/suny/1979suny-starna.html|publisher=State University College of New York|accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Last of the Mohicans}}\n\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1823]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Drama film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional Native American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional sole survivors]]\n[[Category:James Fenimore Cooper]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Chingachgook\n| series             = [[Leatherstocking Tales]]/[[The Last of the Mohicans]]\n| image              = Chingachgook-ASIN-B00005NFMB.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| caption            = [[Gojko Miti\u0107]] playing Chingachgook the Great Serpent, in an eponymous East German western film.\n| first              = ''[[The Pioneers (novel)|The Pioneers]]''\n| last               = ''[[The Deerslayer]]''\n| creator            = [[James Fenimore Cooper]]\n| alias              = Le Gros Serpent, Indian John, John Mohican\n| occupation         = Chief\n| spouse             = Wah-ta-Wah (wife)\n| gender             = Male\n| children           = Uncas (son)\n| religion           = Mahican tradition, Moravian convert\n| nationality        = [[Mahican]]\n}}\n'''Chingachgook''' is a [[fictional character]] in four of [[James Fenimore Cooper]]'s five [[Leatherstocking Tales]], including ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]''. Chingachgook was a lone [[Mohican]] chief and companion of the series' hero, [[Natty Bumppo]]. In ''[[The Deerslayer]]'', Chingachgook married Wah-ta-Wah, who bore him a son named Uncas, but died while she was still young. Uncas, who was at his birth \"last of the Mohicans\",<ref>\"Uncas will be the last pure-blooded Mohican because there are no pure-blooded Mohican women for him to marry.\" [http://coursesite.uhcl.edu/hsh/Whitec/LITR/4232/research/critics/mohicansassgn.htm Craig White, \"Guide to ''The Last of the Mohicans'' (1826) by James Fenimore Cooper (1789-1851)\", LITR 4232 coursesite, University of Houston\u2013Clear Lake]</ref> grew to manhood but was killed in a battle with the Huron warrior [[Magua]]. Chingachgook died as an old man in the novel ''[[The Pioneers (novel)|The Pioneers]]'', which makes him the actual \"last of the Mohicans,\" having outlived his son.\n\n== ''The Leatherstocking Tales'' ==\nIn the series ''[[Leatherstocking Tales|The Leatherstocking Tales]]'' by [[James Fenimore Cooper]], Chingachgook is the best friend and companion of the main character [[Natty Bumppo]], aka Hawkeye. He appears in ''[[The Deerslayer]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/3285/3285-h/3285-h.htm|title=The Deerslayer by James Fenimore Cooper|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]'',<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[The Pathfinder, or The Inland Sea|The Pathfinder]]'',<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/1880?msg=welcome_stranger|title=The Pathfinder; Or, The Inland Sea by James Fenimore Cooper|language=en-US}}</ref> and ''[[The Pioneers (novel)|The Pioneers]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gutenberg.org/files/2275/2275-h/2275-h.htm|title=The Pioneers, by J. Fenimore Cooper|website=www.gutenberg.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> He is characterized by his skills as a warrior and forester, his bravery, his wisdom, and his pride for his tribe.\n\n==Etymology and pronunciation==\n\nChingachgook is said to have been modeled after a real-life wandering Mohican basket maker and hunter named Captain John. The fictional character, occasionally called John Mohegan in the series, was an idealized embodiment of the traditional [[noble savage]]. [[French people|The French]] often refer to Chingachgook as \"''Le Gros Serpent''\", the Great Snake, because he understands the winding ways of men's nature and he can strike a sudden, deadly blow.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://xroads.virginia.edu/~HYPER/HNS/Indians/last.html |title=Last of the Mohicans |publisher=Xroads.virginia.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-04-11}}</ref>\n\nThe name is derived from the [[Lenape language]], which is closely related to the [[Mohican language]]. In Lenape, ''xinkw-'' means 'big'<ref>{{cite web|title=xinkw-|url=http://talk-lenape.org/detail?id=14673|work=Lenape Talking Dictionary|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref> and ''xkuk'' means 'snake'.<ref>{{cite web|title=xkuk|url=http://talk-lenape.org/detail?id=11642|work=Lenape Talking Dictionary|accessdate=2018-08-23}}</ref> ''Chingachgook'' is derived from Lenape ''xinkwi xkuk'', 'big snake', pronounced {{IPA-all|\u00e7i\u014b\u0261wixkuk|}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=xinkwi xkuk|url=http://talk-lenape.org/detail?id=14537|work=Lenape Talking Dictionary|accessdate=2018-08-23|url-status=live}} This page includes an audio file of the words being pronounced by a native Lenape speaker.</ref> The digraph {{angle bracket|ch}} in the spelling used by [[John Heckewelder]], the source for the name, and the letter {{angle bracket|x}} in modern Lenape spelling both represent the [[voiceless velar fricative]] sound {{IPA|[x]}} (as in \"[[Johann Sebastian Bach|Bach]]\") and the [[voiceless palatal fricative]] sound {{IPA|[\u00e7]}} (as in {{lang-de|Ich}}), not the [[voiceless palato-alveolar affricate]] {{IPA|[t\u0361\u0283]}} (as in \"church\").\n\nCooper got the name from Heckewelder's book ''History, Manners, and Customs of the Indian Nations who once inhabited Pennsylvania and the Neighboring States''<ref>{{cite book|last=Slotkin|first=Richard|title=The Fatal Environment: The Myth of the Frontier in the Age of Industrialization, 1800-1890|year=1998|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press|location=Norman|isbn=0-8061-3030-X|pages=93\u201394|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Tf2XVsLUBsoC&lpg=PA93&pg=PA93#v=onepage&q&f=false|authorlink=Richard Slotkin|accessdate=2012-10-28}}</ref> (1818), which cited a Lenape word as \"''chingachgook''\" (in Heckewelder's spelling which was influenced by [[German language|German]]), meaning \"a large snake\". He gave this word as such in the context of how to use the adjective ''xinkwi'' (pronounced {{IPA-all|\u00e7i\u014b\u0261wi}}) 'large', which Heckewelder spelled \"chingue\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Heckewelder|first=John|title=History, Manners, and Customs of the Indian Nations who once inhabited Pennsylvania and the Neighboring States|year=1876|location=Philadelphia|publisher=Historical Society of Pennsylvania|url=https://archive.org/details/historymannersa01heckgoog|authorlink=John Heckewelder|accessdate=2012-10-28|page=[https://archive.org/details/historymannersa01heckgoog/page/n438 431]}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayals in film and television==\n\nThe first film portrayal of Chingachgook was by [[Wallace Reid]] in a 1913 film version of ''The Deerslayer''.\n\n[[Bela Lugosi]] played Chingachgook in two German silent films, ''Lederstrumpf, 1. Teil: Der Wildt\u00f6ter und Chingachgook'' (''Leatherstocking 1: [[The Deerslayer and Chingachgook]]'') and ''Lederstrumpf, 2. Teil: Der Letzte der Mohikaner'' (''Leatherstocking 2: [[The Last of the Mohicans (1920 German film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]''), both filmed in 1920.\n\n[[Jay Silverheels]], best known for his role as [[Tonto]] on ''[[The Lone Ranger (TV series)|The Lone Ranger]]'', played Chingachgook in the 1953 film version of ''[[The Pathfinder (1952 film)|The Pathfinder]]''.\n\n[[Lon Chaney, Jr.]] played Chingachgook in the 1957 TV series ''[[Hawkeye and the Last of the Mohicans]]''.\n\nChingachgook, played by [[Gojko Miti\u0107]], was the main character of an [[East German]] [[Western (genre)|western]], ''Chingachgook the Great Serpent'' (1967), based on Cooper's novels.\n\nIn the [[BBC]] miniseries ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1971 series)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'' and ''The Pathfinder'', Chingachgook was played by [[John Abineri]].\n\nChingachgook was played by [[Ned Romero]] in the TV versions of ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1977 film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'' (1977) and ''The Deerslayer'' (1978), by [[Russell Means]] in the 1992 film adaptation of ''[[The Last of the Mohicans (1992 film)|The Last of the Mohicans]]'', by [[Rodney A. Grant]] in the 1994 TV series ''[[Hawkeye (1994 TV series)|Hawkeye]]'' and by [[Graham Greene (actor)|Graham Greene]] in the 1996 TV version of ''The Pathfinder''.\n\nMany films portray Chingachgook with long hair, braided or flowing. A notable exception is [[The Last of the Mohicans (1920 American film)|the 1920 adaptation]] which faithfully represents him with a tuft on his shaved head, according to the novel.\n\n==In Boy Scout legend==\nIn the Ordeal Ceremony of the [[Order of the Arrow]], a program of the [[Boy Scouts of America]], the Legend of the Order refers to an imaginary [[Lenni Lenape]] chief named Chingachgook. In the legend, Chingachgook's son, Uncas, is the original propagator of the Order. Chingachgook wanted to create a band of volunteers from all the nations of the [[Delaware River]] valley to support and protect their collective interests. Uncas volunteered to be the first member of such a group, and thus the Order of the Arrow was founded.\n\nAccording to the Boy Scouts of America's Ordeal Ceremony, the correct pronunciation of the name is ching-gatch-gook.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boy Scouts of America|title=Order of the Arrow Ordeal Ceremony Pamphlet|url=http://oaceremonies.org/Documents/Training/pronunciation_guide.html|publisher=Boy Scouts of America|accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref> Professor William A. Starna, of SUNY Oneonta, says the initial \"ch\" sound would be pronounced more like the German guttural \"h\" than an English \"ch\". Chingachgook is an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] word meaning big (ching) snake (achgook); hence the references to the character in the book as The Great Serpent.<ref>{{cite web|last=Starna|first=William|title=Cooper's Indians: A Critique|url=http://external.oneonta.edu/cooper/articles/suny/1979suny-starna.html|publisher=State University College of New York|accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Last of the Mohicans}}\n\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1823]]\n[[Category:Characters in American novels of the 19th century]]\n[[Category:Drama film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional Native American people]]\n[[Category:Fictional sole survivors]]\n[[Category:James Fenimore Cooper]]\n", "name_user": "OwenBlacker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEtymology and pronunciation:Language tagging; minor edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chingachgook"}
{"title_page": "Seerat Kapoor", "text_new": "{{Unreliable sources|date=August 2017}}{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Seerat Kapoor\n| image              = https://www.google.com/search?q=seerat+kapoor&safe=active&client=ms-android-lenovo&prmd=inv&sxsrf=ALeKk00N9viJ2FnGekAipt7h1MGZqPTmtg:1586439040723&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjqnuv7udvoAhWS8XMBHUkhBeQQ_AUoAXoECBIQAQ&cshid=1586439054064&biw=360&bih=560&dpr=3#imgrc=YFibhHK8SyPDQM\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Seerat Kapoor\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1993|4|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai, India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = Dance Instructor, Actress, Choreographer and Model\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| height             = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Seerat Kapoor''' (born 3 April 1993) is an Indian film actress, model, choreographer and dancer. She began her career as an Assistant [[Choreographer]] for [[Rockstar (2011 film)|''Rockstar'']]. She made her acting debut in ''[[Run Raja Run]]'' ([[Telugu language|Telugu]]) in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nKapoor was born on 3 April 1993 in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]. Her father, the late Vineet Kapoor was a [[Hotel manager|hotelier]] and her mother, Neena Sihota Kapoor, is an air hostess with [[Air India]]. Her elder brother Varun Kapoor is a graduate from [[National Art School]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] and works as a [[Freelancer|freelance]] [[graphic designer]].\n \nKapoor was educated at [[Mumbai]]'s [[Podar International School]], Santa Cruz and completed her pre-university course at [[R. D. National College]], [[Bandra]]. She subsequently enrolled for a Bachelor Of Arts degree in [[Mass communication]], but quit it due to scheduling conflicts with her acting.\n\nAt the time, she was at the peak of her dance career, which she began at age 16 for Bollywood choreographer; [[Ashley Lobo]], The Danceworx, [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedanceworx.com/|title=Dance Classes in Delhi, Mumbai, Gurgaon, Noida - Jazz Funk Ballet|website=Thedanceworx.com|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> Kapoor was a full-time dance instructor at the academy. In the course of her journey, Kapoor worked on Rockstar and was brought on board as Assistant [[Choreographer]].\n\nIntrigued by modelling, she trained as an actor at her cousin's grandfather's institution, Roshan Tanejaa School Of Acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/discovering-her-calling/article6151636.ece|title=Discovering her calling|website=Thehindu.com|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> In 2014, Kapoor debuted in ''Run Raja Run''.\n\n==Career==\nKapoor announced in 2014 that she would appear in ''[[Sharwanand]]'', directed by [[Sujeeth]] . ''Run Raja Run'' was a commercial success.\n\nIn 2015 Madhu B. and N.V. Prasad signed her to play Ganga in the action film ''Tiger''. Set against the backdrop of [[Varanasi]], the film also starred Sundeep Kishan and Rahul Ravindran. Her next release (2015) came alongside Sumanth Ashwin in the R. Shamala directed romantic comedy, ''Columbus,'' produced by Ashwani Kumar Sahdev. Kapoor's performance was applauded as the highlight of the film in the role of Neeraja.\n\nIn October 2017, she completed filming ''[[Raju Gari Gadhi 2]]'' opposite [[Akkineni Nagarjuna]] and was filming ''[[Touch Chesi Chudu]]'' opposite [[Ravi Teja]] and [[Allu Sirish]]'s ''Okka Kshanam''.\n\nKapoor endorsed several brands and products, including Vivel,<ref>{{cite web|title=Will you say #AbSamjhautaNahin ?\n|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nqxu0BOVoSo|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> Engage Cologne Sprays,<ref>{{cite web|title=Engage Cologne Sprays TVC 45 sec|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WYBZ6m2veg0|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> [[Apollo Tyres]] for [[Dibakar Banerjee]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Apollo Tyres - College Girl|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yFJoEStmrSU|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> [[Mahindra Group|Mahindra]] gusto and<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 #Mahindra #Gusto 125 (#India) promo video\n|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4WzDZX969Jo|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> [[Intex]] with [[Farhan Akhtar]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Intex Aqua Craze TVC With Farhan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YB4GSQVFI3Q|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref>\n\n== Other work ==\nIn addition to acting and dancing, Kapoor is a trained Indian Classical singer from Rajesree School Of Music from age 12.\n\n==Filmography==\n;As actor\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Language !!  Notes\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Zid (2014 film)|Zid]]'' || Nancy || [[Hindi]] ||\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Run Raja Run]]'' || Priya || rowspan='7'|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Tiger (2015 film)|Tiger]]'' || Ganga ||  \n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Columbus (2015 film)|Columbus]]'' || Neeraja || \n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Raju Gari Gadhi 2]]'' || Suhanisa || \n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Okka Kshanam]]'' || Swathi || \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Touch Chesi Chudu]]'' || Divya ||  \n|-\n|2020|| krishna and his leela||{{TBA}}||post-production\n|-\n|}\n\n; As assistant choreographer.....\n\n* 2011 - ''[[Rockstar (2011 film)|Rockstar]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140720/entertainment-tollywood/article/tollywood%E2%80%99s-latest-debutante-seerat-kapoor|title=Tollywood\u2019s latest debutante Seerat Kapoor|date=20 July 2014|website=Deccanchronicle.com|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=6682161|name=Seerat Kapoor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapoor, Seerat}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Female models from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian dance teachers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreliable sources|date=August 2017}}{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Seerat Kapoor\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Seerat Kapoor\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1993|4|3}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai, India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = Dance Instructor, Actress, Choreographer and Model\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| height             = \n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Seerat Kapoor''' (born 3 April 1993) is an Indian film actress, model, choreographer and dancer. She began her career as an Assistant [[Choreographer]] for [[Rockstar (2011 film)|''Rockstar'']]. She made her acting debut in ''[[Run Raja Run]]'' ([[Telugu language|Telugu]]) in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nKapoor was born on 3 April 1993 in [[Mumbai]], [[India]]. Her father, the late Vineet Kapoor was a [[Hotel manager|hotelier]] and her mother, Neena Sihota Kapoor, is an air hostess with [[Air India]]. Her elder brother Varun Kapoor is a graduate from [[National Art School]], [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] and works as a [[Freelancer|freelance]] [[graphic designer]].\n \nKapoor was educated at [[Mumbai]]'s [[Podar International School]], Santa Cruz and completed her pre-university course at [[R. D. National College]], [[Bandra]]. She subsequently enrolled for a Bachelor Of Arts degree in [[Mass communication]], but quit it due to scheduling conflicts with her acting.\n\nAt the time, she was at the peak of her dance career, which she began at age 16 for Bollywood choreographer; [[Ashley Lobo]], The Danceworx, [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thedanceworx.com/|title=Dance Classes in Delhi, Mumbai, Gurgaon, Noida - Jazz Funk Ballet|website=Thedanceworx.com|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> Kapoor was a full-time dance instructor at the academy. In the course of her journey, Kapoor worked on Rockstar and was brought on board as Assistant [[Choreographer]].\n\nIntrigued by modelling, she trained as an actor at her cousin's grandfather's institution, Roshan Tanejaa School Of Acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/discovering-her-calling/article6151636.ece|title=Discovering her calling|website=Thehindu.com|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref> In 2014, Kapoor debuted in ''Run Raja Run''.\n\n==Career==\nKapoor announced in 2014 that she would appear in ''[[Sharwanand]]'', directed by [[Sujeeth]] . ''Run Raja Run'' was a commercial success.\n\nIn 2015 Madhu B. and N.V. Prasad signed her to play Ganga in the action film ''Tiger''. Set against the backdrop of [[Varanasi]], the film also starred Sundeep Kishan and Rahul Ravindran. Her next release (2015) came alongside Sumanth Ashwin in the R. Shamala directed romantic comedy, ''Columbus,'' produced by Ashwani Kumar Sahdev. Kapoor's performance was applauded as the highlight of the film in the role of Neeraja.\n\nIn October 2017, she completed filming ''[[Raju Gari Gadhi 2]]'' opposite [[Akkineni Nagarjuna]] and was filming ''[[Touch Chesi Chudu]]'' opposite [[Ravi Teja]] and [[Allu Sirish]]'s ''Okka Kshanam''.\n\nKapoor endorsed several brands and products, including Vivel,<ref>{{cite web|title=Will you say #AbSamjhautaNahin ?\n|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nqxu0BOVoSo|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> Engage Cologne Sprays,<ref>{{cite web|title=Engage Cologne Sprays TVC 45 sec|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WYBZ6m2veg0|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> [[Apollo Tyres]] for [[Dibakar Banerjee]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Apollo Tyres - College Girl|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yFJoEStmrSU|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> [[Mahindra Group|Mahindra]] gusto and<ref>{{cite web|title=2016 #Mahindra #Gusto 125 (#India) promo video\n|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4WzDZX969Jo|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref> [[Intex]] with [[Farhan Akhtar]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Intex Aqua Craze TVC With Farhan|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YB4GSQVFI3Q|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2017-08-09}}</ref>\n\n== Other work ==\nIn addition to acting and dancing, Kapoor is a trained Indian Classical singer from Rajesree School Of Music from age 12.\n\n==Filmography==\n;As actor\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Language !!  Notes\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Zid (2014 film)|Zid]]'' || Nancy || [[Hindi]] ||\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Run Raja Run]]'' || Priya || rowspan='7'|[[Telugu language|Telugu]]||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Tiger (2015 film)|Tiger]]'' || Ganga ||  \n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Columbus (2015 film)|Columbus]]'' || Neeraja || \n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Raju Gari Gadhi 2]]'' || Suhanisa || \n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Okka Kshanam]]'' || Swathi || \n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Touch Chesi Chudu]]'' || Divya ||  \n|-\n|2020|| krishna and his leela||{{TBA}}||post-production\n|-\n|}\n\n; As assistant choreographer.....\n\n* 2011 - ''[[Rockstar (2011 film)|Rockstar]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/140720/entertainment-tollywood/article/tollywood%E2%80%99s-latest-debutante-seerat-kapoor|title=Tollywood\u2019s latest debutante Seerat Kapoor|date=20 July 2014|website=Deccanchronicle.com|accessdate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=6682161|name=Seerat Kapoor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapoor, Seerat}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian actresses]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Indian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Actresses in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Female models from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian dance teachers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Mumbai