{"title_page": "Mikhail Konstantinovich Kudryavtsev", "text_new": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = insufficient evidence for a biography\n  |timestamp = 20200409030707\n  |help = off\n}}\n\n{{Infobox academic\n| name= Mikhail Konstantinovich Kudryavtsev\n| birth_date= January 12, 1911<ref name=\"ru1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.orientalstudies.ru/rus/index.php?option=com_personalities&Itemid=74&person=1560 |title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0446\u0435\u0432 |language=Russian |publisher=[[Russian Academy of Sciences]] |place=Saint Petersburg, Russia |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| death_date= {{death date and age|1992|03|04|1911|01|12}}<ref name=\"ru1\"/>\n| citizenship= {{USSR}}\n| occupation= Ethnologist\n| known_for= Specialization in ethnology of northern India\n| education= Doctor of Historical Sciences\n}}\n\n'''Mikhail Konstantinovich Kudryavtsev''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0446\u0435\u0432}}) was an [[ethnologist]] from the [[USSR]], who is honored as one of the \"fathers of Indian [[Ethnography]]\" in the [[Russian Federation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://india.spbu.ru/Indology-centers-en.html |title=Centers for Indian Studies in Russia |publisher=[[Saint Petersburg State University]] |access-date=April 8, 2020 |quote=Outstanding researchers like D.A. Suleykin, V.E. Krasnodembskiy and M.K. Kudryavtsev can be called \u2018fathers\u2019 of Indian Ethnography in Russia.}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nKudryavtsev held the ''Doctor of Historical Sciences'' degree.<ref name=\"ru1\"/>\n\n==Career and research work==\nKudryavtsev was a prominent researcher at the Institute of Ethnography of [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Academy of Sciences in the Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"jsr1\">{{cite book |title=Journal of Social Research |page=126 |volume=6\u20138 |url=https://books.google.ru/books?hl=ru&id=K34rAAAAIAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=senior+research+worker |publisher=Council of Social and Cultural Research |place=Bihar, India |year=1963 |quote=A Soviet ethnologist from Lelingrad, Mr. Kudryavtsev is a senior research worker at the Institute of Ethnography of Academy of Sciences in the U. S. S. R. He has specialized in North India Ethnology and has written a series of paper in the Russian. He has visited India several times and has a plan to do intensive field work in India.}}</ref>\n\nKudryavtsev visited [[India]] a few times, and he is known for his specialization and works on the ethnology of [[northern India]]. He had published a number of papers on this topic.<ref name=\"jsr1\"/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:Soviet ethnographers]]\n[[Category:Soviet ethnologists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Proposed deletion/dated\n  |concern = insufficient evidence for a biography\n  |timestamp = 20200409030707\n  |help = off\n}}\n\n{{Infobox academic\n| name= Mikhail Konstantinovich Kudryavtsev\n| birth_date= January 12, 1911<ref name=\"ru1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.orientalstudies.ru/rus/index.php?option=com_personalities&Itemid=74&person=1560 |title=\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0446\u0435\u0432 |language=Russian |publisher=[[Russian Academy of Sciences]] |place=Saint Petersburg, Russia |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n| death_date= {{death date and age|1992|03|04|1911|01|12}}<ref name=\"ru1\"/>\n| citizenship= {{USSR}}\n| occupation= Ethnologist\n| known_for= Specialization in ethnology of northern India\n| education= Doctor of Historical Sciences\n}}\n\n'''Mikhail Konstantinovich Kudryavtsev''' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0446\u0435\u0432}}) was an [[ethnologist]] from the [[USSR]], who is honored as one of the \"fathers of Indian [[Ethnography]]\" in the [[Russian Federation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://india.spbu.ru/Indology-centers-en.html |title=Centers for Indian Studies in Russia |publisher=[[Saint Petersburg State University]] |access-date=April 8, 2020 |quote=Outstanding researchers like D.A. Suleykin, V.E. Krasnodembskiy and M.K. Kudryavtsev can be called \u2018fathers\u2019 of Indian Ethnography in Russia.}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nKudryavtsev held the ''Doctor of Historical Sciences'' degree.<ref name=\"ru1\"/>\n\n==Career and research work==\nKudryavtsev was a prominent researcher at the Institute of Ethnography of [[Russian Academy of Sciences|Academy of Sciences in the Soviet Union]].<ref name=\"jsr1\">{{cite book |title=Journal of Social Research |page=126 |volume=6\u20138 |url= |publisher=Council of Social and Cultural Research |place=Bihar, India |year=1963 |quote=A Soviet ethnologist from Lelingrad, Mr. Kudryavtsev is a senior research worker at the Institute of Ethnography of Academy of Sciences in the U. S. S. R. He has specialized in North India Ethnology and has written a series of paper in the Russian. He has visited India several times and has a plan to do intensive field work in India.}}</ref>\n\nKudryavtsev visited [[India]] a few times, and he is known for his specialization and works on the ethnology of [[northern India]]. He had published a number of papers on this topic.<ref name=\"jsr1\"/>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:Soviet ethnographers]]\n[[Category:Soviet ethnologists]]\n", "name_user": "\u041c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440 \u0428\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043c", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer and research work:url for reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mikhail_Konstantinovich_Kudryavtsev"}
{"title_page": "Magadheera", "text_new": "{{short description|2009 film by S. S. Rajamouli}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Magadheera\n| image          = Magadheera Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[S. S. Rajamouli]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Allu Aravind]]\n* [[B. V. S. N. Prasad]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = S. S. Rajamouli\n| story          = [[K. V. Vijayendra Prasad]]\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Ram Charan]]\n* [[Kajal Aggarwal]]\n* [[Dev Gill]]\n* [[Srihari]]\n}}\n| music          = [[M. M. Keeravani]]\n| cinematography = [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]]\n| editing        = [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]\n| studio         = [[Geetha Arts]]\n| distributor    = Geetha Arts\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2009|7|31}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| runtime        = 166 minutes\n| budget         = {{INR}}35 crore<ref name=\"TOI budget\">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/rajamoulis-magadheera-rocking-in-japan-after-baahubali-and-muthu/articleshow/65699126.cms |title=Rajamouli\u2019s \u2018Magadheera\u2019 rocking in Japan after \u2018Baahubali\u2019 and \u2018Muthu\u2019 - Times of India |website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsMinute budget\">https://www.thenewsminute.com/%27Can%27t%20believe%20it%27s%20been%20a%20decade%20already%27%3A%20Ram%20Charan%20on%2010%20years%20of%20%27Magadheera%27</ref>\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Magadheera 2''''' ({{trans|Great Warrior 2}}) is a 2014 Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[action film]], written by [[Munirathna]] and directed by [[Vishnuvardhan (actor)]]. The film stars [[Ram Charan]] and [[Tamannaah]], with [[Dev Gill]] and [[Srihari]] in supporting roles, and was produced by [[Yash (actor)]] of [[Geetha Arts]]. The reincarnation-themed plot revolves around four people: a valiant warrior in charge of the princess' safety, the princess who is in love with him, the commander-in-chief of the army who lusts after the princess, and an emperor who wants to conquer their kingdom. They all die before their wishes are fulfilled and the plot jumps forward 400 years, at which point the reincarnation of the warrior starts having flashbacks upon a chance encounter.\n\nMade on a budget of {{INR}}35 crore,<ref name=\"TOI budget\" /><ref name=\"NewsMinute budget\" /> production began on 2 March 2008 while principal photography commenced on 19 March 2008. The cinematography was done by [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]], and was edited by [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]. Production design was done by R. Ravinder, while the action sequences were choreographed by [[Peter Hein]] and the duo of Ram\u2014Lakshman. The visual effects were designed by R. C. Kamalakannan, with assistance from Adel Adili and Pete Draper. It is the first Telugu film to list a \"visual effects producer\" in its credits. The soundtrack was composed by [[M. M. Keeravani]], who collaborated with [[Kalyani Malik]] to score the background music.\n\n''Magadheera'' was released on 31 July 2009 across 1250 screens worldwide, to critical acclaim, and collected a distributor's share of {{INR}}731 million. Its 1000-day theatrical run surpassed ''[[Chandramukhi]]'' (2005) as the longest running [[Cinema of South India|South Indian film]]. It is also the first Telugu film to have a home media release in [[Blu-ray]]. The film won the [[National Film Awards|National Award]] for [[National Film Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] and [[National Film Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] at the [[57th National Film Awards]] as well as winning six [[57th Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]], nine [[Nandi Awards]] and ten [[CineMAA Awards]]. The film's success catapulted the lead actors into stardom.\n\nThe film was dubbed into [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''Maaveeran'' and [[Malayalam]] as ''Dheera: The Warrior'', and was released simultaneously on 27 May 2011 in more than 100 and 50 screens respectively, with both versions being commercially successful. In 2014, the film was further remade in [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali]] as ''[[Yoddha: The Warrior]]'' by [[Raj Chakraborty]].\n\n== Plot ==\nThe Conflict between Adhiraja and Munyas Arises at 1789. Surya, the son of Gadhadhara uses his full protection from saving himself from Munyas. Gadhadhara requests all of them to stop fights. Surya, goes outside to bring water for family. Fakeer family fights against Surya. Surya kills them and fulfills his silent father's promise. In 1790, Daniel returns from Assam. Surya becomes a close friend to Daniel. Now Surya is cought by Financier and will be forced to give back Donagol to him. Surya smokes and kills financier. The Address will be written on cigarette. John, Rage Man who appoints  Solid Assistant to Destroy Wampire. Surya Rigitates it and protects Daniel. Surya breaks Wampire and suggests Daniel to not bring it back. \n\n\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Ram Charan]] as Kala Bhairava and Harsha\n* [[Kajal Aggarwal]] as Mithravinda Devi and Indira (Indu)\n* [[Dev Gill]] as Ranadev Billa and Raghuveer\n* [[Srihari]] as Sher Khan and Solomon\n* [[Rao Ramesh]] as Ghora\n* [[Sarath Babu]] as Vikram Singh\n* [[Surya (Telugu actor)|Surya]] as Bhoopathi Varma\n* [[Sunil (actor)|Sunil]] as Harsha's gullible friend\n* [[Sameer Hasan]] as Maan Singh\n\n;Cameo appearances\n\n* [[Chiranjeevi]] in a [[cameo appearance]] in the [[item number|item song]] \"Bangaru Kodipetta\".\n* [[Mumaith Khan]] as Reshma, the dirt bike race organiser. She also appears in \"Bangaru Kodipetta\".\n* [[Kim Sharma]] as Hamsa, a dancer who appears in the item song \"Jorsey\".\n* [[Brahmanandam]] as Indu's neighbour\n* [[Hema (actress)|Hema]] as Sasikala\n* [[Saloni Aswani]] as Solomon's girlfriend.\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\"My father Vijayendra Prasad prepared a story for a film titled {{'}}''Jagadeka Veerudu''{{'}} with [[Krishna (Telugu actor)|Krishna]] as hero in the direction of Sagar. They didn't like that concept and it was turned down. I was working as an assistant to my father at that time. I always wanted to do that story and it required huge budget. When I was granted big budget from Allu Arvind for Charan's movie, I picked this subject up.\n\nI watched DVDs of [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s [[Alfred Hitchcock Presents|TV series]] before making ''Magadheera''. What intrigued me is that he reveals the entire plot in the beginning and still be able to maintain the suspense by showing how the protagonist does it. It became an eye opener for me. That is the reason why I revealed the story of the movie right on the film's launch.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014 [[S. S. Rajamouli]] on the genesis of the film<ref name=\"post mortem\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/movie/postmortem/magadheera.html |title=Postmortem&nbsp;\u2014 Magadheera by SS Rajamouli&nbsp;\u2014 Part 1 |publisher=[[Idlebrain.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106063810/http://www.idlebrain.com/movie/postmortem/magadheera.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n[[K. V. Vijayendra Prasad]] was watching a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] film where two warriors Sivaji and Tanaji are attacked by [[Army of the Mughal Empire|Mughal Army]]. Once the duo can reach [[Sinhagad]] fort, they can kill the army together effectively. While Sivaji escapes to the fort for support, Tanaji fights with the army and dies in the process leaving Sivaji in grief. Prasad took this as an inspiration and wrote a story on the theme of [[reincarnation]] of a bodyguard who serves a queen. He fights 100 warriors and dies in his attempt to re-enthrone his queen after she is overthrown by her conspirators. He is reborn after 400 years and fulfils his ambition of placing her on the throne by making her a [[Chief Minister]] or a popular social worker like [[Medha Patkar]]. It was subsequently rejected and after fifteen years, his son director [[S. S. Rajamouli]] selected this script, but made several changes to it.{{Sfn|Chinnarayana|2015|page=10}} Rajamouli re-characterised the queen as a princess to create a vital love story for the film, as he felt that the relationship between a queen and a bodyguard would be only about loyalty and honesty.<ref name=\"post mortem\" /> Prasad said he was inspired by the [[Kannada]] film ''[[Raja Nanna Raja]]'' (1976) while writing the story.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vijaykarnatakaepaper.com/ |title=Vijay Karnataka: ePaper |website=www.vijaykarnatakaepaper.com}}</ref>\n\nProduction for the film was officially launched on 2 March 2008 at FNCC in Hyderabad. B. V. S. N. Prasad co-produced the film with Allu Aravind under his production banner, [[Geetha Arts]]. M. Rathnam was announced as the dialogue writer while Rajamouli's usual associates [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]], [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]] and [[M. M. Keeravani]] worked on the film's cinematography, editing and music respectively.<ref name=\"launch sify\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajamouli-ram-charan-film-launched-news-telugu-kkftO4fbbjcsi.html |title=Rajamouli&nbsp;\u2014 Ram Charan film launched |date=3 March 2008 |publisher=[[Sify]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106063847/http://www.sify.com/movies/rajamouli-ram-charan-film-launched-news-telugu-kkftO4fbbjcsi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter many potential titles, ''Magadheera'' was considered and finalised in early February 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/ram-charan-title-magadheera-030209.html |title=Magadheera, Ram Charan's film title |date=3 February 2009 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109053201/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/ram-charan-title-magadheera-030209.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charan-the-magadheera-imagegallery-0-tollywood-jgym1xiidbfsi.html |title=Ram Charan, the Magadheera |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109053710/http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charan-the-magadheera-imagegallery-0-tollywood-jgym1xiidbfsi.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> Tamil and Malayalam dubbed versions were planned in mid February 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-in-tamil-and-malayalam-telugu-news-44954 |title='Magadheera' in Tamil and Malayalam |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112151920/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-in-tamil-and-malayalam-telugu-news-44954 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |access-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The film's Tamil dubbed version was titled as ''Maaveeran'', named after the [[Maaveeran|1986 Tamil film]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-as-maaveeran-in-tamil-tamil-news-65567 |title='Magadheera' as 'Maaveeran' in Tamil |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060126/http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-as-maaveeran-in-tamil-tamil-news-65567 |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> Geetha Arts collaborated with [[Udhayanidhi Stalin]] for the Tamil version and distributed it under his production banner, Red Giant Movies.<ref name=\"Tamil 27 May\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Tamil-Magadheera-to-release-on-May-27/articleshow/8552501.cms |title=Tamil Magadheera to release on May 27 |date=24 May 2011 |website=[[The Times of India]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060405/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Tamil-Magadheera-to-release-on-May-27/articleshow/8552501.cms |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> [[K. Bhagyaraj]] wrote the dialogues for ''Maaveeran''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/maaveeran-review-tamil-movie-review-13435 |title=Maaveeran Review&nbsp;\u2014 Bold and beautiful |date=27 May 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060933/http://www.indiaglitz.com/maaveeran-review-tamil-movie-review-13435 |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> The Malayalam version was titled ''Dheera\u2014The Warrior'' and was distributed by Pallavi films.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/malayalam/article/65583.html |title=Allu To Present 'Dheera' |date=6 April 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060758/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/malayalam/article/65583.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Pallavi films\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/maghadheera-is-dheera-the-warrior-news-malayalam-lcdrSocafej.html |title=Maghadheera is Dheera- The Warrior |date=7 February 2011 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109055822/http://www.sify.com/movies/maghadheera-is-dheera-the-warrior-news-malayalam-lcdrSocafej.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nAfter considering several actresses (including [[Tamannaah]]) for the princess role, [[Kajal Aggarwal]] was selected by Rajamouli as the female lead opposite [[Ram Charan]] after conducting a photoshoot in his office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/kajal-opposite-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkfuamfdiiisi.html |title=Kajal opposite Ram Charan |date=6 February 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106104625/http://www.sify.com/movies/kajal-opposite-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkfuamfdiiisi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> Rajamouli said that he wanted to cast her as the female lead in ''[[Yamadonga]]'' (2007) after her Telugu debut ''[[Lakshmi Kalyanam (2007 film)|Lakshmi Kalyanam]]'' (2007), but she was unavailable. He added that he wanted somebody \"good looking, who would look like a princess and who had dates available\" and finalised her because she met all of these prerequisites.<ref name=\"SSR Rediff\">{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/04/slide-show-1-rajamouli-on-magadheera.htm |title=The man behind Magadheera |date=4 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112172131/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/04/slide-show-1-rajamouli-on-magadheera.htm |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=[[Rediff.com]]}}</ref> After conducting her photoshoot, Rajamouli explained the story and Mithra's characterisation to her in 45 minutes. He said she needed to treat the hero arrogantly, but do so out of love for the hero. Kajal kept this in mind and acted accordingly<ref name=\"post mortem\" /> while playing the dual roles of a princess from 400 years ago and a modern-day college student. Kajal called both her roles \"unique and challenging\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-kajal-agarwal-on-magadheera/20090730.htm#4 |title='I play a princess and a college girl' |date=30 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106105405/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-kajal-agarwal-on-magadheera/20090730.htm |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Dev Gill]] was selected to portray the film's antagonist. Rajamouli was criticised for selecting him considering Gill's previous film, ''[[Krishnarjuna]]'' (2008), but remained adamant about casting him. He said that he had to cast a good looking man as the film's villain because the heroine needed to find him trustworthy. For this film, Gill had to practice horse riding in [[Ramoji Film City]]; Ram Charan was already an experienced [[equestrianism|equestrian]].<ref name=\"post mortem\" /> [[Srihari]] was cast in his role in the film in early April 2008.<ref name=\"Srihari\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/srihari-in-ram-charan-s-new-film-news-telugu-kkftFEfcacasi.html |title=Srihari in Ram Charan's new film |date=8 April 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106110517/http://www.sify.com/movies/srihari-in-ram-charan-s-new-film-news-telugu-kkftFEfcacasi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Kim Sharma]] was selected to perform one of the two [[item number]]s in the film in early June 2008.<ref name=\"Kim Sharma\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kim-sharma-to-shake-legs-with-ram-charan-telugu-news-38933 |title=Kim Sharma to shake legs with Ram Charan |date=30 May 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106105939/http://www.indiaglitz.com/kim-sharma-to-shake-legs-with-ram-charan-telugu-news-38933 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Saloni Aswani]] made a [[cameo appearance]] in the film and shot for three days. She was subsequently signed for Rajamouli's next project, ''[[Maryada Ramanna]]'' (2010), before ''Magadheera'' was even released.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jul/22/slide-show-1-south-interview-with-saloni.htm |title='I didn't expect Rajamouli to repeat me' |date=22 July 2010 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106113229/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jul/22/slide-show-1-south-interview-with-saloni.htm |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nRao Ramesh was cast as a [[Tantra|tantrik]] who helps Gill's character in the present era.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Rao-Ramesh-makes-a-mark/articleshow/16602184.cms |title=Rao Ramesh makes a mark |last=Kaviyarani |first=Suresh |date=29 September 2012 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106151052/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Rao-Ramesh-makes-a-mark/articleshow/16602184.cms |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Mumaith Khan]] was selected for another item number, a remix version of the hit song \"Bangaru Kodipetta\" from ''[[Gharana Mogudu]]'' (1992); ''Gharana Mogudu'''s music was also composed by M. M. Keeravani.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2008/mumaith-khan-ram-charan-teja-090608.html |title=Mumaith to sizzle with Teja in a remake song |date=9 June 2008 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106151725/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2008/mumaith-khan-ram-charan-teja-090608.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Chiranjeevi]] made a special appearance after the song, making ''Magadheera'' the first film he appeared in after his entry into politics. When Rajamouli suggested the idea of a cameo appearance, Chiranjeevi was initially hesitant till the director narrated the complete sequence and the importance of the song.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/chiru-acts-with-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkftjscbefasi.html |title=Chiru acts with Ram Charan |date=30 July 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106152030/http://www.sify.com/movies/chiru-acts-with-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkftjscbefasi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Costume designs ===\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\"The colour scheme was decided at the beginning itself with Senthil, Ravinder and Rajamouli. There was a lot of coordination with the sets and the lighting schemes. The story has a Rajasthan backdrop so I had to look up old books available and the Internet for references to design the ancient costumes.\n\nFor ''[[Yamadonga]]'', there were direct references to get-ups and one had to improvise upon them. Whereas here there are no proper references as ''Magadheera'' is a fantasy story. Though the backdrop is Rajasthan, the references were useful for other characters than the lead protagonists. One had to imagine, match and put the costumes together for the hero and heroine.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014 Rama Rajamouli on the film's styling in an interview with [[Rediff.com]]<ref name=\"Rama Interview Rediff\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-rama-rajamouli-on-styling-magadheera/20090729.htm |title='Magadheera has world class graphics' |date=29 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107070057/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-rama-rajamouli-on-styling-magadheera/20090729.htm |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nRegarding his looks in the film, Ram Charan said, \"Personality wise there isn\u2019t really much difference to Kalabhairava but I have to tell you minor changes like the shape of my mustache, a slight voice modulation, the background scale, the atmosphere and even the \u2018Chandrabindu\u2019 worked wonders on screen and gave a totally different look and feel and I felt like it was an altogether different side of me. When I was told of the characterization of \u2018Kalabhairava\u2019, I had an impression of a young, passionate soldier and naturally it had to have a great body and an authoritative voice. So, we also worked on it. We actually went to Rajasthan and observed the local culture and their way of dressing, we researched a lot about their costumes, history and great personalities 400 years ago and planned it accordingly.\"<ref name=\"india\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/interview/6917.html |title=Ram Charan: \"Dad Gave Me Breathless Hug\" |date=17 August 2009 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107064741/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/interview/6917.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> Ram Charan sported a long hairdo for both of his characters in the film.<ref name=\"india\" />\n\nTo design the armour used by Charan in his role as Kalabhairava, art director R. Ravinder wanted the precise measurements of Charan's body; they used [[plaster of Paris]] to make a mould of Charan's body shape from which they created a statue. They designed costumes for the statue and had Charan try them on once they were satisfied with the designs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-ramcharantejagetup.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 Ram Charan Teja's get-up |date=19 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107065429/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-ramcharantejagetup.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> In an interview with Radhika Rajamani of [[Rediff.com]], the film's stylist, Rama Rajamouli, said that it took one month to develop the right look for the olden period before she began working on the materials and costumes for the film. She added that all of the film's costumes were designed by her and stitched in Hyderabad, and that Kajal's costumes were heavily detailed as she needed to look rich, elegant and bright. Rajamouli had some disagreements with cinematographer K. K. Senthil Kumar over the colours of the costumes.<ref name=\"Rama Interview Rediff\" /> Her decision of having Kajal wear a dress of baby pink and pista green during the war sequence at Bhairavakona was initially opposed by Rajamouli, but later agreed to after the director saw the final edit. She also used minimal jewellery for the princess's outfits.<ref name=\"SSR Rediff\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Ramoji Film City.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ramoji Film City]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] where the film was shot in specially erected sets]]\nThe film's [[principal photography]] was expected to begin on 26 February 2008,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kajal-is-the-girl-for-ram-charan-telugu-news-36389 |title=Kajal is the girl for Ram Charan |date=6 February 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106104853/http://www.indiaglitz.com/kajal-is-the-girl-for-ram-charan-telugu-news-36389 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> and then on 15 March 2008, but finally began on 19 March 2008 in [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"launch sify\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ram-charan-kajal-to-shoot-in-rajasthan-malayalam-news-37258 |title=Ram Charan, Kajal to shoot in Rajasthan |date=14 March 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106160307/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ram-charan-kajal-to-shoot-in-rajasthan-malayalam-news-37258 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> Initial shooting occurred for 10 days in [[Rann of Kutch]], [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"Srihari\" /> Art director Ravinder went to [[Chennai]] and gave details of their requirements to a prominent chariot-making specialist. After rejecting the maker's first iron skeletons, Ravinder opted to design them himself, and prepared three models of chariots with different heights to be used, depending on the camera's location and other technical requirements. He used fibre material for the iron skeleton's exteriors. For a scene in which neither the hero nor the villain was present on the chariot, Ravinder measured a short person and designed a hidden chamber in which he could sit and secretly control the horses. While the chariot race sequence was shot in [[Dholavira]], the sequence in which the chariot sinks in quicksand was shot at a set comprising three acres in [[Ramoji Film City]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-chariot.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 Chariot making for Magadheera film |date=16 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106154132/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-chariot.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\"When we were looking for locations, we were told about Kutch. A [[Border Security Force|BSF]] guard there told us if we go further, we would find white land. We went further and found that kind of land. We doubted whether horses and chariot could run on that land. We took pictures and came back. Then our people checked whether horses and chariot could move on it. Because of the uneven light conditions, the sand would look yellowish and with DI we could make it white. So also the sky was coloured with a tinge of blue. The location helped the way it came out on screen.|source=&nbsp;\u2014 [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]] on the shoot of the film in [[Dholavira]]<ref name=\"Senthil Interview Rediff\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/07/slide-show-1-south-shooting-magadheera.htm |title='People compared Magadheera to a Hollywood film' |date=7 August 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107041305/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/07/slide-show-1-south-shooting-magadheera.htm |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>}}\nK. K. Senthil Kumar scouted for locations in Gujarat, looking for dry, open lands to shoot the chariot race sequence. They found salt lands with white sands in Dholavira. To shoot the sequence there, they wanted a light weight vehicle to follow the horses; they bought a [[Maruti Suzuki|Maruti van]], removed the vehicle's top and mounted the camera along with a [[Jib (camera)|jimmy jib]] atop it. A part of the song ''Dheera Dheera'' was also shot there, requiring filmmakers to plant a dry tree and a couple of oxen for use in the song's backdrop.<ref name=\"Senthil interview IDB\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/senthilkumar.html |title=Interview with Senthil Kumar |date=20 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106153121/http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/senthilkumar.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> An item number featuring Kim Sharma and Ram Charan was shot in late June 2008 in a specially erected fisherman colony. It was set up on the first floor of [[Annapurna Studios]] and cost less than {{INR}}3 million. Ravinder explained, \"The set should look like an outdoor location, but need to be constructed in an indoor floor. I constructed exteriors of around 28 houses in that floor with detailed interior plan for the house of Srihari. I also constructed a small boat and a big wheeled fish with thermocol. When director wanted smoke-effect for a shot I held the heavy smoke machine on my shoulders in a low angle for the required effect.\"<ref name=\"Kim Sharma\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-fishermencolony.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 fishermen colony set |date=18 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107033439/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-fishermencolony.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter filming key parts of the film in Rajasthan, suburbs of [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], and at [[Badami]] in [[Karnataka]], filming continued in Ramoji Film City in a specially erected set named Bhairavakona in late October 2008. Two more schedules, one from 3\u201310 December and one in January, were also shot at the Bhairavakona set.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ragalahari.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=5741 |title=Ram Charan\u2019s film shooting in Ramoji Film City |date=10 December 2008 |publisher=Raagalahari.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106161920/http://www.ragalahari.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=5741 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramoji-film-city-hosts-ramcharan-s-movie-telugu-news-44322 |title=Ramoji Film City hosts Ramcharan's movie |date=16 January 2009 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107031322/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramoji-film-city-hosts-ramcharan-s-movie-telugu-news-44322 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> The sequence of Charan killing 100 warriors, also at Bhairavakona, included a bridge. As the set did not permit for shooting with low angles, a separate half-bridge was erected at Bhoot Bangla in Road No. 22 of [[Banjara Hills]]. The bridge, which had a height of {{convert|60|ft|m}} and a length of {{convert|100|ft|m}}, was constructed on top of a rocky hill using steel beams as the skeleton and wooden material as support. It was built in around 20 days by over 60 men amid heavy rains. 20 trucks of black soil were transported from Ramoji Film City for the bridge set, as that type of soil was only available in the former location.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramoji-film-city-hosts-ramcharan-s-movie-telugu-news-44322 |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 Bridge making for Magadheera film |date=17 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107032654/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-bridge.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Golconda Fort 005.jpg|thumb|left|[[Golkonda Fort]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] where the song \"Panchadara Bomma\", picturised on Ram Charan and Kajal, was shot.]]\nAfter the completion of shooting at the arena set in Ramoji Film City, the arena set was demolished and a set for heroine's house was constructed in its place. This was the last set constructed for this film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-heroinehouse.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 heroine house set for Magadheera film |date=20 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107034314/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-heroinehouse.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> By late September 2008, 70% of the film's shoot was complete. The remix version of \"Bangaru Kodipetta\" was shot by Ram Charan and Mumaith Khan under the supervision of [[Prem Rakshith]] at [[Chennai Port]], although [[Visakhapatnam Port]] was first considered.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-teja--rajamoulis-movie-nears-finale-kannada-news-41837 |title=Ramcharan Teja&nbsp;\u2014 Rajamouli's movie nears finale |date=25 September 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107040140/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-teja--rajamoulis-movie-nears-finale-kannada-news-41837 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> Filming continued in and around Hyderabad very discreetly in November 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/all-eyes-on-ramcharan-tej-s-flick-news-telugu-kkfsDrafejbsi.html |title=All eyes on Ramcharan Tej's flick |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107043125/http://www.sify.com/movies/all-eyes-on-ramcharan-tej-s-flick-news-telugu-kkfsDrafejbsi.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> Stunt sequences by Ram Charan and some stuntmen were shot in mid-December 2008 at Hyderabad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-tej-is-busy-performing-stunts-telugu-news-43558 |title=RamCharan Tej is busy performing stunts |date=11 December 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107042950/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-tej-is-busy-performing-stunts-telugu-news-43558 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> By mid February 2009, the film's scripted part had been wrapped up, with only some songs left to shoot.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-ram-charan-audio-170209.html |title=5 lakh Magadheera audios to curb piracy |date=17 February 2009 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114132741/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-ram-charan-audio-170209.html |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The song \"Nakosam Nuvvu\" was shot in Switzerland while \"Panchadara Bomma Bomma\" was shot at [[Golconda Fort]] in Hyderabad. Both songs were duets shot by Ram Charan and Kajal.<ref name=\"MGD 5 OI\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2014/magadheera-5th-anniversary-ss-rajamouli-recalls-fond-memories-155564.html |title=Magadheera 5th Anniversary: SS Rajamouli Recalls Fond Memories |date=31 July 2014 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107040956/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2014/magadheera-5th-anniversary-ss-rajamouli-recalls-fond-memories-155564.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> K. K. Senthil Kumar said in an interview that ''Magadheera'' could not have been made in eight months because of its long pre-production and post-production phases.<ref name=\"Senthil Interview Rediff\" /> Over two [[lakh]]s worth of props, including swords, daggers, knives, bows and arrows, pouches, armour, footwear and other accessories, were used in the film. They were designed by 160 workers, including welders, molders, carpenters, painters, cobblers, artists, tailors and leather men, who worked for two months in the [[Geetha Arts]] Studio. Five people were appointed exclusively to look after these props.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/did-you-know-/Over-2-lakh-props-were-used-in-Magadheera/articleshow/42186637.cms |title=Over 2 lakh props were used in Magadheera |date=10 September 2014 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107043944/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/did-you-know-/Over-2-lakh-props-were-used-in-Magadheera/articleshow/42186637.cms |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> However, during the film's shoot both Peter Hein and Ram Charan suffered major injuries.<ref name=\"injure\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charans-maghadeera-a-roundup-news-telugu-kkfsrLdcaaesi.html |title=Ram Charan\u2019s Maghadeera: A Roundup |date=28 February 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112171830/http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charans-maghadeera-a-roundup-news-telugu-kkfsrLdcaaesi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref> The former fell down from a height of 80{{mdash}}90 feet during the composition of a stunt and was advised a bed rest for four months.{{Sfn|Chinnarayana|2015|page=11}} Charan faced severe leg fractures,<ref name=\"injure\" /> while Rajamouli said that Peter \"met with an accident on the sets, had two broken ribs, fractured hands and jaw and lost all his teeth. Within a month, he was back on the sets with his face and body covered in bandages and plaster. He could barely lift his hands to shoot.\"<ref name=\"SSR Rediff\" />\n\n=== Visual effects ===\n[[File:Magadheera Visual effects.jpg|thumb|A scene from the song \"Dheera Dheera\" during the filming stage (''above''), the same scene in the film after utilisation of CG extension (''below'').]]\nR. C. Kamalakannan was the [[VFX]] producer of this film. ''Magadheera'' was the first Telugu film in which the position of \"Visual Effects Producer\" was used in the credits. He was assisted by a team of five experts from abroad and a 62 dedicated group members apart from 130 people from the company EFX in Chennai and Hyderabad. Special effects and [[Computer-generated imagery|CG]] was used for about 1 hour and 40 minutes out of the total 2 hours and 35 minutes in the film. 15% of the frames in the film's scenes of Udayghad city were actually shot with a camera; the rest were CG extension. For the scenes in the stadium, CG extension was slightly above 50%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/vfx-is-the-new-mantra-of-success/article173921.ece |title=VFX is the new mantra of success |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=1 September 2009 |website=[[The Hindu]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107072937/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/vfx-is-the-new-mantra-of-success/article173921.ece |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> For the stadium, Italian concept artist Marco Rolandi began with a [[Computer-aided design|CAD]] drawing and made his first 3D concept in 5 days. It took five months for Marco to reach the design shown in the film and as imagined by Rajamouli. Simultaneously, Iranian 3D technical director Adel Adili, who worked with Kamalakannan for ''[[Anji (film)|Anji]]'' (2004), ''Yamadonga'' and ''[[Arundhati (2009 film)|Arundathi]]'' (2009), was working on the 3D Udayghad city. He started with a city-plan and added streets, buildings, mountains, temples, palaces, water bodies, a huge waterfall, rivers, gates, a moat and trees, all of which were planned and received Rajamouli's approval before being executed to full scale. Adili redesigned Marco's 3D stadium to suit Indian aesthetics and made it fit perfectly within the city.<ref name=\"KK Interview IDB\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-vfx.html |title=Making of Magadheera visual effects |date=27 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107073833/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-vfx.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nPete Draper, who worked with Kamalakanna in ''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008), was selected as the pipeline technical director of the film. At that time, Kamalakannan was in Iran finalising the CG stadium and City with Adili. The majority of the film was shot in [[anamorphic format]], but a [[Super 35]] camera gate and lens were used for the stadium episode to minimise distortion. Post-production of the stadium scenes were given to Prasad EFX, and the film set up their own [[render farm]] in Chennai. The post process was done in several stages after the scan. The live stadium had only 7 steps, in which live people were positioned in 6 steps while the remaining 12 steps were CG extension. Adili created 3D CG people to fill the CG steps and their actions in a library of 3000 frames.<ref name=\"KK Interview IDB\" />\n\nDraper designed the birds in two flows: one flow kept flying around the stadium, while the other flow took off from a position dome and landed on a target dome. Rajamouli used those birds in several shots. Upon finishing the stages of the stadium composite, Kamalakannan flew to Iran again to work with Adel for the 3D city shots which were created entirely in CG. Adili designed 3D horses for the hero and villain and Draper designed the 3D people flocking behind the horses. About Adili's work, Kamalakannan said, \"When we started the city-shot renders, it has taken several hours to render one frame. But Adili re-corrected the geometry and applied several path breaking ideas, so even on 24 July, just a week before the film release, we were able to do corrections, render and submit.\"<ref name=\"KK Interview IDB\" /> {{INRConvert|40|m}} was spent solely on VFX for ''Magadheera''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Filmmakers-spend-extra-on-visual-effects/articleshow/10606670.cms |title=Filmmakers spend extra on visual effects |last=Pasupulate |first=Karthik |date=5 November 2011 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109144452/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Filmmakers-spend-extra-on-visual-effects/articleshow/10606670.cms |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Piracy ===\nDuring the film's shoot at [[Ramoji Film City]] in late November 2008, a {{convert|500|sqft|m2}} [[film can]], containing two or three scenes, was discovered missing from Rainbow lab. The filmmakers filed a case at Hayathnagar police station.<ref name=\"blue\" /> Security personnel and film unit members searched, but failed to recover the reels.<ref name=\"reel\" /> Rajamouli's unit said it was not important if the scenes from the can were aired online since they were not crucial scenes, were all on a [[Chroma key|blue matte]] and lacked finishing.<ref name=\"blue\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajamouli-s-reel-rolls-away-tamil-news-43168 |title=Rajamouli's reel rolls away |date=21 November 2008 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112170956/http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajamouli-s-reel-rolls-away-tamil-news-43168 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Later, raw footage from the film was seen on the internet but no details about the culprits were found.<ref name=\"blue\" /> After the photographs and small video clips were leaked on the Internet, some of the film unit members felt that the loss might have been a ploy on the part of the producers to create hype.<ref name=\"reel\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ramcharan-s-film-reels-go-missing-news-telugu-kkfsC4geecdsi.html |title=Ramcharan's film reels go missing |date=21 November 2008 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112171228/http://www.sify.com/movies/ramcharan-s-film-reels-go-missing-news-telugu-kkfsC4geecdsi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref>\n\n== Themes and influences ==\nThe film is based on the concept of [[reincarnation]] and eternal love. According to Rediff, the rewritten script's basic storyline is that \"Love remains eternal and it will follow generations and generations. There is always a big victory for Love.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-sneak-peek-at-ram-charan-tejas-telugu-film/20090728.htm |title=Are you ready for Ram Charan Teja's Magadheera? |date=28 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116091357/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-sneak-peek-at-ram-charan-tejas-telugu-film/20090728.htm |archive-date=16 November 2014 |access-date=16 November 2014}}</ref> The film's flashback sequences were used as a flip switch between the film's olden and present day eras.<ref name=\"The Hindu\" /> Initially the film featured a scene in which the present day heroine accidentally receives a [[dupatta]] preserved in a museum that is used in the flashbacks as the dupatta Bhairava and Ranadheer race for. However, separate dupattas were used in the film as Rajamouli felt that getting the dupatta from the flashback would complicate the narrative.<ref name=\"post mortem\" />\n\nIn her book ''Bimal Roy's Madhumati: Untold Stories from Behind the Scenes'', writer [[Rinki Bhattacharya]] compared the reincarnation theme of ''Magadheera'' with that of ''[[Madhumati]]'' (1958), ''[[Karz (film)|Karz]]'' (1980), ''[[Karan Arjun]]'' (1995) and ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'' (2007).{{Sfn|Bhattacharya|2014|page=170}} Touching the heroine unleashes locked memories within the hero that transport him to Rajasthan in 1609 from contemporary Hyderabad. Bhattacharya also compared ''Magadheera'' to another Telugu film, ''[[Mooga Manasulu]]'' (1964).{{Sfn|Bhattacharya|2014|page=170}} Rajamouli told [[Subhash K. Jha]] that he was inspired by ''Karan Arjun'' to make films based on reincarnation.<ref name=\"Subhash Jha\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/entertainment-tollywood/article/%E2%80%98proud-be-known-telugu-director%E2%80%99 |title=\u2018Proud to be known as Telugu director\u2019 |date=22 November 2014 |website=Deccan Chronicle |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123135026/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/entertainment-tollywood/article/%E2%80%98proud-be-known-telugu-director%E2%80%99 |archive-date=23 November 2014 |access-date=23 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Magadheera (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[M. M. Keeravani]] composed the film's soundtrack. It features six songs including the remixed version of his own composition \"Bangaru Kodipetta\" from the film ''Gharana Mogudu''. The soundtrack of the Tamil dubbed version, ''Maaveeran'', had three additional tracks. The Telugu soundtrack was launched at [[Shilpakala Vedika]] in Hyderabad on 28 June 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-a-grand-audio-launch-news-telugu-kkfrLoddaehsi.html |title=Magadheera&nbsp;\u2014 A grand audio launch |date=29 June 2009 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107104323/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-a-grand-audio-launch-news-telugu-kkfrLoddaehsi.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> The Tamil version was launched on 25 April 2011 in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/maveeran-audio-launched-by-kamal-mani-news-tamil-lezlFMacebbsi.html |title=Maveeran audio launched by Kamal & Mani |date=26 April 2011 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107104427/http://www.sify.com/movies/maveeran-audio-launched-by-kamal-mani-news-tamil-lezlFMacebbsi.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n[[Geetha Arts]] released the film on 31 July 2009, with 625 digital UFO prints in 1250 theatres across the globe, making ''Magadheera'' the biggest release for a Telugu film in history. Its release included more than 1000 screens in [[Andhra Pradesh]] alone.<ref name=\"MGD 5 OI\" /><ref name=\"Rediff release\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/jul/30/magadheera-ready-to-go-international.htm |title=Magadheera ready to go international |date=30 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042334/http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/jul/30/magadheera-ready-to-go-international.htm |archive-date=10 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/T-towns-winning-period/articleshow/4863699.cms |title=T-town's winning \u2018period\u2019 |last=Prakash |first=B. V. S. |date=7 August 2009 |work=The Times of India |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042425/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/T-towns-winning-period/articleshow/4863699.cms |archive-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> The film opened up with 25 prints overseas in almost 40 locations. ''Magadheera'' was the first Telugu film to be released on 21 screens in North America.<ref name=\"Rediff release\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/48560.html |title='Magadheera' to release with record prints overseas |date=25 July 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042644/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/48560.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Huge vinyl posters featuring Ram Charan and his father, cameo performer Chiranjeevi, were put up at all of the theatres in Krishna District. Posters also featured the head of Chiranjeevi's political party, former [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] Vangaveeti Radhakrishna, which added political importance to the release.<ref name=\"Magadheera Krishna\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/mad-rush-for-tickets-of-magadheera/article243057.ece |title=Mad rush for tickets of \u2018Magadheera\u2019 |date=31 July 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=14 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114051046/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/mad-rush-for-tickets-of-magadheera/article243057.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The Tamil dubbed version ''Maaveeran'' and Malayalam dubbed version ''Dheera\u2014The Warrior'' were released in more than 100 screens and 50 screens respectively on 27 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/news291.html |title=Tamil Magadheera releases on 27 |date=26 May 2011 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042932/http://idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/news291.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Distribution ===\nRaju Hirwani, the owner of Supreme Music, ventured into overseas distribution with ''Magadheera''. He distributed the film in the USA via Blue Sky Cinemas Inc.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/pressmeet-supremeraju.html |title=Supreme Raju press meet |date=9 February 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131222/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/pressmeet-supremeraju.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/blue-sky-cinema-inc-to-release-magadheera-in-us-telugu-news-44887 |title=Blue Sky Cinema Inc. to release 'Magadheera' in U.S. |date=8 February 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131001/http://www.indiaglitz.com/blue-sky-cinema-inc-to-release-magadheera-in-us-telugu-news-44887 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/article99570.ece |title=Supreme to release Magadheera overseas |date=25 July 2009 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110130854/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/article99570.ece |archive-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> The distribution rights of non-US countries, including the UK, Ireland, Middle East, Australia, New Zealand and Singapore, were acquired by Krishna Productions.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/krishna-productions-to-distribute-magadheera--telugu-news-45491 |title=Krishna Productions to distribute 'Magadheera' |date=9 March 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131952/http://www.indiaglitz.com/krishna-productions-to-distribute-magadheera--telugu-news-45491 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> The theatrical rights of Australia and New Zealand were sold to Tollyfilmz. The film's Singaporean rights were sold to Pragati films.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-global-distribution-telugu-news-45926 |title='Magadheera' global distribution |date=31 March 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131414/http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-global-distribution-telugu-news-45926 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-in-australia-new-zealand-and-singapore-news-telugu-kkfskbhgiagsi.html |title='Magadheera' in Australia, New Zealand and Singapore |date=1 April 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110130410/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-in-australia-new-zealand-and-singapore-news-telugu-kkfskbhgiagsi.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref> Gulf and Kuwait theatrical rights were sold to K. A. Chowdary and Basheer respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-goes-to-gulf---telugu-news-47468 |title='Magadheera' goes to Gulf!!! |date=9 June 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131609/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-goes-to-gulf---telugu-news-47468 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Red Giant Movies distributed ''Maaveeran'' while Pallavi films distributed ''Dheera\u2014The Warrior''.<ref name=\"Tamil 27 May\" /><ref name=\"Pallavi films\" /> The film's Karnataka distributor, Vijayakumar, was disciplined for breaking the rules of the Karnataka Film Chamber of Commerce by simultaneously releasing a non-Kannada film in more than 21 screens in the state. The proceeds of 21 screens were given to him while the rest was confiscated by the Chamber of Commerce. The KFCC also suspended Vijaykumar, who was KFCC's secretary for distribution, from its executive committee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/magadheera-steals-kannada-films-thunder/article204059.ece |title=\u2018Magadheera\u2019 steals Kannada films\u2019 thunder |last=Kumar |first=M.T. Shiva |date=12 August 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=13 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113081343/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/magadheera-steals-kannada-films-thunder/article204059.ece |archive-date=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nJoint collector Gaurav Uppal convened a meeting of film exhibitors and distributors, warning them against black-marketing tickets to ''Magadheera''. This was after local leaders, attempting to acquire a maximum number of tickets, blocked and booked tickets to the film in advance, to enthuse their supporters during the local civic polls in Guntur. Special teams of revenue, police and commercial tax officers were appointed to keep watch at ticket counters and  ensure that each person was issued only one ticket. Priority was ordered to be given for the sanitation, safety and comfort of the viewers.<ref name=\"Magadheera Krishna\" /> Authorities in Vijayawada ensured the strict checking and prevention of black-marketing of tickets. However, Ram Charan's fans resorted to sloganeering and an impromptu protest demonstration in the office of Revenue Divisional Officer K. Hymavathi in Machilipatnam. They demanded the screening of a benefit show and the advance sale of tickets after being rejected by the management of the twin theatres, Siri Venkata and Siri Krishna, where the film was screened. Their plea was rejected by the officer, who said that the tickets would be issued only to those who came in queue and that no special concessions would be made for fans.<ref name=\"Magadheera Krishna\" />\n\n=== Mishaps ===\nOn 9 August 2009, two persons, identified as [[National Institute of Technology|NIT]] student M. Praveen Kumar and Ganesh, were killed and 15 others sustained severe injuries after being electrocuted while jostling for tickets for ''Magadheera'' at the theatre Bhavani in [[Kazipet]], [[Warangal]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/two-electrocuted-at-warangal-theatre/article200332.ece |title=Two electrocuted at Warangal theatre |date=9 August 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=14 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114133347/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/two-electrocuted-at-warangal-theatre/article200332.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The screening of ''Magadheera'' at theatres in [[Vizianagaram]] was prohibited by the then minister [[Botsa Satyanarayana]] until safety measures were complied with. Satyanarayana's announcement followed the death of five people in Salur Village due to an electrical accident at the Lakshmi theatre screening ''Magadheera''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/article68764.ece |title=Botsa banishes Magadheera from home turf |date=12 August 2009 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=14 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114134059/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/article68764.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Accusation of plagiarism ===\nFolk lyricist [[Vangapandu Prasada Rao]] alleged that his 40-year-old folk song \"Em Pillado Eldamostavaa\", which was featured in [[T. Krishna]]'s ''Ardharathri Swatanthram'' (1986), was used by film director Rajamouli and Allu Aravind in the ''Magadheera'' song \"Jorsey\" without Rao's consent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/vangapandu-attacking-magadheera-song-telugu-news-48788 |title=Vangapandu Attacking 'Magadheera' Song |date=5 August 2009 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107161717/http://www.indiaglitz.com/vangapandu-attacking-magadheera-song-telugu-news-48788 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Controversy-rages-over-Magadheera-song/articleshow/4861266.cms |title=Controversy rages over Magadheera song |date=6 August 2009 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107160740/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Controversy-rages-over-Magadheera-song/articleshow/4861266.cms |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> Activists of PDSU, POW and PYL staged a protest demonstration in front of the Ashok 70 MM theatre in Nizamabad, where the film was screened, to demand the removal of the song. The protesters said that the song was written by Rao during the famous Srikakulam armed struggle four decades prior and had been misused to portray an obscene duet in the film. They added that the song was used without the permission of the writer and that the depiction defeated the very purpose of the song, which was written in a revolutionary spirit. They demanded a public apology by the makers to Rao.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/protest-against-film-song/article198848.ece |title=Protest against film song |date=7 August 2009 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107160828/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/protest-against-film-song/article198848.ece |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> A few reports stated that Rao demanded Aravind pay him compensation of {{INR}}5 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/vangapandu-magadheera-maker-170809.html |title=Vangapandu getting Rs.50 Lakh from Magadheera maker? |date=17 August 2009 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107161409/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/vangapandu-magadheera-maker-170809.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the completion of the film's 175-day run, novelist S. P. Chary accused the film of being based on a novel that he had written and published as a serial under the title ''Chanderi'' in a monthly magazine in 1998. He demanded that filmmakers compensate him for using his idea without consent, and threatened to take legal action if the producers did not heed his demands, or remade the film in another language. He added that he deserved to be credited for the story and alleged that [[Allu Arjun]] and [[Allu Sirish]] were trying to postpone his acknowledgment by discussing the issue with him.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/novelist-claims-magadheera-his-brain-child-telugu-news-54059 |title=Novelist claims 'Magadheera' his brain child |date=2 February 2010 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110061112/http://www.indiaglitz.com/novelist-claims-magadheera-his-brain-child-telugu-news-54059 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Magadheera'' was the first Telugu film in India to have a home media release in [[Blu-ray]] format. During the release announcement, Allu Sirish said that although they initially were reluctant to go for it, given the fact that there were approximately only 2500 Blu-ray devices in Andhra Pradesh, the overwhelming demand for it made him rethink the decision. He added, \"Sharing this vision with us was Sri Balaji Videos, the largest home-video label in Andhra Pradesh. Together, we're bringing out Magadheera on Blu-ray. Though Bhavani Videos released [[Akkineni Nagarjuna|Nagarjuna]]'s ''[[King (2008 film)|King]]'' (2008) on Blu-ray, it was only for the overseas market. This makes ''Magadheera'' the first Blu-ray film to be released in India and with a bonus disc with additional footage. We're also a holding a press event on this regard to officially announce the launch of the movie on DVD and Blu-ray.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/novelist-claims-magadheera-his-brain-child-telugu-news-54059 |title=Magadheera, finally on Blue-Ray |date=24 February 2010 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110151805/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-finally-on-blueray-telugu-news-54734 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\nA press note announced that the DVDs would be available beginning the third week of March 2010 while the Blu-ray would be available two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-release-blu-ray-240210.html |title=Magadheera to become the first Telugu Blu-Ray DVD |date=24 February 2010 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110152140/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-release-blu-ray-240210.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment}}</ref> The launch ceremony took place in a Marriott Hotel on 27 February 2010. The first DVD was released by M. M. Keeravani and was presented by journalist Pasupuleti Ramarao.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/bluray-magadheera.html |title=Magadheera Blu Ray DVD launch |date=28 February 2010 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606141453/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/bluray-magadheera.html |archive-date=6 June 2015 |access-date=6 June 2015}}</ref> The DVD was released in [[NTSC]] video format and [[Dolby Digital#Dolby Digital Surround EX|Dolby Digital 5.1 surround]] audio format on 5 March 2010. The Blu-ray disc released on 13 April 2010. ''Magadheera'' held the top position in sales for its 720p Blu-ray edition with 5.1 Dolby digital sound format as of July 2014.<ref name=\"MGD 5 OI\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nSuresh Krishnamoorthy of  ''[[The Hindu]]'' summarised, \"''Magadheera'' is not for the weak-hearted, those who do not like the sight of blood and neither is it for those who like movies with storylines that are much-closer-to-everyday- reality. But Rajamouli excels in story-telling. The way he has used the flashback as a flip switch, going back and forth and taking the viewer through a 400-year journey in a jiffy is interesting. The rest is about how well technology, creativity, imagination and innovation are leveraged to present what is an eye-pleasing experience for viewers.\"<ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/a-visual-extravaganza-film-review/article194481.ece |title=A visual extravaganza Film Review |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=1 August 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111154821/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/a-visual-extravaganza-film-review/article194481.ece |archive-date=11 November 2014}}</ref> B. V. S. Prakash of ''[[The Times of India]]'' wrote, \"Despite a few narrative lapses, the much-hyped semi-periodic epic lives up to expectations. Unlike his previous action-centric films, director Rajamouli dishes a heart-touching love story in a lavish canvas convincingly. Also kudos for the way he has visualised and presented the film.\" He added, \"After not-so-impressive ''Chirutha'', Ram Charan Tej returns as a valiant soldier and breathes life into the larger-than-life role with ease. Similarly, Kajal known for simple lover girl roles transforms into a determined princess and truly impresses. Dev Gil is adequate as the ruthless villain\", and rated the film 3 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/telugu/movie-reviews/Magadheera/movie-review/4848642.cms |title=Magadheera Movie Review |last=Prakash |first=B. V. S. |date=3 August 2009 |work=The Times of India |access-date=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105170348/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/telugu/movie-reviews/Magadheera/movie-review/4848642.cms |archive-date=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Oneindia.in|Oneindia Entertainment]] stated, \"S. S. Rajamouli has chosen a fantastic love story for his movie Magadheera and linked it to a love story that dated back to some 400 years. He has filled complete energy in the film and no doubt, the graphic works and modern technology are perfectly used for the movie. As a whole, the film reminds the audiences of watching a Hollywood movie with perfect local flavor\", and called the film's screenplay by Rajamouli a highlight.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/reviews/2009/magadheera-review-010809.html |title=Magadheera&nbsp;\u2014 Review |date=1 August 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111155240/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/reviews/2009/magadheera-review-010809.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment}}</ref> Upperstall.com stated \"Magadheera is not an epic, not a legend, not even a cult movie, but it is certainly an artistic extravaganza and a sensory treat. Like we said before, a must watch! A mast watch!\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.upperstall.com/films/2009/magadheera |title=Magadheera Review |date=31 July 2009 |access-date=9 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109094336/http://www.upperstall.com/films/2009/magadheera |archive-date=9 January 2015 |publisher=Upperstall.com}}</ref>\n\nRadhika Rajamani of [[Rediff.com]] called the film \"technically brilliant\" and wrote \"A reincarnation story is not often seen in Telugu cinema and SS Rajamouli uses this theme for Ram Charan Teja's second film Magadheera. It's a magnum opus production with great technical work. The graphics are excellent for a Telugu movie. Overall, the movie is a mainstream one with good packaging.\" She rated the film 3 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/review/2009/jul/31/the-magadheera-review.htm |title=Magadheera is technically brilliant |date=31 July 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111155453/http://movies.rediff.com/review/2009/jul/31/the-magadheera-review.htm |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref> [[Sify]] called the film a \"brilliant entertainer\" and wrote, \"Set against the backdrop of an eerie theme&nbsp;\u2014 reincarnation&nbsp;\u2014 Magadheera unfolds on the screen with multiple shades of entertainment. When the movie was launched last year, director Rajamouli dared to reveal the central theme of the story. He has succeeded in his attempt, as he was able to keep the screenplay and narration gripping from start to finish. The second half has the soul in it.\" Sify summarised, \"In short, the movie encompasses some of the best commercial elements that Telugu audience have seen in the recent past.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-review-telugu-14902427.html |title=Movie Review : Magadheera |date=1 August 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111173514/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-review-telugu-14902427.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref>\n\nIndiaGlitz called the film \"royal and spellbinding\" and opined, \"The film deserves a special credit for many reasons, notable among them is the grandeur of the movie and the amazing technical aspects. This is surely a path breaker in terms of Telugu film making and with the likes of 'Arundhati', Tollywood sure is proud to have this one in its league. It is a valiant attempt to bring such genre to the modern day audience and present it with finesse so that it fits the historical angle and the today's angle.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-review-telugu-movie-review-11250 |title=Magadheera Review&nbsp;\u2014 Royal and spellbinding |date=31 July 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111173613/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-review-telugu-movie-review-11250 |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> However, Rajamouli was accused of lifting scenes from films like ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' (2000), ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004), ''[[The Myth (film)|The Myth]]'' (2005) and ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' (2007).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Is-Rajamouli-a-skilled-copycat/articleshow/25953750.cms |title=Is Rajamouli a skilled copycat? |date=17 November 2013 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114135446/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Is-Rajamouli-a-skilled-copycat/articleshow/25953750.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film collected a share of approximately {{INRConvert|200|m}} in its first week in [[Andhra Pradesh]] alone, of which a share of {{INRConvert|71|m}} was collected in Nizam region.<ref name=\"200 m\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-20cr-firstweek-070809.html |title=Magadheera grosses Rs 20 cr in first week |date=7 August 2009 |website=[[Oneindia]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109105742/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-20cr-firstweek-070809.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-1stweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 20 crores |date=7 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112134412/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-1stweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> Sixteen centres collected {{INRConvert|10|m}}, each of which was an all-time state record.<ref name=\"MGD 100\">{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/nov/12/south-report-magadheera-not-out.htm |title=Magadheera, 100 not out! |date=12 November 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112144930/http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/nov/12/south-report-magadheera-not-out.htm |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref> It collected a share of {{INRConvert|381.5|m}} in 21 days in Andhra Pradesh.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-3rdweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 38.51 crores in 3 weeks in AP |date=26 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112134814/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-3rdweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> By the end of its four-week run, the film was declared a blockbuster and collected a share of {{INRConvert|435.6|m}} in 28 days and {{INRConvert|470.8|m}} in 35 days.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-4thweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 43.56 crores in 4 weeks in AP |date=31 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112134636/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-4thweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-5thweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 47.08 crores in 5 weeks in AP |date=8 September 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112135010/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-5thweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> The film completed a 50-day run in 302 centres on 18 September 2009. By then, the film had collected {{INRConvert|650|m}} and stood strong.<ref name=\"MGD 175\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-completes-175-days-news-telugu-kkfqXWfddabsi.html |title=Magadheera completes 175 days |date=23 January 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112140118/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-completes-175-days-news-telugu-kkfqXWfddabsi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-celebrates-50-days---malayalam-news-50106 |title='Magadheera' celebrates 50 days!!! |date=19 September 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112140820/http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-celebrates-50-days---malayalam-news-50106 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\nThe film completed its 100-day run in 223 centres. By then it had surpassed [[Rajinikanth]]'s ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' (2007), which grossed {{INRConvert|650|m}} in [[Tamil Nadu]], and stood second to ''Ghajini'' (2008), which reached {{INRConvert|2|b}}.<ref name=\"MGD 100\" /> The film completed a 175-day run in 3 centres and, by then, collected a share of {{INRConvert|580|m}}.<ref name=\"MGD 175\" /> The film completed a 365-day run in Vijayalakshmi theatre in [[Kurnool]] on 31 July 2010 and a 1000-day run in the same theatre on 26 April 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/aug/05/slide-show-1-south-telugu-snippets.htm |title=Magadheera runs non-stop for 365 days |date=5 August 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112145924/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/aug/05/slide-show-1-south-telugu-snippets.htm |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Magadheera-1000-days-poster/articleshow/13608953.cms |title=Magadheera 1000 day\u2019s poster |date=28 May 2012 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112150032/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Magadheera-1000-days-poster/articleshow/13608953.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nMore than 50% of the film's lifetime collections were from the Nizam region.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Nizam-territory-will-remain-indispensable-for-Tollywood/articleshow/21499426.cms |title=Nizam territory will remain indispensable for Tollywood |date=31 July 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112151416/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Nizam-territory-will-remain-indispensable-for-Tollywood/articleshow/21499426.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The film also did well in the overseas box office. It was released in [[New Jersey]] with three prints on three screens and collected a record share of more than 150,000 dollars, turning the highest amount raised overseas by a Telugu film; the previous record holder was [[Trivikram Srinivas]]' ''[[Jalsa]]'' (2008), which collected more than 100,000 dollars. It grossed 102,000 dollars in its first two days in New Jersey and a share of 95,000 dollars in [[Virginia]] with two prints as of mid August 2009. It collected a share of 78,000 dollars in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] with a single print. It managed to sell 2300 tickets in [[Minneapolis]]; the previous record for tickets sold there for a Telugu film was 1200.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-bozofficelegend.html |title=Magadheera&nbsp;\u2013 a box office legend |date=17 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112151152/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-bozofficelegend.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> The film's overseas records were beaten two years later by ''[[Dookudu]]'' (2011), although disputes have arisen over which film holds the Tollywood all-time sales record.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/dookudu-vs-magadheera-news-news-llqmdIaijagsi.html |title=Dookudu vs. Magadheera |date=16 November 2011 |access-date=26 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126041846/http://www.sify.com/movies/dookudu-vs-magadheera-news-news-llqmdIaijagsi.html |archive-date=26 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref>\n\nThe film was dubbed in Japanese and released there in 2018. This version earned an additional $1.2 million, the second highest for an Indian film after ''[[Muthu (1995 film)|Muthu]]'' (1995), which earned $1.6 million after being released in Japan.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/ss-rajamouli-s-magadheera-starring-ram-charan-opens-to-packed-house-in-japan/story-LBXNpg3D5ZOfwLUcl5h4LI.html |title=SS Rajamouli\u2019s Magadheera, starring Ram Charan, opens to packed house in Japan |date=5 September 2018 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n''Magadheera'''s success turned Kajal into one of the most sought-after actresses in Telugu cinema and catapulted her into the foray of leading Telugu actresses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/53748.html |title='Magadheera' earns 175 successful days! |date=21 January 2010 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113083214/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/53748.html |archive-date=13 November 2014 |access-date=13 November 2014}}</ref> The film was also considered a fate changer in the career of Ram Charan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/will-yevadu-be-another-magadheera/article4929256.ece |title=Will \u2018Yevadu\u2019 be another \u2018Magadheera\u2019? |last=IANS |date=19 July 2013 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114052812/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/will-yevadu-be-another-magadheera/article4929256.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The role of Sher Khan played by Srihari was considered as one of the best roles in his career and also catapulted S. S. Rajamouli to stardom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/regional/magadheera-completes-five-years-rajamouli-gets-nostalgic/article1-1247091.aspx |title=Magadheera completes five years, Rajamouli gets nostalgic |date=1 August 2014 |website=[[Hindustan Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114053215/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/regional/magadheera-completes-five-years-rajamouli-gets-nostalgic/article1-1247091.aspx |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Dev Gill attained stardom with this film and went on to work in several South Indian films as an antagonist. After the release of ''Magadheera'', people began recognising him as Ranadheer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hyderabad-gave-him-everything/article2764374.ece |title=Hyderabad gave him everything |last=Chowdhary |first=Y. Sunita |date=1 January 2012 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114093055/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hyderabad-gave-him-everything/article2764374.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> According to writer [[Gopimohan]], ''Magadheera'' started a trend of experimentation with period, socio-fantasy and spiritual themes that was continued in films like ''[[Panchakshari]]'' (2010), ''[[Nagavalli (film)|Nagavalli]]'' (2010), ''[[Anaganaga O Dheerudu]]'' (2011), ''Mangala'' (2011), ''[[Sri Rama Rajyam]]'' (2011) and ''[[Uu Kodathara? Ulikki Padathara?]]'' (2012).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/article358499.ece |title=Old genres, new packaging! |date=5 September 2011 |website=The New Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114054205/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/article358499.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe props used in this film, including weapons like swords and shields, were auctioned by Movie Artist Association. Actors, technicians, and the general public were invited to bid and the proceeds were used to aid poor artists in the Telugu film industry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-weapons-to-be-auctioned-telugu-news-56817 |title=Magadheera Weapons To Be Auctioned |date=8 May 2010 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114093734/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-weapons-to-be-auctioned-telugu-news-56817 |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Actor [[Sivaji Raja]] started the bidding by offering {{INR}}50,000 for the sword that Ram Charan used and comedian [[Venu Madhav (actor)|Venu Madhav]] started the bidding for the shield with {{INR}}25,000. B. V. S. N. Prasad bid for both the sword and knife for {{INR}}100,000. The bidding started on 7 May 2010 online in the association's official website and ended on 16 May. The winners were declared on 20 May 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-maa-auction-100510.html |title=Magadheera's swords and shields are on auction |date=10 May 2010 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114094206/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-maa-auction-100510.html |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> After ''Magadheera'', S. S. Rajamouli worked on a small budget film ''[[Maryada Ramanna]]'' (2010) which, according to [[Crazy Mohan]], was similar to the act of [[S. S. Vasan]] directing the small budget film ''[[Mr. Sampat]]'' (1952) after ''[[Chandralekha (1948 film)|Chandralekha]]'' (1948).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/buzzing-like-crazy/article3291780.ece |title=Buzzing like crazy |last=Rangrajan |first=Malathi |date=8 April 2012 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114104741/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/buzzing-like-crazy/article3291780.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Rajamouli explained his decision by saying, \"I decided that my next project would be ''Maryada Ramanna'' during the ''Magadheera'' shooting itself because it is a 1 and half year project that demands lot of physical labor and mental strain. I didn't want to commit another physically exhausting film immediately after ''Magadheera''. ''Maryada Ramanna'' gave us time to recharge our batteries so that we could come up with another huge project.\" He revealed ''Maryada Ramanna''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s plot before its launch to minimise the expectations of his audience after ''Magadheera''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s success.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/ssrajamouli-maryadaramanna.html |title=Interview with SS Rajamouli |date=20 July 2010 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114105429/http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/ssrajamouli-maryadaramanna.html |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Tammareddy Bharadwaja]] said \"Ever since ''Arundhati'' and ''Magadheera'' did well at the box office, the rest of the industry started following their footsteps. Also, since there is an irrational craze to make high budget films right now, producers are turning towards mythological films. It is the only genre where you can boast of spending crores for creating the sets and the look of the film. But what they don't realize is that if these films flop, the blow to the producer will be severe.\" Films like ''Anaganaga O Dheerudu'' (2011) and ''[[Shakti (2011 film)|Shakti]]'' (2011) were commercial failures and ''[[Badrinath (film)|Badrinath]]'' (2012) was an average grosser; all being fantasy films in which the protagonist is a warrior.<ref name=\"resemblance\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Mythological-characters-a-hit-in-T-town/articleshow/8207023.cms |title=Mythological characters, a hit in T-town |last=Bhat |first=Prashanth |date=10 May 2011 |work=The Times of India |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219080236/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Mythological-characters-a-hit-in-T-town/articleshow/8207023.cms |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Badrinath-completes-50days-in-187-theatres/articleshow/9466159.cms |title=Badrinath completes 50days in 187 theatres |date=3 August 2011 |work=The Times of India |access-date=19 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219080609/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Badrinath-completes-50days-in-187-theatres/articleshow/9466159.cms |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> The promos of ''Badrinath'' looked similar to ''Magadheera'' and the former's director [[V. V. Vinayak]] along with its male lead [[Allu Arjun]] kept insisting that ''Badrinath'' is dissimilar to ''Magadheera''. Producer Natti Kumar said \"If a hero delivers a hit, producers run after him for five years and burn their fingers only after six or eight flops. It's the same story with movies. Since ''Magadheera'' became a hit, every other hero and director wants to do period film where there is scope to spend crores. They don't work on the script, story or relevance. It is a pure display of graphics, heroes' abs and grandeur. The plot is lost. ''Magadheera'' worked because it was a novel genre then, but why will people want to see the same things again?\".<ref name=\"resemblance\" />\n\n[[Janani Iyer]] cited the character of Mithravinda played by Kajal in the film as one of her dream roles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/in-spotlight/article4003989.ece |title=In spotlight |last=Jeshi |first=K. |date=17 October 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219081543/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/in-spotlight/article4003989.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> [[Ram Gopal Varma]] refused to call ''Magadheera'' a film and instead termed it as an event that comes \"once in a blue moon\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-envisons-a-New-Telugu-Film-Industry/articleshow/39348963.cms |title=RGV envisons a New Telugu Film Industry |date=31 July 2010 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114105857/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-envisons-a-New-Telugu-Film-Industry/articleshow/39348963.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> While commenting on [[Mahesh Babu]]'s ''[[Aagadu]]'' (2014), he said that ''Magadheera'' looked like a 750 [[crore]] film when compared to ''Aagadu'' if the latter was a 75 crore film and added, \"My comparison between \"''Aagadu''\" and \"''Magadheera''\" is mainly because they both are the most expensive films for their own individual times.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-taunts-Mahesh-Babus-Aagadu/articleshow/42919785.cms |title=RGV taunts Mahesh Babu's Aagadu |last=Pasupulate |first=Karthik |date=19 September 2014 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114110208/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-taunts-Mahesh-Babus-Aagadu/articleshow/42919785.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Reviewing the Tamil film ''[[Anegan]]'' (2014), few critics opined that the film had traces of ''Magadheera'' mainly due to the theme of reincarnation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Anegan/movie-review/46236503.cms |title=Anegan Movie Review |date=13 February 2015 |work=The Times of India |access-date=20 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6aA4dsVt3?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Anegan/movie-review/46236503.cms |archive-date=20 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/anegan-review-welcome-back-karthik-you-are-in-a-love-story-in-2015-wait-dhanush-is-the-hero-who-are-you-in-the-film-then-967225.html |title='Anegan' review: Welcome back Karthik! You are in a love story in 2015? Wait. Dhanush is the hero? Who are you in the film then? |date=14 February 2015 |access-date=20 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720111827/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/anegan-review-welcome-back-karthik-you-are-in-a-love-story-in-2015-wait-dhanush-is-the-hero-who-are-you-in-the-film-then-967225.html |archive-date=20 July 2015 |publisher=CNN-IBN}}</ref> The Tamil dubbed version of the Telugu film ''[[Yevadu]]'' (2014), which featured Charan in one of the lead roles and Kajal in a crucial cameo, was titled ''Magadheera''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.andhrajyothy.com/Artical?SID=128134&SupID=24 |title=\u2018\u0c2e\u0c17\u0c27\u0c40\u0c30\u2019\u0c17\u0c3e \u0c35\u0c38\u0c4d\u0c24\u0c41\u0c28\u0c4d\u0c28 \u2018\u0c0e\u0c35\u0c21\u0c41\u2019 |date=10 July 2015 |work=[[Andhra Jyothy]] |access-date=20 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720112159/http://www.andhrajyothy.com/Artical?SID=128134&SupID=24 |archive-date=20 July 2015 |language=Telugu |trans-title='Yevadu' as 'Magadheera'}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nThe film won the [[National Film Awards|National Award]] for [[National Film Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] and [[National Film Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] at the [[57th National Film Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Magadheera-bags-best-spl-effects-choreography-awards/articleshow/6562319.cms |title=`Magadheera' bags best spl effects, choreography awards' |date=15 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052254/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Magadheera-bags-best-spl-effects-choreography-awards/articleshow/6562319.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The film also won six [[57th Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadhera-wins-6-filmfare-awards-news-telugu-kkguRAfifbbsi.html |title=Magadhera wins 6 Filmfare awards |date=9 August 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052048/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadhera-wins-6-filmfare-awards-news-telugu-kkguRAfifbbsi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref> nine [[Nandi Awards]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-sweeps-nandi-awards-telugu-news-60632 |title='Magadheera' Sweeps Nandi Awards |date=7 October 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052352/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-sweeps-nandi-awards-telugu-news-60632 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> and ten [[CineMAA Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/cine-maa-awards-10--magadheera-grabs-it-all-telugu-news-59471 |title=Cine'Maa' Awards'10: 'Magadheera' grabs it all |date=18 August 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112131605/http://www.indiaglitz.com/cine-maa-awards-10--magadheera-grabs-it-all-telugu-news-59471 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\n== Remakes ==\nRam Charan decided not to debut in [[Bollywood]] with ''Magadheera''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Hindi]] remake, as he believed the film might not be recreated well. In an interview with ''[[The Times of India]]'', Charan said, \"When I met [[Anil Kapoor]] some time back, he told me I will ask [[Boney Kapoor]] to remake ''Magadheera'' with you in Hindi. But I said I don't know if I would want to do the remake. ''Magadheera'' is a lovely film which can't be recreated.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Why-Ram-Charan-didnt-debut-with-Magadheera-remake/articleshow/12934631.cms |title=Why Ram Charan didn't debut with Magadheera remake? |date=30 April 2012 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114134803/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Why-Ram-Charan-didnt-debut-with-Magadheera-remake/articleshow/12934631.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The film was remade in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] as ''[[Yoddha: The Warrior]]'' in 2014; it was directed by [[Raj Chakraborty]] with [[Dev (Bengali actor)|Dev]] and [[Mimi Chakraborty]] playing the lead roles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/movies/news/Shopping-mall-or-railway-station-Dev-gets-mobbed-everywhere-Raj-Chakrabarty/articleshow/44947373.cms |title=Shopping mall or railway station, Dev gets mobbed everywhere: Raj Chakrabarty |last=Ganguly |first=Ruman |date=27 October 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112042143/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/movies/news/Shopping-mall-or-railway-station-Dev-gets-mobbed-everywhere-Raj-Chakrabarty/articleshow/44947373.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The 2014 [[Kannada]] film ''[[Brahma (2014 film)|Brahma]]'', according to its director [[R. Chandru]], was inspired by ''Magadheera'' but was not a remake.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bangalore/Chandru-Uppi-team-up-for-Brahma/2013/05/07/article1577938.ece |title=Chandru-Uppi team up for Brahma |date=7 May 2013 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112042755/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bangalore/Chandru-Uppi-team-up-for-Brahma/2013/05/07/article1577938.ece |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref><!-- In August 2014, [[Shahid Kapoor]] expressed his desire to reprise Ram Charan's role in a Hindi remake saying, \"I have been wanting to do ''Magadheera'' for the longest. I have seen the film and loved it.....I think it\u2019s a killer subject.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/shahid-kapoor-keen-to-do-magadheera-remake/ |title=Shahid Kapoor keen to do Magadheera remake |date=22 August 2014 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=22 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141122124329/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/shahid-kapoor-keen-to-do-magadheera-remake/ |archive-date=22 November 2014}}</ref> In late November 2014, [[Sajid Nadiadwala]] confirmed that he would direct the film's Hindi remake with Kapoor as the lead.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sajid-nadiadwala-denies-sequel-to-salman-khans-kick-confirms-magadheera-remake-with-shahid-kapoor/ |title=Sajid Nadiadwala denies sequel to Salman Khan\u2019s \u2018Kick\u2019, confirms \u2018Magadheera\u2019 remake with Shahid Kapoor |date=21 November 2014 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=22 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141122124602/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sajid-nadiadwala-denies-sequel-to-salman-khans-kick-confirms-magadheera-remake-with-shahid-kapoor/ |archive-date=22 November 2014}}</ref> When asked by Subhash K. Jha the reason for not directing the Hindi remake, Rajamouli said \"I've already spent two years of my life on it. I\u2019d rather make something else. ''Magadheera'' was my toughest film to make. Very tiring.\"<ref name=\"Subhash Jha\" /> By June 2016, Kapoor was no longer part of the Hindi remake.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-ll-be-unemployed-after-rangoon-shahid-kapoor-2223790 |title=I\u2019ll be unemployed after Rangoon: Shahid Kapoor |last=Rakshit |first=Nayandeep |date=15 June 2016 |website=Daily News and Analysis |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830142326/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-ll-be-unemployed-after-rangoon-shahid-kapoor-2223790 |archive-date=30 August 2016 |access-date=21 August 2016}}</ref> --> The film was dubbed in Hindi under the same name by Goldmines Telefilms and released in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WAR8aa462kg |title=Magadheera 2015 Hindi Dubbed Movie With Telugu Songs |date=9 July 2015 |publisher=Goldmines Movies |access-date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book|last=Chinnarayana|first=Pulagam|url=http://s1056.photobucket.com/user/PavanJandhyala/library/Magadheera?sort=3&page=1|title=\u0c27\u0c40\u0c30... \u0c27\u0c40\u0c30... \u0c27\u0c40\u0c30... \u0c2e\u0c28\u0c38\u0c3e\u0c17 \u0c32\u0c47\u0c26\u0c41\u0c30\u0c3e!|trans-title=O brave one... my heart can't wait any longer|language=Telugu|date=2 August 2015|work=[[Sakshi (newspaper)|Sakshi]]|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Rinki Roy|last=Bhattacharya|title=Bimal Roy's Madhumati: Untold Stories from Behind the Scenes|year=2014|publisher=Rupa Publications|isbn=978-8129129161|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1447500|Magadheera}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Special Effects|state=collapsed}}\n{{Nandi Award for Best Popular Feature Film}}\n{{Filmfare Best Telugu Film}}\n{{S. S. Rajamouli}}\n{{K. Bhagyaraj}}\n[[Category:2000s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s action films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:Indian fantasy action films]]\n[[Category:Indian fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:Films directed by S. S. Rajamouli]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Choreography National Film Award-winning choreography]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by M. M. Keeravani]]\n[[Category:Films set in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Ramoji Film City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Special Effects National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Indian action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2009 film by S. S. Rajamouli}}\n{{good article}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Magadheera\n| image          = Magadheera Poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[S. S. Rajamouli]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Allu Aravind]]\n* [[B. V. S. N. Prasad]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = S. S. Rajamouli\n| story          = [[K. V. Vijayendra Prasad]]\n| starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Ram Charan]]\n* [[Kajal Aggarwal]]\n* [[Dev Gill]]\n* [[Srihari]]\n}}\n| music          = [[M. M. Keeravani]]\n| cinematography = [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]]\n| editing        = [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]\n| studio         = [[Geetha Arts]]\n| distributor    = Geetha Arts\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|2009|7|31}}\n| country        = India\n| language       = Telugu\n| runtime        = 166 minutes\n| budget         = {{INR}}35 crore<ref name=\"TOI budget\">{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/rajamoulis-magadheera-rocking-in-japan-after-baahubali-and-muthu/articleshow/65699126.cms |title=Rajamouli\u2019s \u2018Magadheera\u2019 rocking in Japan after \u2018Baahubali\u2019 and \u2018Muthu\u2019 - Times of India |website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"NewsMinute budget\">https://www.thenewsminute.com/%27Can%27t%20believe%20it%27s%20been%20a%20decade%20already%27%3A%20Ram%20Charan%20on%2010%20years%20of%20%27Magadheera%27</ref>\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''Magadheera''''' ({{trans|Great Warrior}}) is a 2009 Indian [[Telugu language|Telugu]]-language [[Fantasy film|fantasy]] [[action film]], written by [[K. V. Vijayendra Prasad]] and directed by [[S. S. Rajamouli]]. The film stars [[Ram Charan]] and [[Kajal Aggarwal]], with [[Dev Gill]] and [[Srihari]] in supporting roles, and was produced by [[Allu Aravind]] of [[Geetha Arts]]. The reincarnation-themed plot revolves around four people: a valiant warrior in charge of the princess' safety, the princess who is in love with him, the commander-in-chief of the army who lusts after the princess, and an emperor who wants to conquer their kingdom. They all die before their wishes are fulfilled and the plot jumps forward 400 years, at which point the reincarnation of the warrior starts having flashbacks upon a chance encounter.\n\nMade on a budget of {{INR}}35 crore,<ref name=\"TOI budget\" /><ref name=\"NewsMinute budget\" /> production began on 2 March 2008 while principal photography commenced on 19 March 2008. The cinematography was done by [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]], and was edited by [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]]. Production design was done by R. Ravinder, while the action sequences were choreographed by [[Peter Hein]] and the duo of Ram\u2014Lakshman. The visual effects were designed by R. C. Kamalakannan, with assistance from Adel Adili and Pete Draper. It is the first Telugu film to list a \"visual effects producer\" in its credits. The soundtrack was composed by [[M. M. Keeravani]], who collaborated with [[Kalyani Malik]] to score the background music.\n\n''Magadheera'' was released on 31 July 2009 across 1250 screens worldwide, to critical acclaim, and collected a distributor's share of {{INR}}731 million. Its 1000-day theatrical run surpassed ''[[Chandramukhi]]'' (2005) as the longest running [[Cinema of South India|South Indian film]]. It is also the first Telugu film to have a home media release in [[Blu-ray]]. The film won the [[National Film Awards|National Award]] for [[National Film Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] and [[National Film Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] at the [[57th National Film Awards]] as well as winning six [[57th Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]], nine [[Nandi Awards]] and ten [[CineMAA Awards]]. The film's success catapulted the lead actors into stardom.\n\nThe film was dubbed into [[Tamil language|Tamil]] as ''Maaveeran'' and [[Malayalam]] as ''Dheera: The Warrior'', and was released simultaneously on 27 May 2011 in more than 100 and 50 screens respectively, with both versions being commercially successful. In 2014, the film was further remade in [[Cinema of West Bengal|Bengali]] as ''[[Yoddha: The Warrior]]'' by [[Raj Chakraborty]].\n\n== Plot ==\nHarsha, a [[Freestyle motocross|dirt-bike racer]], is travelling via [[auto rickshaw]]. He spots the blurry outline of a woman trying to flag the auto down, and gestures to her that it is already occupied. As he does, their fingers accidentally touch, and Harsha feels an electric current passing through him, which triggers a few fleeting images. After recovering from the shock, he flees the auto in search of the girl and inquires about her to a woman named Indira \"Indu\", unaware that Indu is the same woman. Indu, thinking he is stalking her, misdirects him by convincing him that the girl is her neighbour. She and her friends exploit Harsha, having him take them to places and promising that the girl will show. After Harsha beats up a group of men who were verbally harassing Indu, she starts to fall in love with him.\n\nMeanwhile, Indu's distant cousin Raghuveer, lusts after her. He manipulates Indu and her father into trusting him. However, when he attempts to touch a sleeping Indu, he sees visions of a warrior slitting his throat. Raghuveer consults a [[Tantra|tantrik]], Ghora, who reveals that in a prior life, Raghuveer was a prince who lusted after Indu, and was killed by her lover, a warrior. Raghuveer is determined to find the [[reincarnation]] of the warrior and kill him. Meanwhile, Harsha discovers how Indu and her friends have been defrauding him, and after he pranks her in retaliation, they start to fall in love. Raghuveer discovers that Harsha is the reincarnation of the warrior, murders Indu's father and frames Harsha. As Raghuveer and Indu leave in a helicopter, Harsha fails to catch them; falling into a lake, he faces a [[near-death experience]] and gets a full vision of his past-life in 1609.\n\nIn 1609, Emperor Sher Khan is preparing to invade the kingdom of Udayghar when he hears of the brave warrior Kala Bhairava (Harsha). King Vikram Singh's daughter, Mithravindha Devi (Indu), loves Bhairava, but he holds himself back. Ranadev Billa (Raghuveer), lusts after Mithra and plans a competition between himself and Bhairava; the winner will marry her and the loser will be banished from Udayghad. Bhairava's victory leads to Ranadev's banishment. Vikram Singh, however, secretly requests that Bhairava not marry his daughter, because Bhairava has a high chance of dying in the ensuing battle with Khan's forces, and he does not wish to see Mithra widowed. Though shocked, Bhairava concedes to the king's request and publicly declines to marry Mithra, leaving her distraught.\n\nBhairava takes Mithra, his soldiers, and his caretakers to the Bhairavakona temple atop a cliff to seek blessings from God prior to the attack. Mithra demands that Bhairava admit his love for her. When he does not respond, she upsets the sacred items they have brought for the ''[[Puja (Hinduism)|puja]]'' and, using her own blood, paints an image of Bhairava on a rock leaving his true love to do his duty. An injured soldier arrives to tell Bhairava that Ranadev has aided Khan's army, who have killed Vikram Singh and are now rushing toward them. They arrive, and Khan challenges Bhairava to kill at least 100 of his soldiers. Bhairava completes the challenge, but is severely injured in the battle. Khan, impressed by Bhairava's bravery, has a change of heart and accepts him as his friend. However, Ranadev continues attacking, eventually wounding Mithra before being killed by Bhairava. A dying Mithra asks Bhairava to confess his love, but before he can respond, she dies and falls off the cliff. Distraught, he jumps to his own death.\n\nIn the present, Harsha is rescued by a fisherman named Solomon (the reincarnation of Khan) and, with Solomon's help, visits Udayghad. He reaches Raghuveer's palace and overhears Ghora telling Raghuveer that if Indu's past-life memories are not revived within the day they never can be, and she will be with Raghuveer forever. Harsha kidnaps Indu and takes her to Bhairavakona and in the process, Raghuveer accidentally kills Ghora. Raghuveer arrives by helicopter and asks Indu to come with him; however Indu sees Mithra's painting, and her past-life memories are revived. Harsha fights Raghuveer, and with the help of Solomon, manages to kill him and the couple reunites.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Ram Charan]] as Kala Bhairava and Harsha\n* [[Kajal Aggarwal]] as Mithravinda Devi and Indira (Indu)\n* [[Dev Gill]] as Ranadev Billa and Raghuveer\n* [[Srihari]] as Sher Khan and Solomon\n* [[Rao Ramesh]] as Ghora\n* [[Sarath Babu]] as Vikram Singh\n* [[Surya (Telugu actor)|Surya]] as Bhoopathi Varma\n* [[Sunil (actor)|Sunil]] as Harsha's gullible friend\n* [[Sameer Hasan]] as Maan Singh\n\n;Cameo appearances\n\n* [[Chiranjeevi]] in a [[cameo appearance]] in the [[item number|item song]] \"Bangaru Kodipetta\".\n* [[Mumaith Khan]] as Reshma, the dirt bike race organiser. She also appears in \"Bangaru Kodipetta\".\n* [[Kim Sharma]] as Hamsa, a dancer who appears in the item song \"Jorsey\".\n* [[Brahmanandam]] as Indu's neighbour\n* [[Hema (actress)|Hema]] as Sasikala\n* [[Saloni Aswani]] as Solomon's girlfriend.\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\"My father Vijayendra Prasad prepared a story for a film titled {{'}}''Jagadeka Veerudu''{{'}} with [[Krishna (Telugu actor)|Krishna]] as hero in the direction of Sagar. They didn't like that concept and it was turned down. I was working as an assistant to my father at that time. I always wanted to do that story and it required huge budget. When I was granted big budget from Allu Arvind for Charan's movie, I picked this subject up.\n\nI watched DVDs of [[Alfred Hitchcock]]'s [[Alfred Hitchcock Presents|TV series]] before making ''Magadheera''. What intrigued me is that he reveals the entire plot in the beginning and still be able to maintain the suspense by showing how the protagonist does it. It became an eye opener for me. That is the reason why I revealed the story of the movie right on the film's launch.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014 [[S. S. Rajamouli]] on the genesis of the film<ref name=\"post mortem\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/movie/postmortem/magadheera.html |title=Postmortem&nbsp;\u2014 Magadheera by SS Rajamouli&nbsp;\u2014 Part 1 |publisher=[[Idlebrain.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106063810/http://www.idlebrain.com/movie/postmortem/magadheera.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n[[K. V. Vijayendra Prasad]] was watching a [[Marathi language|Marathi]] film where two warriors Sivaji and Tanaji are attacked by [[Army of the Mughal Empire|Mughal Army]]. Once the duo can reach [[Sinhagad]] fort, they can kill the army together effectively. While Sivaji escapes to the fort for support, Tanaji fights with the army and dies in the process leaving Sivaji in grief. Prasad took this as an inspiration and wrote a story on the theme of [[reincarnation]] of a bodyguard who serves a queen. He fights 100 warriors and dies in his attempt to re-enthrone his queen after she is overthrown by her conspirators. He is reborn after 400 years and fulfils his ambition of placing her on the throne by making her a [[Chief Minister]] or a popular social worker like [[Medha Patkar]]. It was subsequently rejected and after fifteen years, his son director [[S. S. Rajamouli]] selected this script, but made several changes to it.{{Sfn|Chinnarayana|2015|page=10}} Rajamouli re-characterised the queen as a princess to create a vital love story for the film, as he felt that the relationship between a queen and a bodyguard would be only about loyalty and honesty.<ref name=\"post mortem\" /> Prasad said he was inspired by the [[Kannada]] film ''[[Raja Nanna Raja]]'' (1976) while writing the story.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vijaykarnatakaepaper.com/ |title=Vijay Karnataka: ePaper |website=www.vijaykarnatakaepaper.com}}</ref>\n\nProduction for the film was officially launched on 2 March 2008 at FNCC in Hyderabad. B. V. S. N. Prasad co-produced the film with Allu Aravind under his production banner, [[Geetha Arts]]. M. Rathnam was announced as the dialogue writer while Rajamouli's usual associates [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]], [[Kotagiri Venkateswara Rao]] and [[M. M. Keeravani]] worked on the film's cinematography, editing and music respectively.<ref name=\"launch sify\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/rajamouli-ram-charan-film-launched-news-telugu-kkftO4fbbjcsi.html |title=Rajamouli&nbsp;\u2014 Ram Charan film launched |date=3 March 2008 |publisher=[[Sify]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106063847/http://www.sify.com/movies/rajamouli-ram-charan-film-launched-news-telugu-kkftO4fbbjcsi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter many potential titles, ''Magadheera'' was considered and finalised in early February 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/ram-charan-title-magadheera-030209.html |title=Magadheera, Ram Charan's film title |date=3 February 2009 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109053201/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/ram-charan-title-magadheera-030209.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charan-the-magadheera-imagegallery-0-tollywood-jgym1xiidbfsi.html |title=Ram Charan, the Magadheera |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109053710/http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charan-the-magadheera-imagegallery-0-tollywood-jgym1xiidbfsi.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> Tamil and Malayalam dubbed versions were planned in mid February 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-in-tamil-and-malayalam-telugu-news-44954 |title='Magadheera' in Tamil and Malayalam |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112151920/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-in-tamil-and-malayalam-telugu-news-44954 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |access-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The film's Tamil dubbed version was titled as ''Maaveeran'', named after the [[Maaveeran|1986 Tamil film]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-as-maaveeran-in-tamil-tamil-news-65567 |title='Magadheera' as 'Maaveeran' in Tamil |date=5 April 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060126/http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-as-maaveeran-in-tamil-tamil-news-65567 |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> Geetha Arts collaborated with [[Udhayanidhi Stalin]] for the Tamil version and distributed it under his production banner, Red Giant Movies.<ref name=\"Tamil 27 May\">{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Tamil-Magadheera-to-release-on-May-27/articleshow/8552501.cms |title=Tamil Magadheera to release on May 27 |date=24 May 2011 |website=[[The Times of India]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060405/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Tamil-Magadheera-to-release-on-May-27/articleshow/8552501.cms |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> [[K. Bhagyaraj]] wrote the dialogues for ''Maaveeran''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/maaveeran-review-tamil-movie-review-13435 |title=Maaveeran Review&nbsp;\u2014 Bold and beautiful |date=27 May 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060933/http://www.indiaglitz.com/maaveeran-review-tamil-movie-review-13435 |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref> The Malayalam version was titled ''Dheera\u2014The Warrior'' and was distributed by Pallavi films.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/malayalam/article/65583.html |title=Allu To Present 'Dheera' |date=6 April 2011 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109060758/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/malayalam/article/65583.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Pallavi films\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/maghadheera-is-dheera-the-warrior-news-malayalam-lcdrSocafej.html |title=Maghadheera is Dheera- The Warrior |date=7 February 2011 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109055822/http://www.sify.com/movies/maghadheera-is-dheera-the-warrior-news-malayalam-lcdrSocafej.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Casting ===\nAfter considering several actresses (including [[Tamannaah]]) for the princess role, [[Kajal Aggarwal]] was selected by Rajamouli as the female lead opposite [[Ram Charan]] after conducting a photoshoot in his office.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/kajal-opposite-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkfuamfdiiisi.html |title=Kajal opposite Ram Charan |date=6 February 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106104625/http://www.sify.com/movies/kajal-opposite-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkfuamfdiiisi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> Rajamouli said that he wanted to cast her as the female lead in ''[[Yamadonga]]'' (2007) after her Telugu debut ''[[Lakshmi Kalyanam (2007 film)|Lakshmi Kalyanam]]'' (2007), but she was unavailable. He added that he wanted somebody \"good looking, who would look like a princess and who had dates available\" and finalised her because she met all of these prerequisites.<ref name=\"SSR Rediff\">{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/04/slide-show-1-rajamouli-on-magadheera.htm |title=The man behind Magadheera |date=4 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112172131/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/04/slide-show-1-rajamouli-on-magadheera.htm |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=[[Rediff.com]]}}</ref> After conducting her photoshoot, Rajamouli explained the story and Mithra's characterisation to her in 45 minutes. He said she needed to treat the hero arrogantly, but do so out of love for the hero. Kajal kept this in mind and acted accordingly<ref name=\"post mortem\" /> while playing the dual roles of a princess from 400 years ago and a modern-day college student. Kajal called both her roles \"unique and challenging\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-kajal-agarwal-on-magadheera/20090730.htm#4 |title='I play a princess and a college girl' |date=30 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106105405/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-kajal-agarwal-on-magadheera/20090730.htm |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Dev Gill]] was selected to portray the film's antagonist. Rajamouli was criticised for selecting him considering Gill's previous film, ''[[Krishnarjuna]]'' (2008), but remained adamant about casting him. He said that he had to cast a good looking man as the film's villain because the heroine needed to find him trustworthy. For this film, Gill had to practice horse riding in [[Ramoji Film City]]; Ram Charan was already an experienced [[equestrianism|equestrian]].<ref name=\"post mortem\" /> [[Srihari]] was cast in his role in the film in early April 2008.<ref name=\"Srihari\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/srihari-in-ram-charan-s-new-film-news-telugu-kkftFEfcacasi.html |title=Srihari in Ram Charan's new film |date=8 April 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106110517/http://www.sify.com/movies/srihari-in-ram-charan-s-new-film-news-telugu-kkftFEfcacasi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Kim Sharma]] was selected to perform one of the two [[item number]]s in the film in early June 2008.<ref name=\"Kim Sharma\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kim-sharma-to-shake-legs-with-ram-charan-telugu-news-38933 |title=Kim Sharma to shake legs with Ram Charan |date=30 May 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106105939/http://www.indiaglitz.com/kim-sharma-to-shake-legs-with-ram-charan-telugu-news-38933 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Saloni Aswani]] made a [[cameo appearance]] in the film and shot for three days. She was subsequently signed for Rajamouli's next project, ''[[Maryada Ramanna]]'' (2010), before ''Magadheera'' was even released.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jul/22/slide-show-1-south-interview-with-saloni.htm |title='I didn't expect Rajamouli to repeat me' |date=22 July 2010 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106113229/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/jul/22/slide-show-1-south-interview-with-saloni.htm |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nRao Ramesh was cast as a [[Tantra|tantrik]] who helps Gill's character in the present era.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Rao-Ramesh-makes-a-mark/articleshow/16602184.cms |title=Rao Ramesh makes a mark |last=Kaviyarani |first=Suresh |date=29 September 2012 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106151052/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Rao-Ramesh-makes-a-mark/articleshow/16602184.cms |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Mumaith Khan]] was selected for another item number, a remix version of the hit song \"Bangaru Kodipetta\" from ''[[Gharana Mogudu]]'' (1992); ''Gharana Mogudu'''s music was also composed by M. M. Keeravani.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2008/mumaith-khan-ram-charan-teja-090608.html |title=Mumaith to sizzle with Teja in a remake song |date=9 June 2008 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106151725/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2008/mumaith-khan-ram-charan-teja-090608.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> [[Chiranjeevi]] made a special appearance after the song, making ''Magadheera'' the first film he appeared in after his entry into politics. When Rajamouli suggested the idea of a cameo appearance, Chiranjeevi was initially hesitant till the director narrated the complete sequence and the importance of the song.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/chiru-acts-with-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkftjscbefasi.html |title=Chiru acts with Ram Charan |date=30 July 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106152030/http://www.sify.com/movies/chiru-acts-with-ram-charan-news-telugu-kkftjscbefasi.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Costume designs ===\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\"The colour scheme was decided at the beginning itself with Senthil, Ravinder and Rajamouli. There was a lot of coordination with the sets and the lighting schemes. The story has a Rajasthan backdrop so I had to look up old books available and the Internet for references to design the ancient costumes.\n\nFor ''[[Yamadonga]]'', there were direct references to get-ups and one had to improvise upon them. Whereas here there are no proper references as ''Magadheera'' is a fantasy story. Though the backdrop is Rajasthan, the references were useful for other characters than the lead protagonists. One had to imagine, match and put the costumes together for the hero and heroine.\"|source=&nbsp;\u2014 Rama Rajamouli on the film's styling in an interview with [[Rediff.com]]<ref name=\"Rama Interview Rediff\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-rama-rajamouli-on-styling-magadheera/20090729.htm |title='Magadheera has world class graphics' |date=29 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107070057/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-rama-rajamouli-on-styling-magadheera/20090729.htm |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nRegarding his looks in the film, Ram Charan said, \"Personality wise there isn\u2019t really much difference to Kalabhairava but I have to tell you minor changes like the shape of my mustache, a slight voice modulation, the background scale, the atmosphere and even the \u2018Chandrabindu\u2019 worked wonders on screen and gave a totally different look and feel and I felt like it was an altogether different side of me. When I was told of the characterization of \u2018Kalabhairava\u2019, I had an impression of a young, passionate soldier and naturally it had to have a great body and an authoritative voice. So, we also worked on it. We actually went to Rajasthan and observed the local culture and their way of dressing, we researched a lot about their costumes, history and great personalities 400 years ago and planned it accordingly.\"<ref name=\"india\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/interview/6917.html |title=Ram Charan: \"Dad Gave Me Breathless Hug\" |date=17 August 2009 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107064741/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/interview/6917.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> Ram Charan sported a long hairdo for both of his characters in the film.<ref name=\"india\" />\n\nTo design the armour used by Charan in his role as Kalabhairava, art director R. Ravinder wanted the precise measurements of Charan's body; they used [[plaster of Paris]] to make a mould of Charan's body shape from which they created a statue. They designed costumes for the statue and had Charan try them on once they were satisfied with the designs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-ramcharantejagetup.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 Ram Charan Teja's get-up |date=19 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107065429/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-ramcharantejagetup.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> In an interview with Radhika Rajamani of [[Rediff.com]], the film's stylist, Rama Rajamouli, said that it took one month to develop the right look for the olden period before she began working on the materials and costumes for the film. She added that all of the film's costumes were designed by her and stitched in Hyderabad, and that Kajal's costumes were heavily detailed as she needed to look rich, elegant and bright. Rajamouli had some disagreements with cinematographer K. K. Senthil Kumar over the colours of the costumes.<ref name=\"Rama Interview Rediff\" /> Her decision of having Kajal wear a dress of baby pink and pista green during the war sequence at Bhairavakona was initially opposed by Rajamouli, but later agreed to after the director saw the final edit. She also used minimal jewellery for the princess's outfits.<ref name=\"SSR Rediff\" />\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[File:Ramoji Film City.jpg|thumb|right|[[Ramoji Film City]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] where the film was shot in specially erected sets]]\nThe film's [[principal photography]] was expected to begin on 26 February 2008,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/kajal-is-the-girl-for-ram-charan-telugu-news-36389 |title=Kajal is the girl for Ram Charan |date=6 February 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106104853/http://www.indiaglitz.com/kajal-is-the-girl-for-ram-charan-telugu-news-36389 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> and then on 15 March 2008, but finally began on 19 March 2008 in [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"launch sify\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ram-charan-kajal-to-shoot-in-rajasthan-malayalam-news-37258 |title=Ram Charan, Kajal to shoot in Rajasthan |date=14 March 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106160307/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ram-charan-kajal-to-shoot-in-rajasthan-malayalam-news-37258 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> Initial shooting occurred for 10 days in [[Rann of Kutch]], [[Gujarat]].<ref name=\"Srihari\" /> Art director Ravinder went to [[Chennai]] and gave details of their requirements to a prominent chariot-making specialist. After rejecting the maker's first iron skeletons, Ravinder opted to design them himself, and prepared three models of chariots with different heights to be used, depending on the camera's location and other technical requirements. He used fibre material for the iron skeleton's exteriors. For a scene in which neither the hero nor the villain was present on the chariot, Ravinder measured a short person and designed a hidden chamber in which he could sit and secretly control the horses. While the chariot race sequence was shot in [[Dholavira]], the sequence in which the chariot sinks in quicksand was shot at a set comprising three acres in [[Ramoji Film City]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-chariot.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 Chariot making for Magadheera film |date=16 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106154132/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-chariot.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|quote=\"When we were looking for locations, we were told about Kutch. A [[Border Security Force|BSF]] guard there told us if we go further, we would find white land. We went further and found that kind of land. We doubted whether horses and chariot could run on that land. We took pictures and came back. Then our people checked whether horses and chariot could move on it. Because of the uneven light conditions, the sand would look yellowish and with DI we could make it white. So also the sky was coloured with a tinge of blue. The location helped the way it came out on screen.|source=&nbsp;\u2014 [[K. K. Senthil Kumar]] on the shoot of the film in [[Dholavira]]<ref name=\"Senthil Interview Rediff\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/07/slide-show-1-south-shooting-magadheera.htm |title='People compared Magadheera to a Hollywood film' |date=7 August 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107041305/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2009/aug/07/slide-show-1-south-shooting-magadheera.htm |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>}}\nK. K. Senthil Kumar scouted for locations in Gujarat, looking for dry, open lands to shoot the chariot race sequence. They found salt lands with white sands in Dholavira. To shoot the sequence there, they wanted a light weight vehicle to follow the horses; they bought a [[Maruti Suzuki|Maruti van]], removed the vehicle's top and mounted the camera along with a [[Jib (camera)|jimmy jib]] atop it. A part of the song ''Dheera Dheera'' was also shot there, requiring filmmakers to plant a dry tree and a couple of oxen for use in the song's backdrop.<ref name=\"Senthil interview IDB\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/senthilkumar.html |title=Interview with Senthil Kumar |date=20 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106153121/http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/senthilkumar.html |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref> An item number featuring Kim Sharma and Ram Charan was shot in late June 2008 in a specially erected fisherman colony. It was set up on the first floor of [[Annapurna Studios]] and cost less than {{INR}}3 million. Ravinder explained, \"The set should look like an outdoor location, but need to be constructed in an indoor floor. I constructed exteriors of around 28 houses in that floor with detailed interior plan for the house of Srihari. I also constructed a small boat and a big wheeled fish with thermocol. When director wanted smoke-effect for a shot I held the heavy smoke machine on my shoulders in a low angle for the required effect.\"<ref name=\"Kim Sharma\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-fishermencolony.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 fishermen colony set |date=18 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107033439/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-fishermencolony.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter filming key parts of the film in Rajasthan, suburbs of [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], and at [[Badami]] in [[Karnataka]], filming continued in Ramoji Film City in a specially erected set named Bhairavakona in late October 2008. Two more schedules, one from 3\u201310 December and one in January, were also shot at the Bhairavakona set.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ragalahari.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=5741 |title=Ram Charan\u2019s film shooting in Ramoji Film City |date=10 December 2008 |publisher=Raagalahari.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106161920/http://www.ragalahari.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=5741 |archive-date=6 November 2014 |access-date=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramoji-film-city-hosts-ramcharan-s-movie-telugu-news-44322 |title=Ramoji Film City hosts Ramcharan's movie |date=16 January 2009 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107031322/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramoji-film-city-hosts-ramcharan-s-movie-telugu-news-44322 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> The sequence of Charan killing 100 warriors, also at Bhairavakona, included a bridge. As the set did not permit for shooting with low angles, a separate half-bridge was erected at Bhoot Bangla in Road No. 22 of [[Banjara Hills]]. The bridge, which had a height of {{convert|60|ft|m}} and a length of {{convert|100|ft|m}}, was constructed on top of a rocky hill using steel beams as the skeleton and wooden material as support. It was built in around 20 days by over 60 men amid heavy rains. 20 trucks of black soil were transported from Ramoji Film City for the bridge set, as that type of soil was only available in the former location.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramoji-film-city-hosts-ramcharan-s-movie-telugu-news-44322 |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 Bridge making for Magadheera film |date=17 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107032654/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-bridge.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Golconda Fort 005.jpg|thumb|left|[[Golkonda Fort]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] where the song \"Panchadara Bomma\", picturised on Ram Charan and Kajal, was shot.]]\nAfter the completion of shooting at the arena set in Ramoji Film City, the arena set was demolished and a set for heroine's house was constructed in its place. This was the last set constructed for this film.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-heroinehouse.html |title=Art director Ravinder special&nbsp;\u2014 heroine house set for Magadheera film |date=20 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107034314/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-sets-heroinehouse.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> By late September 2008, 70% of the film's shoot was complete. The remix version of \"Bangaru Kodipetta\" was shot by Ram Charan and Mumaith Khan under the supervision of [[Prem Rakshith]] at [[Chennai Port]], although [[Visakhapatnam Port]] was first considered.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-teja--rajamoulis-movie-nears-finale-kannada-news-41837 |title=Ramcharan Teja&nbsp;\u2014 Rajamouli's movie nears finale |date=25 September 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107040140/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-teja--rajamoulis-movie-nears-finale-kannada-news-41837 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> Filming continued in and around Hyderabad very discreetly in November 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/all-eyes-on-ramcharan-tej-s-flick-news-telugu-kkfsDrafejbsi.html |title=All eyes on Ramcharan Tej's flick |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107043125/http://www.sify.com/movies/all-eyes-on-ramcharan-tej-s-flick-news-telugu-kkfsDrafejbsi.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> Stunt sequences by Ram Charan and some stuntmen were shot in mid-December 2008 at Hyderabad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-tej-is-busy-performing-stunts-telugu-news-43558 |title=RamCharan Tej is busy performing stunts |date=11 December 2008 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107042950/http://www.indiaglitz.com/ramcharan-tej-is-busy-performing-stunts-telugu-news-43558 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> By mid February 2009, the film's scripted part had been wrapped up, with only some songs left to shoot.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-ram-charan-audio-170209.html |title=5 lakh Magadheera audios to curb piracy |date=17 February 2009 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114132741/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-ram-charan-audio-170209.html |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The song \"Nakosam Nuvvu\" was shot in Switzerland while \"Panchadara Bomma Bomma\" was shot at [[Golconda Fort]] in Hyderabad. Both songs were duets shot by Ram Charan and Kajal.<ref name=\"MGD 5 OI\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2014/magadheera-5th-anniversary-ss-rajamouli-recalls-fond-memories-155564.html |title=Magadheera 5th Anniversary: SS Rajamouli Recalls Fond Memories |date=31 July 2014 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107040956/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2014/magadheera-5th-anniversary-ss-rajamouli-recalls-fond-memories-155564.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> K. K. Senthil Kumar said in an interview that ''Magadheera'' could not have been made in eight months because of its long pre-production and post-production phases.<ref name=\"Senthil Interview Rediff\" /> Over two [[lakh]]s worth of props, including swords, daggers, knives, bows and arrows, pouches, armour, footwear and other accessories, were used in the film. They were designed by 160 workers, including welders, molders, carpenters, painters, cobblers, artists, tailors and leather men, who worked for two months in the [[Geetha Arts]] Studio. Five people were appointed exclusively to look after these props.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/did-you-know-/Over-2-lakh-props-were-used-in-Magadheera/articleshow/42186637.cms |title=Over 2 lakh props were used in Magadheera |date=10 September 2014 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107043944/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/did-you-know-/Over-2-lakh-props-were-used-in-Magadheera/articleshow/42186637.cms |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> However, during the film's shoot both Peter Hein and Ram Charan suffered major injuries.<ref name=\"injure\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charans-maghadeera-a-roundup-news-telugu-kkfsrLdcaaesi.html |title=Ram Charan\u2019s Maghadeera: A Roundup |date=28 February 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112171830/http://www.sify.com/movies/ram-charans-maghadeera-a-roundup-news-telugu-kkfsrLdcaaesi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref> The former fell down from a height of 80{{mdash}}90 feet during the composition of a stunt and was advised a bed rest for four months.{{Sfn|Chinnarayana|2015|page=11}} Charan faced severe leg fractures,<ref name=\"injure\" /> while Rajamouli said that Peter \"met with an accident on the sets, had two broken ribs, fractured hands and jaw and lost all his teeth. Within a month, he was back on the sets with his face and body covered in bandages and plaster. He could barely lift his hands to shoot.\"<ref name=\"SSR Rediff\" />\n\n=== Visual effects ===\n[[File:Magadheera Visual effects.jpg|thumb|A scene from the song \"Dheera Dheera\" during the filming stage (''above''), the same scene in the film after utilisation of CG extension (''below'').]]\nR. C. Kamalakannan was the [[VFX]] producer of this film. ''Magadheera'' was the first Telugu film in which the position of \"Visual Effects Producer\" was used in the credits. He was assisted by a team of five experts from abroad and a 62 dedicated group members apart from 130 people from the company EFX in Chennai and Hyderabad. Special effects and [[Computer-generated imagery|CG]] was used for about 1 hour and 40 minutes out of the total 2 hours and 35 minutes in the film. 15% of the frames in the film's scenes of Udayghad city were actually shot with a camera; the rest were CG extension. For the scenes in the stadium, CG extension was slightly above 50%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/vfx-is-the-new-mantra-of-success/article173921.ece |title=VFX is the new mantra of success |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=1 September 2009 |website=[[The Hindu]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107072937/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/vfx-is-the-new-mantra-of-success/article173921.ece |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> For the stadium, Italian concept artist Marco Rolandi began with a [[Computer-aided design|CAD]] drawing and made his first 3D concept in 5 days. It took five months for Marco to reach the design shown in the film and as imagined by Rajamouli. Simultaneously, Iranian 3D technical director Adel Adili, who worked with Kamalakannan for ''[[Anji (film)|Anji]]'' (2004), ''Yamadonga'' and ''[[Arundhati (2009 film)|Arundathi]]'' (2009), was working on the 3D Udayghad city. He started with a city-plan and added streets, buildings, mountains, temples, palaces, water bodies, a huge waterfall, rivers, gates, a moat and trees, all of which were planned and received Rajamouli's approval before being executed to full scale. Adili redesigned Marco's 3D stadium to suit Indian aesthetics and made it fit perfectly within the city.<ref name=\"KK Interview IDB\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-vfx.html |title=Making of Magadheera visual effects |date=27 August 2009 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107073833/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/magadheera-vfx.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nPete Draper, who worked with Kamalakanna in ''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008), was selected as the pipeline technical director of the film. At that time, Kamalakannan was in Iran finalising the CG stadium and City with Adili. The majority of the film was shot in [[anamorphic format]], but a [[Super 35]] camera gate and lens were used for the stadium episode to minimise distortion. Post-production of the stadium scenes were given to Prasad EFX, and the film set up their own [[render farm]] in Chennai. The post process was done in several stages after the scan. The live stadium had only 7 steps, in which live people were positioned in 6 steps while the remaining 12 steps were CG extension. Adili created 3D CG people to fill the CG steps and their actions in a library of 3000 frames.<ref name=\"KK Interview IDB\" />\n\nDraper designed the birds in two flows: one flow kept flying around the stadium, while the other flow took off from a position dome and landed on a target dome. Rajamouli used those birds in several shots. Upon finishing the stages of the stadium composite, Kamalakannan flew to Iran again to work with Adel for the 3D city shots which were created entirely in CG. Adili designed 3D horses for the hero and villain and Draper designed the 3D people flocking behind the horses. About Adili's work, Kamalakannan said, \"When we started the city-shot renders, it has taken several hours to render one frame. But Adili re-corrected the geometry and applied several path breaking ideas, so even on 24 July, just a week before the film release, we were able to do corrections, render and submit.\"<ref name=\"KK Interview IDB\" /> {{INRConvert|40|m}} was spent solely on VFX for ''Magadheera''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Filmmakers-spend-extra-on-visual-effects/articleshow/10606670.cms |title=Filmmakers spend extra on visual effects |last=Pasupulate |first=Karthik |date=5 November 2011 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109144452/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Filmmakers-spend-extra-on-visual-effects/articleshow/10606670.cms |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Piracy ===\nDuring the film's shoot at [[Ramoji Film City]] in late November 2008, a {{convert|500|sqft|m2}} [[film can]], containing two or three scenes, was discovered missing from Rainbow lab. The filmmakers filed a case at Hayathnagar police station.<ref name=\"blue\" /> Security personnel and film unit members searched, but failed to recover the reels.<ref name=\"reel\" /> Rajamouli's unit said it was not important if the scenes from the can were aired online since they were not crucial scenes, were all on a [[Chroma key|blue matte]] and lacked finishing.<ref name=\"blue\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajamouli-s-reel-rolls-away-tamil-news-43168 |title=Rajamouli's reel rolls away |date=21 November 2008 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112170956/http://www.indiaglitz.com/rajamouli-s-reel-rolls-away-tamil-news-43168 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Later, raw footage from the film was seen on the internet but no details about the culprits were found.<ref name=\"blue\" /> After the photographs and small video clips were leaked on the Internet, some of the film unit members felt that the loss might have been a ploy on the part of the producers to create hype.<ref name=\"reel\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ramcharan-s-film-reels-go-missing-news-telugu-kkfsC4geecdsi.html |title=Ramcharan's film reels go missing |date=21 November 2008 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112171228/http://www.sify.com/movies/ramcharan-s-film-reels-go-missing-news-telugu-kkfsC4geecdsi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref>\n\n== Themes and influences ==\nThe film is based on the concept of [[reincarnation]] and eternal love. According to Rediff, the rewritten script's basic storyline is that \"Love remains eternal and it will follow generations and generations. There is always a big victory for Love.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-sneak-peek-at-ram-charan-tejas-telugu-film/20090728.htm |title=Are you ready for Ram Charan Teja's Magadheera? |date=28 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116091357/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-south-sneak-peek-at-ram-charan-tejas-telugu-film/20090728.htm |archive-date=16 November 2014 |access-date=16 November 2014}}</ref> The film's flashback sequences were used as a flip switch between the film's olden and present day eras.<ref name=\"The Hindu\" /> Initially the film featured a scene in which the present day heroine accidentally receives a [[dupatta]] preserved in a museum that is used in the flashbacks as the dupatta Bhairava and Ranadheer race for. However, separate dupattas were used in the film as Rajamouli felt that getting the dupatta from the flashback would complicate the narrative.<ref name=\"post mortem\" />\n\nIn her book ''Bimal Roy's Madhumati: Untold Stories from Behind the Scenes'', writer [[Rinki Bhattacharya]] compared the reincarnation theme of ''Magadheera'' with that of ''[[Madhumati]]'' (1958), ''[[Karz (film)|Karz]]'' (1980), ''[[Karan Arjun]]'' (1995) and ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'' (2007).{{Sfn|Bhattacharya|2014|page=170}} Touching the heroine unleashes locked memories within the hero that transport him to Rajasthan in 1609 from contemporary Hyderabad. Bhattacharya also compared ''Magadheera'' to another Telugu film, ''[[Mooga Manasulu]]'' (1964).{{Sfn|Bhattacharya|2014|page=170}} Rajamouli told [[Subhash K. Jha]] that he was inspired by ''Karan Arjun'' to make films based on reincarnation.<ref name=\"Subhash Jha\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/entertainment-tollywood/article/%E2%80%98proud-be-known-telugu-director%E2%80%99 |title=\u2018Proud to be known as Telugu director\u2019 |date=22 November 2014 |website=Deccan Chronicle |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141123135026/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/141122/entertainment-tollywood/article/%E2%80%98proud-be-known-telugu-director%E2%80%99 |archive-date=23 November 2014 |access-date=23 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Music ==\n{{Main|Magadheera (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[M. M. Keeravani]] composed the film's soundtrack. It features six songs including the remixed version of his own composition \"Bangaru Kodipetta\" from the film ''Gharana Mogudu''. The soundtrack of the Tamil dubbed version, ''Maaveeran'', had three additional tracks. The Telugu soundtrack was launched at [[Shilpakala Vedika]] in Hyderabad on 28 June 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-a-grand-audio-launch-news-telugu-kkfrLoddaehsi.html |title=Magadheera&nbsp;\u2014 A grand audio launch |date=29 June 2009 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107104323/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-a-grand-audio-launch-news-telugu-kkfrLoddaehsi.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref> The Tamil version was launched on 25 April 2011 in Chennai.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/maveeran-audio-launched-by-kamal-mani-news-tamil-lezlFMacebbsi.html |title=Maveeran audio launched by Kamal & Mani |date=26 April 2011 |publisher=Sify |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107104427/http://www.sify.com/movies/maveeran-audio-launched-by-kamal-mani-news-tamil-lezlFMacebbsi.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n[[Geetha Arts]] released the film on 31 July 2009, with 625 digital UFO prints in 1250 theatres across the globe, making ''Magadheera'' the biggest release for a Telugu film in history. Its release included more than 1000 screens in [[Andhra Pradesh]] alone.<ref name=\"MGD 5 OI\" /><ref name=\"Rediff release\">{{Cite web |url=http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/jul/30/magadheera-ready-to-go-international.htm |title=Magadheera ready to go international |date=30 July 2009 |publisher=Rediff.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042334/http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/jul/30/magadheera-ready-to-go-international.htm |archive-date=10 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/T-towns-winning-period/articleshow/4863699.cms |title=T-town's winning \u2018period\u2019 |last=Prakash |first=B. V. S. |date=7 August 2009 |work=The Times of India |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042425/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/T-towns-winning-period/articleshow/4863699.cms |archive-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> The film opened up with 25 prints overseas in almost 40 locations. ''Magadheera'' was the first Telugu film to be released on 21 screens in North America.<ref name=\"Rediff release\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/48560.html |title='Magadheera' to release with record prints overseas |date=25 July 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042644/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/48560.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Huge vinyl posters featuring Ram Charan and his father, cameo performer Chiranjeevi, were put up at all of the theatres in Krishna District. Posters also featured the head of Chiranjeevi's political party, former [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] Vangaveeti Radhakrishna, which added political importance to the release.<ref name=\"Magadheera Krishna\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/mad-rush-for-tickets-of-magadheera/article243057.ece |title=Mad rush for tickets of \u2018Magadheera\u2019 |date=31 July 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=14 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114051046/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/mad-rush-for-tickets-of-magadheera/article243057.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The Tamil dubbed version ''Maaveeran'' and Malayalam dubbed version ''Dheera\u2014The Warrior'' were released in more than 100 screens and 50 screens respectively on 27 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/news291.html |title=Tamil Magadheera releases on 27 |date=26 May 2011 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110042932/http://idlebrain.com/news/2000march20/news291.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Distribution ===\nRaju Hirwani, the owner of Supreme Music, ventured into overseas distribution with ''Magadheera''. He distributed the film in the USA via Blue Sky Cinemas Inc.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/pressmeet-supremeraju.html |title=Supreme Raju press meet |date=9 February 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131222/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/pressmeet-supremeraju.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/blue-sky-cinema-inc-to-release-magadheera-in-us-telugu-news-44887 |title=Blue Sky Cinema Inc. to release 'Magadheera' in U.S. |date=8 February 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131001/http://www.indiaglitz.com/blue-sky-cinema-inc-to-release-magadheera-in-us-telugu-news-44887 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/article99570.ece |title=Supreme to release Magadheera overseas |date=25 July 2009 |work=[[The New Indian Express]] |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110130854/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/article99570.ece |archive-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> The distribution rights of non-US countries, including the UK, Ireland, Middle East, Australia, New Zealand and Singapore, were acquired by Krishna Productions.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/krishna-productions-to-distribute-magadheera--telugu-news-45491 |title=Krishna Productions to distribute 'Magadheera' |date=9 March 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131952/http://www.indiaglitz.com/krishna-productions-to-distribute-magadheera--telugu-news-45491 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> The theatrical rights of Australia and New Zealand were sold to Tollyfilmz. The film's Singaporean rights were sold to Pragati films.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-global-distribution-telugu-news-45926 |title='Magadheera' global distribution |date=31 March 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131414/http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-global-distribution-telugu-news-45926 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-in-australia-new-zealand-and-singapore-news-telugu-kkfskbhgiagsi.html |title='Magadheera' in Australia, New Zealand and Singapore |date=1 April 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110130410/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-in-australia-new-zealand-and-singapore-news-telugu-kkfskbhgiagsi.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref> Gulf and Kuwait theatrical rights were sold to K. A. Chowdary and Basheer respectively.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-goes-to-gulf---telugu-news-47468 |title='Magadheera' goes to Gulf!!! |date=9 June 2009 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110131609/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-goes-to-gulf---telugu-news-47468 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Red Giant Movies distributed ''Maaveeran'' while Pallavi films distributed ''Dheera\u2014The Warrior''.<ref name=\"Tamil 27 May\" /><ref name=\"Pallavi films\" /> The film's Karnataka distributor, Vijayakumar, was disciplined for breaking the rules of the Karnataka Film Chamber of Commerce by simultaneously releasing a non-Kannada film in more than 21 screens in the state. The proceeds of 21 screens were given to him while the rest was confiscated by the Chamber of Commerce. The KFCC also suspended Vijaykumar, who was KFCC's secretary for distribution, from its executive committee.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/magadheera-steals-kannada-films-thunder/article204059.ece |title=\u2018Magadheera\u2019 steals Kannada films\u2019 thunder |last=Kumar |first=M.T. Shiva |date=12 August 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=13 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113081343/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/magadheera-steals-kannada-films-thunder/article204059.ece |archive-date=13 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nJoint collector Gaurav Uppal convened a meeting of film exhibitors and distributors, warning them against black-marketing tickets to ''Magadheera''. This was after local leaders, attempting to acquire a maximum number of tickets, blocked and booked tickets to the film in advance, to enthuse their supporters during the local civic polls in Guntur. Special teams of revenue, police and commercial tax officers were appointed to keep watch at ticket counters and  ensure that each person was issued only one ticket. Priority was ordered to be given for the sanitation, safety and comfort of the viewers.<ref name=\"Magadheera Krishna\" /> Authorities in Vijayawada ensured the strict checking and prevention of black-marketing of tickets. However, Ram Charan's fans resorted to sloganeering and an impromptu protest demonstration in the office of Revenue Divisional Officer K. Hymavathi in Machilipatnam. They demanded the screening of a benefit show and the advance sale of tickets after being rejected by the management of the twin theatres, Siri Venkata and Siri Krishna, where the film was screened. Their plea was rejected by the officer, who said that the tickets would be issued only to those who came in queue and that no special concessions would be made for fans.<ref name=\"Magadheera Krishna\" />\n\n=== Mishaps ===\nOn 9 August 2009, two persons, identified as [[National Institute of Technology|NIT]] student M. Praveen Kumar and Ganesh, were killed and 15 others sustained severe injuries after being electrocuted while jostling for tickets for ''Magadheera'' at the theatre Bhavani in [[Kazipet]], [[Warangal]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/two-electrocuted-at-warangal-theatre/article200332.ece |title=Two electrocuted at Warangal theatre |date=9 August 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=14 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114133347/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/two-electrocuted-at-warangal-theatre/article200332.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The screening of ''Magadheera'' at theatres in [[Vizianagaram]] was prohibited by the then minister [[Botsa Satyanarayana]] until safety measures were complied with. Satyanarayana's announcement followed the death of five people in Salur Village due to an electrical accident at the Lakshmi theatre screening ''Magadheera''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/article68764.ece |title=Botsa banishes Magadheera from home turf |date=12 August 2009 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=14 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114134059/http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/andhra_pradesh/article68764.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Accusation of plagiarism ===\nFolk lyricist [[Vangapandu Prasada Rao]] alleged that his 40-year-old folk song \"Em Pillado Eldamostavaa\", which was featured in [[T. Krishna]]'s ''Ardharathri Swatanthram'' (1986), was used by film director Rajamouli and Allu Aravind in the ''Magadheera'' song \"Jorsey\" without Rao's consent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/vangapandu-attacking-magadheera-song-telugu-news-48788 |title=Vangapandu Attacking 'Magadheera' Song |date=5 August 2009 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107161717/http://www.indiaglitz.com/vangapandu-attacking-magadheera-song-telugu-news-48788 |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Controversy-rages-over-Magadheera-song/articleshow/4861266.cms |title=Controversy rages over Magadheera song |date=6 August 2009 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107160740/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Controversy-rages-over-Magadheera-song/articleshow/4861266.cms |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> Activists of PDSU, POW and PYL staged a protest demonstration in front of the Ashok 70 MM theatre in Nizamabad, where the film was screened, to demand the removal of the song. The protesters said that the song was written by Rao during the famous Srikakulam armed struggle four decades prior and had been misused to portray an obscene duet in the film. They added that the song was used without the permission of the writer and that the depiction defeated the very purpose of the song, which was written in a revolutionary spirit. They demanded a public apology by the makers to Rao.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/protest-against-film-song/article198848.ece |title=Protest against film song |date=7 August 2009 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107160828/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/protest-against-film-song/article198848.ece |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref> A few reports stated that Rao demanded Aravind pay him compensation of {{INR}}5 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/vangapandu-magadheera-maker-170809.html |title=Vangapandu getting Rs.50 Lakh from Magadheera maker? |date=17 August 2009 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107161409/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/vangapandu-magadheera-maker-170809.html |archive-date=7 November 2014 |access-date=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter the completion of the film's 175-day run, novelist S. P. Chary accused the film of being based on a novel that he had written and published as a serial under the title ''Chanderi'' in a monthly magazine in 1998. He demanded that filmmakers compensate him for using his idea without consent, and threatened to take legal action if the producers did not heed his demands, or remade the film in another language. He added that he deserved to be credited for the story and alleged that [[Allu Arjun]] and [[Allu Sirish]] were trying to postpone his acknowledgment by discussing the issue with him.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/novelist-claims-magadheera-his-brain-child-telugu-news-54059 |title=Novelist claims 'Magadheera' his brain child |date=2 February 2010 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110061112/http://www.indiaglitz.com/novelist-claims-magadheera-his-brain-child-telugu-news-54059 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\n=== Home media ===\n''Magadheera'' was the first Telugu film in India to have a home media release in [[Blu-ray]] format. During the release announcement, Allu Sirish said that although they initially were reluctant to go for it, given the fact that there were approximately only 2500 Blu-ray devices in Andhra Pradesh, the overwhelming demand for it made him rethink the decision. He added, \"Sharing this vision with us was Sri Balaji Videos, the largest home-video label in Andhra Pradesh. Together, we're bringing out Magadheera on Blu-ray. Though Bhavani Videos released [[Akkineni Nagarjuna|Nagarjuna]]'s ''[[King (2008 film)|King]]'' (2008) on Blu-ray, it was only for the overseas market. This makes ''Magadheera'' the first Blu-ray film to be released in India and with a bonus disc with additional footage. We're also a holding a press event on this regard to officially announce the launch of the movie on DVD and Blu-ray.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/novelist-claims-magadheera-his-brain-child-telugu-news-54059 |title=Magadheera, finally on Blue-Ray |date=24 February 2010 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110151805/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-finally-on-blueray-telugu-news-54734 |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\nA press note announced that the DVDs would be available beginning the third week of March 2010 while the Blu-ray would be available two weeks later.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-release-blu-ray-240210.html |title=Magadheera to become the first Telugu Blu-Ray DVD |date=24 February 2010 |access-date=10 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141110152140/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-release-blu-ray-240210.html |archive-date=10 November 2014 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment}}</ref> The launch ceremony took place in a Marriott Hotel on 27 February 2010. The first DVD was released by M. M. Keeravani and was presented by journalist Pasupuleti Ramarao.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/bluray-magadheera.html |title=Magadheera Blu Ray DVD launch |date=28 February 2010 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606141453/http://www.idlebrain.com/news/functions/bluray-magadheera.html |archive-date=6 June 2015 |access-date=6 June 2015}}</ref> The DVD was released in [[NTSC]] video format and [[Dolby Digital#Dolby Digital Surround EX|Dolby Digital 5.1 surround]] audio format on 5 March 2010. The Blu-ray disc released on 13 April 2010. ''Magadheera'' held the top position in sales for its 720p Blu-ray edition with 5.1 Dolby digital sound format as of July 2014.<ref name=\"MGD 5 OI\" />\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nSuresh Krishnamoorthy of  ''[[The Hindu]]'' summarised, \"''Magadheera'' is not for the weak-hearted, those who do not like the sight of blood and neither is it for those who like movies with storylines that are much-closer-to-everyday- reality. But Rajamouli excels in story-telling. The way he has used the flashback as a flip switch, going back and forth and taking the viewer through a 400-year journey in a jiffy is interesting. The rest is about how well technology, creativity, imagination and innovation are leveraged to present what is an eye-pleasing experience for viewers.\"<ref name=\"The Hindu\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/a-visual-extravaganza-film-review/article194481.ece |title=A visual extravaganza Film Review |last=Krishnamoorthy |first=Suresh |date=1 August 2009 |work=The Hindu |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111154821/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-andhrapradesh/a-visual-extravaganza-film-review/article194481.ece |archive-date=11 November 2014}}</ref> B. V. S. Prakash of ''[[The Times of India]]'' wrote, \"Despite a few narrative lapses, the much-hyped semi-periodic epic lives up to expectations. Unlike his previous action-centric films, director Rajamouli dishes a heart-touching love story in a lavish canvas convincingly. Also kudos for the way he has visualised and presented the film.\" He added, \"After not-so-impressive ''Chirutha'', Ram Charan Tej returns as a valiant soldier and breathes life into the larger-than-life role with ease. Similarly, Kajal known for simple lover girl roles transforms into a determined princess and truly impresses. Dev Gil is adequate as the ruthless villain\", and rated the film 3 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/telugu/movie-reviews/Magadheera/movie-review/4848642.cms |title=Magadheera Movie Review |last=Prakash |first=B. V. S. |date=3 August 2009 |work=The Times of India |access-date=11 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105170348/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/telugu/movie-reviews/Magadheera/movie-review/4848642.cms |archive-date=5 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Oneindia.in|Oneindia Entertainment]] stated, \"S. S. Rajamouli has chosen a fantastic love story for his movie Magadheera and linked it to a love story that dated back to some 400 years. He has filled complete energy in the film and no doubt, the graphic works and modern technology are perfectly used for the movie. As a whole, the film reminds the audiences of watching a Hollywood movie with perfect local flavor\", and called the film's screenplay by Rajamouli a highlight.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/reviews/2009/magadheera-review-010809.html |title=Magadheera&nbsp;\u2014 Review |date=1 August 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111155240/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/reviews/2009/magadheera-review-010809.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment}}</ref> Upperstall.com stated \"Magadheera is not an epic, not a legend, not even a cult movie, but it is certainly an artistic extravaganza and a sensory treat. Like we said before, a must watch! A mast watch!\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.upperstall.com/films/2009/magadheera |title=Magadheera Review |date=31 July 2009 |access-date=9 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109094336/http://www.upperstall.com/films/2009/magadheera |archive-date=9 January 2015 |publisher=Upperstall.com}}</ref>\n\nRadhika Rajamani of [[Rediff.com]] called the film \"technically brilliant\" and wrote \"A reincarnation story is not often seen in Telugu cinema and SS Rajamouli uses this theme for Ram Charan Teja's second film Magadheera. It's a magnum opus production with great technical work. The graphics are excellent for a Telugu movie. Overall, the movie is a mainstream one with good packaging.\" She rated the film 3 out of 5.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/review/2009/jul/31/the-magadheera-review.htm |title=Magadheera is technically brilliant |date=31 July 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111155453/http://movies.rediff.com/review/2009/jul/31/the-magadheera-review.htm |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref> [[Sify]] called the film a \"brilliant entertainer\" and wrote, \"Set against the backdrop of an eerie theme&nbsp;\u2014 reincarnation&nbsp;\u2014 Magadheera unfolds on the screen with multiple shades of entertainment. When the movie was launched last year, director Rajamouli dared to reveal the central theme of the story. He has succeeded in his attempt, as he was able to keep the screenplay and narration gripping from start to finish. The second half has the soul in it.\" Sify summarised, \"In short, the movie encompasses some of the best commercial elements that Telugu audience have seen in the recent past.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-review-telugu-14902427.html |title=Movie Review : Magadheera |date=1 August 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111173514/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-review-telugu-14902427.html |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref>\n\nIndiaGlitz called the film \"royal and spellbinding\" and opined, \"The film deserves a special credit for many reasons, notable among them is the grandeur of the movie and the amazing technical aspects. This is surely a path breaker in terms of Telugu film making and with the likes of 'Arundhati', Tollywood sure is proud to have this one in its league. It is a valiant attempt to bring such genre to the modern day audience and present it with finesse so that it fits the historical angle and the today's angle.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-review-telugu-movie-review-11250 |title=Magadheera Review&nbsp;\u2014 Royal and spellbinding |date=31 July 2009 |access-date=11 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111173613/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-review-telugu-movie-review-11250 |archive-date=11 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> However, Rajamouli was accused of lifting scenes from films like ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' (2000), ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004), ''[[The Myth (film)|The Myth]]'' (2005) and ''[[300 (film)|300]]'' (2007).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Is-Rajamouli-a-skilled-copycat/articleshow/25953750.cms |title=Is Rajamouli a skilled copycat? |date=17 November 2013 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114135446/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Is-Rajamouli-a-skilled-copycat/articleshow/25953750.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\nThe film collected a share of approximately {{INRConvert|200|m}} in its first week in [[Andhra Pradesh]] alone, of which a share of {{INRConvert|71|m}} was collected in Nizam region.<ref name=\"200 m\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-20cr-firstweek-070809.html |title=Magadheera grosses Rs 20 cr in first week |date=7 August 2009 |website=[[Oneindia]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109105742/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2009/magadheera-20cr-firstweek-070809.html |archive-date=9 November 2014 |access-date=9 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-1stweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 20 crores |date=7 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112134412/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-1stweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> Sixteen centres collected {{INRConvert|10|m}}, each of which was an all-time state record.<ref name=\"MGD 100\">{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/nov/12/south-report-magadheera-not-out.htm |title=Magadheera, 100 not out! |date=12 November 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112144930/http://movies.rediff.com/report/2009/nov/12/south-report-magadheera-not-out.htm |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref> It collected a share of {{INRConvert|381.5|m}} in 21 days in Andhra Pradesh.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-3rdweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 38.51 crores in 3 weeks in AP |date=26 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112134814/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-3rdweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> By the end of its four-week run, the film was declared a blockbuster and collected a share of {{INRConvert|435.6|m}} in 28 days and {{INRConvert|470.8|m}} in 35 days.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-4thweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 43.56 crores in 4 weeks in AP |date=31 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112134636/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-4thweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-5thweekshare.html |title=Magadheera collects a share of 47.08 crores in 5 weeks in AP |date=8 September 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112135010/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-5thweekshare.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> The film completed a 50-day run in 302 centres on 18 September 2009. By then, the film had collected {{INRConvert|650|m}} and stood strong.<ref name=\"MGD 175\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-completes-175-days-news-telugu-kkfqXWfddabsi.html |title=Magadheera completes 175 days |date=23 January 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112140118/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadheera-completes-175-days-news-telugu-kkfqXWfddabsi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-celebrates-50-days---malayalam-news-50106 |title='Magadheera' celebrates 50 days!!! |date=19 September 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112140820/http://www.indiaglitz.com/-magadheera-celebrates-50-days---malayalam-news-50106 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\nThe film completed its 100-day run in 223 centres. By then it had surpassed [[Rajinikanth]]'s ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' (2007), which grossed {{INRConvert|650|m}} in [[Tamil Nadu]], and stood second to ''Ghajini'' (2008), which reached {{INRConvert|2|b}}.<ref name=\"MGD 100\" /> The film completed a 175-day run in 3 centres and, by then, collected a share of {{INRConvert|580|m}}.<ref name=\"MGD 175\" /> The film completed a 365-day run in Vijayalakshmi theatre in [[Kurnool]] on 31 July 2010 and a 1000-day run in the same theatre on 26 April 2012.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/aug/05/slide-show-1-south-telugu-snippets.htm |title=Magadheera runs non-stop for 365 days |date=5 August 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112145924/http://movies.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/aug/05/slide-show-1-south-telugu-snippets.htm |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Rediff.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Magadheera-1000-days-poster/articleshow/13608953.cms |title=Magadheera 1000 day\u2019s poster |date=28 May 2012 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112150032/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/Magadheera-1000-days-poster/articleshow/13608953.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nMore than 50% of the film's lifetime collections were from the Nizam region.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Nizam-territory-will-remain-indispensable-for-Tollywood/articleshow/21499426.cms |title=Nizam territory will remain indispensable for Tollywood |date=31 July 2013 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112151416/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Nizam-territory-will-remain-indispensable-for-Tollywood/articleshow/21499426.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The film also did well in the overseas box office. It was released in [[New Jersey]] with three prints on three screens and collected a record share of more than 150,000 dollars, turning the highest amount raised overseas by a Telugu film; the previous record holder was [[Trivikram Srinivas]]' ''[[Jalsa]]'' (2008), which collected more than 100,000 dollars. It grossed 102,000 dollars in its first two days in New Jersey and a share of 95,000 dollars in [[Virginia]] with two prints as of mid August 2009. It collected a share of 78,000 dollars in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] with a single print. It managed to sell 2300 tickets in [[Minneapolis]]; the previous record for tickets sold there for a Telugu film was 1200.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-bozofficelegend.html |title=Magadheera&nbsp;\u2013 a box office legend |date=17 August 2009 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112151152/http://www.idlebrain.com/trade/magadheera-bozofficelegend.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Idlebrain.com}}</ref> The film's overseas records were beaten two years later by ''[[Dookudu]]'' (2011), although disputes have arisen over which film holds the Tollywood all-time sales record.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/dookudu-vs-magadheera-news-news-llqmdIaijagsi.html |title=Dookudu vs. Magadheera |date=16 November 2011 |access-date=26 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141126041846/http://www.sify.com/movies/dookudu-vs-magadheera-news-news-llqmdIaijagsi.html |archive-date=26 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref>\n\nThe film was dubbed in Japanese and released there in 2018. This version earned an additional $1.2 million, the second highest for an Indian film after ''[[Muthu (1995 film)|Muthu]]'' (1995), which earned $1.6 million after being released in Japan.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/regional-movies/ss-rajamouli-s-magadheera-starring-ram-charan-opens-to-packed-house-in-japan/story-LBXNpg3D5ZOfwLUcl5h4LI.html |title=SS Rajamouli\u2019s Magadheera, starring Ram Charan, opens to packed house in Japan |date=5 September 2018 |work=[[Hindustan Times]] |access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n''Magadheera'''s success turned Kajal into one of the most sought-after actresses in Telugu cinema and catapulted her into the foray of leading Telugu actresses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/53748.html |title='Magadheera' earns 175 successful days! |date=21 January 2010 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113083214/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/53748.html |archive-date=13 November 2014 |access-date=13 November 2014}}</ref> The film was also considered a fate changer in the career of Ram Charan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/will-yevadu-be-another-magadheera/article4929256.ece |title=Will \u2018Yevadu\u2019 be another \u2018Magadheera\u2019? |last=IANS |date=19 July 2013 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114052812/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/will-yevadu-be-another-magadheera/article4929256.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The role of Sher Khan played by Srihari was considered as one of the best roles in his career and also catapulted S. S. Rajamouli to stardom.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/regional/magadheera-completes-five-years-rajamouli-gets-nostalgic/article1-1247091.aspx |title=Magadheera completes five years, Rajamouli gets nostalgic |date=1 August 2014 |website=[[Hindustan Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114053215/http://www.hindustantimes.com/entertainment/regional/magadheera-completes-five-years-rajamouli-gets-nostalgic/article1-1247091.aspx |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Dev Gill attained stardom with this film and went on to work in several South Indian films as an antagonist. After the release of ''Magadheera'', people began recognising him as Ranadheer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hyderabad-gave-him-everything/article2764374.ece |title=Hyderabad gave him everything |last=Chowdhary |first=Y. Sunita |date=1 January 2012 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114093055/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/hyderabad-gave-him-everything/article2764374.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> According to writer [[Gopimohan]], ''Magadheera'' started a trend of experimentation with period, socio-fantasy and spiritual themes that was continued in films like ''[[Panchakshari]]'' (2010), ''[[Nagavalli (film)|Nagavalli]]'' (2010), ''[[Anaganaga O Dheerudu]]'' (2011), ''Mangala'' (2011), ''[[Sri Rama Rajyam]]'' (2011) and ''[[Uu Kodathara? Ulikki Padathara?]]'' (2012).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/article358499.ece |title=Old genres, new packaging! |date=5 September 2011 |website=The New Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114054205/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/telugu/article358499.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe props used in this film, including weapons like swords and shields, were auctioned by Movie Artist Association. Actors, technicians, and the general public were invited to bid and the proceeds were used to aid poor artists in the Telugu film industry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-weapons-to-be-auctioned-telugu-news-56817 |title=Magadheera Weapons To Be Auctioned |date=8 May 2010 |publisher=IndiaGlitz |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114093734/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-weapons-to-be-auctioned-telugu-news-56817 |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Actor [[Sivaji Raja]] started the bidding by offering {{INR}}50,000 for the sword that Ram Charan used and comedian [[Venu Madhav (actor)|Venu Madhav]] started the bidding for the shield with {{INR}}25,000. B. V. S. N. Prasad bid for both the sword and knife for {{INR}}100,000. The bidding started on 7 May 2010 online in the association's official website and ended on 16 May. The winners were declared on 20 May 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-maa-auction-100510.html |title=Magadheera's swords and shields are on auction |date=10 May 2010 |publisher=Oneindia Entertainment |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114094206/http://www.filmibeat.com/telugu/news/2010/magadheera-maa-auction-100510.html |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> After ''Magadheera'', S. S. Rajamouli worked on a small budget film ''[[Maryada Ramanna]]'' (2010) which, according to [[Crazy Mohan]], was similar to the act of [[S. S. Vasan]] directing the small budget film ''[[Mr. Sampat]]'' (1952) after ''[[Chandralekha (1948 film)|Chandralekha]]'' (1948).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/buzzing-like-crazy/article3291780.ece |title=Buzzing like crazy |last=Rangrajan |first=Malathi |date=8 April 2012 |website=The Hindu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114104741/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-cinemaplus/buzzing-like-crazy/article3291780.ece |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Rajamouli explained his decision by saying, \"I decided that my next project would be ''Maryada Ramanna'' during the ''Magadheera'' shooting itself because it is a 1 and half year project that demands lot of physical labor and mental strain. I didn't want to commit another physically exhausting film immediately after ''Magadheera''. ''Maryada Ramanna'' gave us time to recharge our batteries so that we could come up with another huge project.\" He revealed ''Maryada Ramanna''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s plot before its launch to minimise the expectations of his audience after ''Magadheera''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s success.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/ssrajamouli-maryadaramanna.html |title=Interview with SS Rajamouli |date=20 July 2010 |publisher=Idlebrain.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114105429/http://www.idlebrain.com/celeb/interview/ssrajamouli-maryadaramanna.html |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Tammareddy Bharadwaja]] said \"Ever since ''Arundhati'' and ''Magadheera'' did well at the box office, the rest of the industry started following their footsteps. Also, since there is an irrational craze to make high budget films right now, producers are turning towards mythological films. It is the only genre where you can boast of spending crores for creating the sets and the look of the film. But what they don't realize is that if these films flop, the blow to the producer will be severe.\" Films like ''Anaganaga O Dheerudu'' (2011) and ''[[Shakti (2011 film)|Shakti]]'' (2011) were commercial failures and ''[[Badrinath (film)|Badrinath]]'' (2012) was an average grosser; all being fantasy films in which the protagonist is a warrior.<ref name=\"resemblance\">{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Mythological-characters-a-hit-in-T-town/articleshow/8207023.cms |title=Mythological characters, a hit in T-town |last=Bhat |first=Prashanth |date=10 May 2011 |work=The Times of India |access-date=19 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219080236/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Mythological-characters-a-hit-in-T-town/articleshow/8207023.cms |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Badrinath-completes-50days-in-187-theatres/articleshow/9466159.cms |title=Badrinath completes 50days in 187 theatres |date=3 August 2011 |work=The Times of India |access-date=19 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219080609/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/others/news-interviews/Badrinath-completes-50days-in-187-theatres/articleshow/9466159.cms |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> The promos of ''Badrinath'' looked similar to ''Magadheera'' and the former's director [[V. V. Vinayak]] along with its male lead [[Allu Arjun]] kept insisting that ''Badrinath'' is dissimilar to ''Magadheera''. Producer Natti Kumar said \"If a hero delivers a hit, producers run after him for five years and burn their fingers only after six or eight flops. It's the same story with movies. Since ''Magadheera'' became a hit, every other hero and director wants to do period film where there is scope to spend crores. They don't work on the script, story or relevance. It is a pure display of graphics, heroes' abs and grandeur. The plot is lost. ''Magadheera'' worked because it was a novel genre then, but why will people want to see the same things again?\".<ref name=\"resemblance\" />\n\n[[Janani Iyer]] cited the character of Mithravinda played by Kajal in the film as one of her dream roles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/in-spotlight/article4003989.ece |title=In spotlight |last=Jeshi |first=K. |date=17 October 2012 |work=The Hindu |access-date=19 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219081543/http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/in-spotlight/article4003989.ece |archive-date=19 December 2014}}</ref> [[Ram Gopal Varma]] refused to call ''Magadheera'' a film and instead termed it as an event that comes \"once in a blue moon\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-envisons-a-New-Telugu-Film-Industry/articleshow/39348963.cms |title=RGV envisons a New Telugu Film Industry |date=31 July 2010 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114105857/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-envisons-a-New-Telugu-Film-Industry/articleshow/39348963.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> While commenting on [[Mahesh Babu]]'s ''[[Aagadu]]'' (2014), he said that ''Magadheera'' looked like a 750 [[crore]] film when compared to ''Aagadu'' if the latter was a 75 crore film and added, \"My comparison between \"''Aagadu''\" and \"''Magadheera''\" is mainly because they both are the most expensive films for their own individual times.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-taunts-Mahesh-Babus-Aagadu/articleshow/42919785.cms |title=RGV taunts Mahesh Babu's Aagadu |last=Pasupulate |first=Karthik |date=19 September 2014 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114110208/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movies/news/RGV-taunts-Mahesh-Babus-Aagadu/articleshow/42919785.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> Reviewing the Tamil film ''[[Anegan]]'' (2014), few critics opined that the film had traces of ''Magadheera'' mainly due to the theme of reincarnation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Anegan/movie-review/46236503.cms |title=Anegan Movie Review |date=13 February 2015 |work=The Times of India |access-date=20 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6aA4dsVt3?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movie-reviews/Anegan/movie-review/46236503.cms |archive-date=20 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/anegan-review-welcome-back-karthik-you-are-in-a-love-story-in-2015-wait-dhanush-is-the-hero-who-are-you-in-the-film-then-967225.html |title='Anegan' review: Welcome back Karthik! You are in a love story in 2015? Wait. Dhanush is the hero? Who are you in the film then? |date=14 February 2015 |access-date=20 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720111827/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/movies/anegan-review-welcome-back-karthik-you-are-in-a-love-story-in-2015-wait-dhanush-is-the-hero-who-are-you-in-the-film-then-967225.html |archive-date=20 July 2015 |publisher=CNN-IBN}}</ref> The Tamil dubbed version of the Telugu film ''[[Yevadu]]'' (2014), which featured Charan in one of the lead roles and Kajal in a crucial cameo, was titled ''Magadheera''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.andhrajyothy.com/Artical?SID=128134&SupID=24 |title=\u2018\u0c2e\u0c17\u0c27\u0c40\u0c30\u2019\u0c17\u0c3e \u0c35\u0c38\u0c4d\u0c24\u0c41\u0c28\u0c4d\u0c28 \u2018\u0c0e\u0c35\u0c21\u0c41\u2019 |date=10 July 2015 |work=[[Andhra Jyothy]] |access-date=20 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150720112159/http://www.andhrajyothy.com/Artical?SID=128134&SupID=24 |archive-date=20 July 2015 |language=Telugu |trans-title='Yevadu' as 'Magadheera'}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\nThe film won the [[National Film Awards|National Award]] for [[National Film Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]] and [[National Film Award for Best Special Effects|Best Special Effects]] at the [[57th National Film Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Magadheera-bags-best-spl-effects-choreography-awards/articleshow/6562319.cms |title=`Magadheera' bags best spl effects, choreography awards' |date=15 September 2010 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052254/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Magadheera-bags-best-spl-effects-choreography-awards/articleshow/6562319.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The film also won six [[57th Filmfare Awards South|Filmfare Awards]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sify.com/movies/magadhera-wins-6-filmfare-awards-news-telugu-kkguRAfifbbsi.html |title=Magadhera wins 6 Filmfare awards |date=9 August 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052048/http://www.sify.com/movies/magadhera-wins-6-filmfare-awards-news-telugu-kkguRAfifbbsi.html |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=Sify}}</ref> nine [[Nandi Awards]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-sweeps-nandi-awards-telugu-news-60632 |title='Magadheera' Sweeps Nandi Awards |date=7 October 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052352/http://www.indiaglitz.com/magadheera-sweeps-nandi-awards-telugu-news-60632 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> and ten [[CineMAA Awards]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/cine-maa-awards-10--magadheera-grabs-it-all-telugu-news-59471 |title=Cine'Maa' Awards'10: 'Magadheera' grabs it all |date=18 August 2010 |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112131605/http://www.indiaglitz.com/cine-maa-awards-10--magadheera-grabs-it-all-telugu-news-59471 |archive-date=12 November 2014 |publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref>\n\n== Remakes ==\nRam Charan decided not to debut in [[Bollywood]] with ''Magadheera''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Hindi]] remake, as he believed the film might not be recreated well. In an interview with ''[[The Times of India]]'', Charan said, \"When I met [[Anil Kapoor]] some time back, he told me I will ask [[Boney Kapoor]] to remake ''Magadheera'' with you in Hindi. But I said I don't know if I would want to do the remake. ''Magadheera'' is a lovely film which can't be recreated.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Why-Ram-Charan-didnt-debut-with-Magadheera-remake/articleshow/12934631.cms |title=Why Ram Charan didn't debut with Magadheera remake? |date=30 April 2012 |website=The Times of India |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114134803/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Why-Ram-Charan-didnt-debut-with-Magadheera-remake/articleshow/12934631.cms |archive-date=14 November 2014 |access-date=14 November 2014}}</ref> The film was remade in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] as ''[[Yoddha: The Warrior]]'' in 2014; it was directed by [[Raj Chakraborty]] with [[Dev (Bengali actor)|Dev]] and [[Mimi Chakraborty]] playing the lead roles.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/movies/news/Shopping-mall-or-railway-station-Dev-gets-mobbed-everywhere-Raj-Chakrabarty/articleshow/44947373.cms |title=Shopping mall or railway station, Dev gets mobbed everywhere: Raj Chakrabarty |last=Ganguly |first=Ruman |date=27 October 2014 |work=The Times of India |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112042143/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bengali/movies/news/Shopping-mall-or-railway-station-Dev-gets-mobbed-everywhere-Raj-Chakrabarty/articleshow/44947373.cms |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref> The 2014 [[Kannada]] film ''[[Brahma (2014 film)|Brahma]]'', according to its director [[R. Chandru]], was inspired by ''Magadheera'' but was not a remake.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bangalore/Chandru-Uppi-team-up-for-Brahma/2013/05/07/article1577938.ece |title=Chandru-Uppi team up for Brahma |date=7 May 2013 |work=The New Indian Express |access-date=12 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112042755/http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/bangalore/Chandru-Uppi-team-up-for-Brahma/2013/05/07/article1577938.ece |archive-date=12 November 2014}}</ref><!-- In August 2014, [[Shahid Kapoor]] expressed his desire to reprise Ram Charan's role in a Hindi remake saying, \"I have been wanting to do ''Magadheera'' for the longest. I have seen the film and loved it.....I think it\u2019s a killer subject.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/shahid-kapoor-keen-to-do-magadheera-remake/ |title=Shahid Kapoor keen to do Magadheera remake |date=22 August 2014 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=22 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141122124329/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/screen/shahid-kapoor-keen-to-do-magadheera-remake/ |archive-date=22 November 2014}}</ref> In late November 2014, [[Sajid Nadiadwala]] confirmed that he would direct the film's Hindi remake with Kapoor as the lead.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sajid-nadiadwala-denies-sequel-to-salman-khans-kick-confirms-magadheera-remake-with-shahid-kapoor/ |title=Sajid Nadiadwala denies sequel to Salman Khan\u2019s \u2018Kick\u2019, confirms \u2018Magadheera\u2019 remake with Shahid Kapoor |date=21 November 2014 |work=The Indian Express |access-date=22 November 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141122124602/http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/sajid-nadiadwala-denies-sequel-to-salman-khans-kick-confirms-magadheera-remake-with-shahid-kapoor/ |archive-date=22 November 2014}}</ref> When asked by Subhash K. Jha the reason for not directing the Hindi remake, Rajamouli said \"I've already spent two years of my life on it. I\u2019d rather make something else. ''Magadheera'' was my toughest film to make. Very tiring.\"<ref name=\"Subhash Jha\" /> By June 2016, Kapoor was no longer part of the Hindi remake.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-ll-be-unemployed-after-rangoon-shahid-kapoor-2223790 |title=I\u2019ll be unemployed after Rangoon: Shahid Kapoor |last=Rakshit |first=Nayandeep |date=15 June 2016 |website=Daily News and Analysis |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830142326/http://www.dnaindia.com/entertainment/report-i-ll-be-unemployed-after-rangoon-shahid-kapoor-2223790 |archive-date=30 August 2016 |access-date=21 August 2016}}</ref> --> The film was dubbed in Hindi under the same name by Goldmines Telefilms and released in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WAR8aa462kg |title=Magadheera 2015 Hindi Dubbed Movie With Telugu Songs |date=9 July 2015 |publisher=Goldmines Movies |access-date=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book|last=Chinnarayana|first=Pulagam|url=http://s1056.photobucket.com/user/PavanJandhyala/library/Magadheera?sort=3&page=1|title=\u0c27\u0c40\u0c30... \u0c27\u0c40\u0c30... \u0c27\u0c40\u0c30... \u0c2e\u0c28\u0c38\u0c3e\u0c17 \u0c32\u0c47\u0c26\u0c41\u0c30\u0c3e!|trans-title=O brave one... my heart can't wait any longer|language=Telugu|date=2 August 2015|work=[[Sakshi (newspaper)|Sakshi]]|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Rinki Roy|last=Bhattacharya|title=Bimal Roy's Madhumati: Untold Stories from Behind the Scenes|year=2014|publisher=Rupa Publications|isbn=978-8129129161|ref=harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1447500|Magadheera}}\n\n{{National Film Award Best Special Effects|state=collapsed}}\n{{Nandi Award for Best Popular Feature Film}}\n{{Filmfare Best Telugu Film}}\n{{S. S. Rajamouli}}\n{{K. Bhagyaraj}}\n[[Category:2000s action adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s action films]]\n[[Category:2000s romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:2000s Telugu-language films]]\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:Indian fantasy action films]]\n[[Category:Indian fantasy adventure films]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:Films directed by S. S. Rajamouli]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Choreography National Film Award-winning choreography]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Films involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:Films scored by M. M. Keeravani]]\n[[Category:Films set in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Ramoji Film City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Special Effects National Film Award]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Indian action adventure films]]\n[[Category:Indian action drama films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian romantic fantasy films]]\n[[Category:Masala films]]\n[[Category:Telugu films remade in other languages]]\n[[Category:Telugu-language films]]\n", "name_user": "106.51.240.80", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magadheera"}
{"title_page": "Google Play Games", "text_new": "{{short description|Online gaming service}}\n{{Infobox  software\n| logo = Google Play Games.png\n| logo_alt = Green gamepad inside of a green triangle, used to distinguish the Google Play Games service\n| logo size = 150px\n| developer = [[Google]]\n| screenshot = Play Games app.png\n| screenshot alt = Screenshot of Google Play Games\n| caption = The [[user interface]] of Google Play Games in dark mode\n| collapsible = yes\n| platform = [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|2013|07|24}}\n| ver layout = stacked\n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| genre = Online service\n| website = {{URL|https://play.google.com/store/apps/category/GAME|Google Play Games on the Play Store}}\n}}\n'''Google Play Games''' is an [[Online game|online gaming]] service and [[software development kit]] operated by [[Google]], part of its [[Google Play]] product line, for the [[Android (operating system)|Android operating system]]. It features gamer profiles, [[Cloud storage|cloud saves]], social and public leaderboards, [[Achievement (video gaming)|achievements]], and real-time [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer gaming]] capabilities.<ref>{{cite web |first=Greg |last=Hartrell |title=Unlocking the Power of Google for Your Games, at GDC |url=https://android-developers.googleblog.com/2014/03/unlocking-power-of-google-for-your_17.html |website=Android Developers Blog |publisher=Google |date=March 17, 2014 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> The Play Games service allows developers to incorporate the above features into their games without having to develop those features from scratch themselves.\n\n==History==\nThe Google Play Games service was introduced at the [[Google I/O]] 2013 Developer Conference,<ref name=\"Announcement\">{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Webster |title=Google announces Play game services, Android's cross-platform answer to Game Center |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/5/15/4327880/google-announces-android-game-center-competitor |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=Vox Media |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> and the standalone Google Play Games [[mobile app]] was launched for Android on July 24, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nathan |last=Ingraham |title=Google takes on Game Center with Google Play Games for Android |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4553190/google-play-games-app-for-android-will-be-available-today |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=Vox Media |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Andrew Webster of ''[[The Verge]]'' compared Google Play Games to [[Game Center]], a similar gaming network for users of [[Apple Inc.]]'s own [[iOS]] operating system.<ref name=\"Announcement\"/>\n\nGoogle Play Games has received updates over the years since its launch, including a screen-recording feature,<ref>{{cite web |first=Duncan |last=Curtis |title=Google Play Games: capture and share the moment |url=https://android.googleblog.com/2015/10/google-play-games-capture-and-share.html |website=Official Android Blog |publisher=Google |date=October 28, 2015 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> custom gamer [[Identifier|IDs]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Benjamin |last=Frenkel |title=Embrace your inner gaming hero with Gamer ID |url=https://blog.google/products/google-play/embrace-your-inner-gaming-hero-with/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 18, 2016 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> built-in games, and an arcade for game discovery.\n\nReal-time and turn-based multiplayer services have been deprecated since September 16, 2019. Support for these API functions ended on March 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |title=Ending support for multiplayer APIs in Play Games Services |url=https://support.google.com/googleplay/android-developer/answer/9469745 |website=Play Console Help |publisher=Google}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Google Inc.}}\n{{Major video game companies}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:Google software|Play Games]]\n[[Category:Google Play|Games]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 software]]\n\n{{Google-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Online gaming service}}\n{{Infobox  software\n| logo = Google Play Games.png\n| logo_alt = Green gamepad inside of a green triangle, used to distinguish the Google Play Games service\n| logo size = 150px\n| developer = [[Google]]\n| screenshot = Play Games app.png\n| screenshot alt = Screenshot of Google Play Games\n| caption = The [[user interface]] of Google Play Games in dark mode\n| collapsible = yes\n| platform = [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| released = {{Start date and age|2013|07|24}}\n| ver layout = stacked\n| operating system = [[Android (operating system)|Android]]\n| genre = Online service\n| website = {{URL|https://play.google.com/store/apps/category/GAME|Google Play Games on the Play Store}}\n}}\n'''Google Play Games''' is an [[Online game|online gaming]] service and [[software development kit]] operated by [[Google]], part of its [[Google Play]] product line, for the [[Android (operating system)|Android operating system]]. It features gamer profiles, [[Cloud storage|cloud saves]], social and public leaderboards, [[Achievement (video gaming)|achievements]], and real-time [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer gaming]] capabilities.<ref>{{cite web |first=Greg |last=Hartrell |title=Unlocking the Power of Google for Your Games, at GDC |url=https://android-developers.googleblog.com/2014/03/unlocking-power-of-google-for-your_17.html |website=Android Developers Blog |publisher=Google |date=March 17, 2014 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> The Play Games service allows developers to incorporate the above features into their games without having to develop those features from scratch themselves.\n\n==History==\nThe Google Play Games service was introduced at the [[Google I/O]] 2013 Developer Conference,<ref name=\"Announcement\">{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Webster |title=Google announces Play game services, Android's cross-platform answer to Game Center |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/5/15/4327880/google-announces-android-game-center-competitor |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=Vox Media |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> and the standalone Google Play Games [[mobile app]] was launched for Android on July 24, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nathan |last=Ingraham |title=Google takes on Game Center with Google Play Games for Android |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4553190/google-play-games-app-for-android-will-be-available-today |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=Vox Media |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> Andrew Webster of ''[[The Verge]]'' compared Google Play Games to [[Game Center]], a similar gaming network for users of [[Apple Inc.]]'s own [[iOS]] operating system.<ref name=\"Announcement\"/>\n\nGoogle Play Games has received updates over the years since its launch, including a screen-recording feature,<ref>{{cite web |first=Duncan |last=Curtis |title=Google Play Games: capture and share the moment |url=https://android.googleblog.com/2015/10/google-play-games-capture-and-share.html |website=Official Android Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=October 28, 2015 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> custom gamer [[Identifier|IDs]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Benjamin |last=Frenkel |title=Embrace your inner gaming hero with Gamer ID |url=https://blog.google/products/google-play/embrace-your-inner-gaming-hero-with/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |publisher=[[Google]] |date=February 18, 2016 |accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> built-in games, and an arcade for game discovery.\n\nReal-time and turn-based multiplayer services have been deprecated since September 16, 2019. Support for these API functions will end on March 31, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |title=Ending support for multiplayer APIs in Play Games Services |url=https://support.google.com/googleplay/android-developer/answer/9469745 |website=Play Console Help |publisher=Google}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Google Inc.}}\n{{Major video game companies}}\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system) software]]\n[[Category:Google software|Play Games]]\n[[Category:Google Play|Games]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 software]]\n\n{{Google-stub}}\n", "name_user": "The Grid", "label": "safe", "comment": "change tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_Play_Games"}
{"title_page": "Alago language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Alago\n|nativename=''Idoma Noku''\n|region=[[Nassarawa State]]\n|states=Nigeria\n|speakers={{sigfig|351000|2}}\n|date=2000\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Niger-Congo\n|fam2=[[Atlantic\u2013Congo]]\n|fam3=[[Volta\u2013Niger]]\n|fam4={{sm|noi}}\n|fam5=[[Idomoid languages|Idomoid]]\n|fam6=Etulo\u2013Idoma\n|fam7=Idoma\n|iso3=ala\n|glotto=alag1242\n|glottorefname=Alago\n}}\n'''Alago''', or '''Idoma Nokwu''', is an [[Idomoid language]] of [[Nigeria]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Volta-Niger languages}}\n[[Category:Idomoid languages]]\n\n\n{{VoltaNiger-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Alago\n|nativename=Idoma Noku\n|region=[[Nassarawa State]]\n|states=Nigeria\n|speakers={{sigfig|351000|2}}\n|date=2000\n|ref=e18\n|familycolor=Niger-Congo\n|fam2=[[Atlantic\u2013Congo]]\n|fam3=[[Volta\u2013Niger]]\n|fam4={{sm|noi}}\n|fam5=[[Idomoid languages|Idomoid]]\n|fam6=Etulo\u2013Idoma\n|fam7=Idoma\n|iso3=ala\n|glotto=alag1242\n|glottorefname=Alago\n}}\n'''Alago''', or '''Idoma Nokwu''', is an [[Idomoid language]] of [[Nigeria]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Volta-Niger languages}}\n[[Category:Idomoid languages]]\n\n\n{{VoltaNiger-lang-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Liggliluff", "label": "safe", "comment": "nativename in cursive", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alago_language"}
{"title_page": "Vansire", "text_new": "{{short description|American dream pop/bedroom pop band}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Vansire\n| image            = Vansire.jpg\n| caption          = Winemiller and Augustin in 2018\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| genre            = {{Flatlist|\n* [[dream pop]]<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\"></ref>\n* [[bedroom pop]]\n* [[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]\n}}\n| years_active     = {{start date|2015}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* Spirit Goth Records\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|FLOOR CRY|Chester Watson|[[sophie meiers]]|[[Jeremiah Jae]]|[[MED (rapper)|MED]]|Mellow Fellow}}\n| website          = {{url|https://vansire.bandcamp.com|Bandcamp}}\n| current_members  = * Josh Augustin\n* Sam Winemiller\n}}\n'''Vansire''' is a [[dream pop]] band from Rochester, Minnesota consisting of Josh Augustin and Sam Winemiller. The band has performed at ROCKChester,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/opinion/our-view-rockchester-music-festival-showcases-city-s-young-talent/article_af844788-9860-575f-a546-fce3744cd0b3.html|title=Our View: ROCKchester music festival showcases city's young talent|date=14 May 2016|work=Post Bulletin|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and has done a live session with [[Audiotree]].<ref name=\"VansireAudioTree\">{{Cite web|url=https://midwestaxn.com/music/watch-this-vansire-on-audiotree-live/|title=Watch This: Vansire on Audiotree Live|last=Welch|first=Alyssa|date=29 August 2019|website=Midwest Action|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n===Formation===\nVansire formed as band members Josh Augustin (vocals, synths, guitar, and drums) and Sam Winemiller (bass, guitar, and synths) were attending [[Century High School (Rochester, Minnesota)|Century High School]] in Rochester, Minnesota.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/magazines/507/rockchester-festival-highlights-our-city-s-young-musicians/article_cc66f666-67f1-11e7-99ac-5f980a51efda.html|title=ROCKchester festival highlights our city's young musicians|last=Colby|first=Claire|date=13 July 2017|website=Post Bulletin|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714023530/https://www.postbulletin.com/magazines/507/rockchester-festival-highlights-our-city-s-young-musicians/article_cc66f666-67f1-11e7-99ac-5f980a51efda.html|archive-date=14 July 2017|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Augustin and Winemiller met while playing together on the school's [[drumline]] and continued to find themselves performing together through school activities (such as concert band and pit orchestra), something the duo says contributed to their creative synergy and friendship, which later helped in Vansire's formation.<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\"></ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015, Winemiller approached Augustin after practice for the school's drumline with an idea to make a band \"that sounds like [[Mac DeMarco|Mac [DeMarco]]]\". The pair's early recordings were made by holding instruments to the internal microphone of an [[iPad]] running [[GarageBand]].<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oberlin.edu/news/qa-vansire-cofounder-josh-augustin-20|title=Q&A with Vansire Cofounder Josh Augustin \u201920|last=Jones|first=Ben|date=7 December 2018|website=Oberlin College and Conservatory|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224080520/https://www.oberlin.edu/news/qa-vansire-cofounder-josh-augustin-20|archive-date=24 February 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Augustin and Winemiller, initially unsure of what to call their new project, turned to an online random word generator which landed on \"vansire\",<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\" /> an alternative name for the [[Marsh mongoose]].<ref name=\"KingdonHappold2013\">{{cite book|author1=Jonathan Kingdon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_07noCPc4kC&pg=RA4-PA298|title=Mammals of Africa|author2=David Happold|author3=Thomas Butynski|date=23 May 2013|publisher=A&amp;C Black|others=Michael Hoffmann, Meredith Happold, Jan Kalina|isbn=978-1-4081-8996-2|pages=298}}</ref>\n\nFrom there, the two continued to record together in their basements, living rooms, and bedrooms under the new Vansire moniker.\n\n=== ''Reflections and Reveries'' and ''The Rolling, Driftless North'' (2016-2017) ===\nIn August 2016, Vansire self-released their first album, ''Reflections and Reveries''. The duo recorded the album entirely in Winemiller's basement in a roughly one-year period from August 2015 to August 2016, and included Winemiller's brother, Issac, on bass for some songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vansire.bandcamp.com/album/reflections-and-reveries|title=Reflections and Reveries - Vansire|last=|first=|date=|website=Bandcamp|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2018/02/vansire-chester-watson-star-catcher|title=Vansire and Chester Watson Blend Dream Pop and Hip-Hop \"Star Catcher\"|last=Corrigan|first=Graham|date=2 February 2018|website=Complex|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, Augustin began studying at the [[Oberlin Conservatory of Music]] and [[Oberlin College]], while Winemiller started at the [[University of Minnesota]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.krtuindie.org/blog/2018/12/3/qampa-josh-augustin|title=Q&A: Josh Augustin of Vansire|last=Anthony|first=Dominic|date=3 December 2018|website=KRTU Indie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://retriever.umbc.edu/2019/08/vansire-woos-crowd-with-dream-pop-performance-at-songbyrd/|title=Vansire woos crowd with dream-pop performance at Songbyrd|last=Dassarma|first=Anjali|date=27 August 2019|website=The Retriever|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327211414/https://retriever.umbc.edu/2019/08/vansire-woos-crowd-with-dream-pop-performance-at-songbyrd/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Despite the distance, the duo vowed to remain committed to the Vansire project, now describing it as a \"a long-distance band relationship.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fordhamram.com/62323/culture/vansire-sets-the-bar-high-for-dream-pop-soundtrack-of-the-summer/|title=Vansire Sets High Bar for Dream Pop Soundtrack of the Summer|last=Nangle|first=Olivia|date=25 April 2018|website=The Fordham Ram|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327211421/https://fordhamram.com/62323/culture/vansire-sets-the-bar-high-for-dream-pop-soundtrack-of-the-summer/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Angel Youth'' (2018-present)===\n\nVansire released their second album ''Angel Youth'' in April 2018 on Spirit Goth Records. Augustin and Winemiller produced and mastered the album themselves,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/78021/Vansire-Angel-Youth/|title=Review: Angel Youth - Vansire|last=K.|first=Rudy|date=27 September 2018|website=Sputnikmusic|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710223723/https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/78021/Vansire-Angel-Youth/|archive-date=10 July 2019|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and is the band's first full length album that featured collaborations with other artists.\n\nIn June 2019, the duo released their single \"Metamodernity\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atwoodmagazine.com/vsmm-vansire-metamodernity-song-review/|title=TODAY\u2019S SONG: VANSIRE MUSE ABOUT MODERN LIFE WITH \u201cMETAMODERNITY\u201d|last=Vettorino|first=Madison|date=19 August 2019|website=Atwood Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> also recording an [[Audiotree]] Live session at Audiotree's studios in Chicago later that August.<ref name=\"VansireAudioTree\"></ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n'''Albums'''\n*''Reflections and Reveries'' (2016)\n*''Angel Youth'' (Spirit Goth Records, 2018)\n\n'''EPs'''\n* ''The Rolling Driftless North'' (2017)\n\n'''Singles'''\n* \"Metamodernity\" (2019)\n* \"That I Miss You\" (2018)\n* \"Star Catcher\" (2018)\n* \"Halcyon Age\" (2017)\n* \"Brown Study\" (2017)\n* \"Driftless\" (2017)\n* \"Pontchartrain\" (2016)\n* \"Postal Codes\" (2016)\n* \"Bridges for the Young\" (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Dream pop musical groups]]\n[[Category:Bedroom pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American dream pop/bedroom pop band}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Vansire\n| image            = Vansire.jpg\n| caption          = Winemiller and Augustin in 2018\n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Rochester, Minnesota]]\n| genre            = {{Flatlist|\n* [[dream pop]]<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\"></ref>\n* [[bedroom pop]]\n* [[Lo-fi music|lo-fi]]\n}}\n| years_active     = {{start date|2015}}\u2013present\n| label            = {{flatlist|\n* Spirit Goth Records\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|FLOOR CRY|Chester Watson|[[sophie meiers]]|[[Jeremiah Jae]]|[[MED (rapper)|MED]]|Mellow Fellow}}\n| website          = {{url|https://vansire.bandcamp.com|Bandcamp}}\n| current_members  = * Josh Augustin\n* Sam Winemiller\n}}\n'''Vansire''' is a [[dream pop]] band from Rochester, Minnesota consisting of Josh Augustin and Sam Winemiller. The band has performed at ROCKChester,<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/opinion/our-view-rockchester-music-festival-showcases-city-s-young-talent/article_af844788-9860-575f-a546-fce3744cd0b3.html|title=Our View: ROCKchester music festival showcases city's young talent|date=14 May 2016|work=Post Bulletin|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and has done a live session with [[Audiotree]].<ref name=\"VansireAudioTree\">{{Cite web|url=https://midwestaxn.com/music/watch-this-vansire-on-audiotree-live/|title=Watch This: Vansire on Audiotree Live|last=Welch|first=Alyssa|date=29 August 2019|website=Midwest Action|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n===Formation===\nVansire formed as band members Josh Augustin (vocals, synths, guitar, and drums) and Sam Winemiller (bass, guitar, and synths) were attending [[Century High School (Rochester, Minnesota)|Century High School]] in Rochester, Minnesota.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.postbulletin.com/magazines/507/rockchester-festival-highlights-our-city-s-young-musicians/article_cc66f666-67f1-11e7-99ac-5f980a51efda.html|title=ROCKchester festival highlights our city's young musicians|last=Colby|first=Claire|date=13 July 2017|website=Post Bulletin|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714023530/https://www.postbulletin.com/magazines/507/rockchester-festival-highlights-our-city-s-young-musicians/article_cc66f666-67f1-11e7-99ac-5f980a51efda.html|archive-date=14 July 2017|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Augustin and Winemiller met while playing together on the school's [[drumline]] and continued to find themselves performing together through school activities (such as concert band and pit orchestra), something the duo says contributed to their creative synergy and friendship, which later helped in Vansire's formation.<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\"></ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015, Winemiller approached Augustin after practice for the school's drumline with an idea to make a band \"that sounds like [[Mac DeMarco|Mac [DeMarco]]]\". The pair's early recordings were made by holding instruments to the internal microphone of an [[iPad]] running [[GarageBand]].<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oberlin.edu/news/qa-vansire-cofounder-josh-augustin-20|title=Q&A with Vansire Cofounder Josh Augustin \u201920|last=Jones|first=Ben|date=7 December 2018|website=Oberlin College and Conservatory|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224080520/https://www.oberlin.edu/news/qa-vansire-cofounder-josh-augustin-20|archive-date=24 February 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> Augustin and Winemiller, initially unsure of what to call their new project, turned to an online random word generator which landed on \"vansire\",<ref name=\"JonesOberlin2018\" /> an alternative name for the [[Marsh mongoose]].<ref name=\"KingdonHappold2013\">{{cite book|author1=Jonathan Kingdon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B_07noCPc4kC&pg=RA4-PA298|title=Mammals of Africa|author2=David Happold|author3=Thomas Butynski|date=23 May 2013|publisher=A&amp;C Black|others=Michael Hoffmann, Meredith Happold, Jan Kalina|isbn=978-1-4081-8996-2|pages=298}}</ref>\n\nFrom there, the two continued to record together in their basements, living rooms, and bedrooms under the new Vansire moniker.\n\n=== ''Reflections and Reveries'' and ''The Rolling, Driftless North'' (2016-2017) ===\nIn August 2016, Vansire self-released their first album, ''Reflections and Reveries''. The duo recorded the album entirely in Winemiller's basement in a roughly one-year period from August 2015 to August 2016, and included Winemiller's brother, Issac, on bass for some songs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vansire.bandcamp.com/album/reflections-and-reveries|title=Reflections and Reveries - Vansire|last=|first=|date=|website=Bandcamp|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/pigeons-and-planes/2018/02/vansire-chester-watson-star-catcher|title=Vansire and Chester Watson Blend Dream Pop and Hip-Hop \"Star Catcher\"|last=Corrigan|first=Graham|date=2 February 2018|website=Complex|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, Augustin began studying at the [[Oberlin Conservatory of Music]] and [[Oberlin College]], while Winemiller started at the [[University of Minnesota]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.krtuindie.org/blog/2018/12/3/qampa-josh-augustin|title=Q&A: Josh Augustin of Vansire|last=Anthony|first=Dominic|date=3 December 2018|website=KRTU Indie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://retriever.umbc.edu/2019/08/vansire-woos-crowd-with-dream-pop-performance-at-songbyrd/|title=Vansire woos crowd with dream-pop performance at Songbyrd|last=Dassarma|first=Anjali|date=27 August 2019|website=The Retriever|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327211414/https://retriever.umbc.edu/2019/08/vansire-woos-crowd-with-dream-pop-performance-at-songbyrd/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Despite the distance, the duo vowed to remain committed to the Vansire project, now describing it as a \"a long-distance band relationship.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fordhamram.com/62323/culture/vansire-sets-the-bar-high-for-dream-pop-soundtrack-of-the-summer/|title=Vansire Sets High Bar for Dream Pop Soundtrack of the Summer|last=Nangle|first=Olivia|date=25 April 2018|website=The Fordham Ram|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327211421/https://fordhamram.com/62323/culture/vansire-sets-the-bar-high-for-dream-pop-soundtrack-of-the-summer/|archive-date=27 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''Angel Youth'' (2018-present)===\n\nVansire released their second album ''Angel Youth'' in April 2018 on Spirit Goth Records. Augustin and Winemiller produced and mastered the album themselves,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/78021/Vansire-Angel-Youth/|title=Review: Angel Youth - Vansire|last=K.|first=Rudy|date=27 September 2018|website=Sputnikmusic|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190710223723/https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/78021/Vansire-Angel-Youth/|archive-date=10 July 2019|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> and was the band's first full length album that featured collaborations with other artists.\n\nIn June 2019, the duo released their single \"Metamodernity\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atwoodmagazine.com/vsmm-vansire-metamodernity-song-review/|title=TODAY\u2019S SONG: VANSIRE MUSE ABOUT MODERN LIFE WITH \u201cMETAMODERNITY\u201d|last=Vettorino|first=Madison|date=19 August 2019|website=Atwood Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> also recording an [[Audiotree]] Live session at Audiotree's studios in Chicago later that August.<ref name=\"VansireAudioTree\"></ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n'''Albums'''\n*''Reflections and Reveries'' (2016)\n*''Angel Youth'' (Spirit Goth Records, 2018)\n\n'''EPs'''\n* ''The Rolling Driftless North'' (2017)\n\n'''Singles'''\n* \"Metamodernity\" (2019)\n* \"That I Miss You\" (2018)\n* \"Star Catcher\" (2018)\n* \"Halcyon Age\" (2017)\n* \"Brown Study\" (2017)\n* \"Driftless\" (2017)\n* \"Pontchartrain\" (2016)\n* \"Postal Codes\" (2016)\n* \"Bridges for the Young\" (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:American pop music groups]]\n[[Category:Dream pop musical groups]]\n[[Category:Bedroom pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "JCBird1012", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changes to better conform to MOS:TENSE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vansire"}
{"title_page": "Benjamin Mandel", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Benjamin Mandel\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1891|10|2}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1973|8|8|1891|10|2}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, DC]]\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = Bert Miller\n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = 1923\u20131967\n| known_for     = [[Communist Party of the USA|CPUSA]] functionary, [[HUAC]] research director\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Benjamin Mandel''' (1887\u20131973) {{aka}} \"Bert Miller\" was a New York city school teacher and communist activist who later became an ex-communist director of research for the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) and the [[United States Senate Subcommittee on Internal Security|Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]] (SIS).<ref name=WPobit>\n{{cite news\n  | title = Communist Prober Benjamin Mandel\n  | work = Washington Post\n| url  = http://jfk.hood.edu/Collection/Weisberg%20Subject%20Index%20Files/N%20Disk/Nixon%20Richard%20M%20President%20Watergate%20Files/Past%20Records%20Hiss/Item%2003.pdf\n  | page = C4\n  | date = 10 August 1973\n  | accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=Witness>\n  {{Cite book\n  | last = Chambers\n  | first = Whittaker\n  | authorlink = Whittaker Chambers\n  | title = Witness\n  | publisher = Random House\n  | year = 1952\n  | location = New York\n  | pages = 207, 536, 558, 563\u2013564, 566\u2013568, 571, 600, 628, 647, 663, 665\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WIkNAAAAIAAJ\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 978-0-8488-0958-4}}</ref><ref name=Kienholz>\n{{cite book\n| first = M.  \n| last = Kienholz\n| title = The Canwell Files: Murder, Arson and Intrigue in the Evergreen State\n| publisher = iUniverse\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7XJjhezDH1EC\n| pages = 174\n| date = 21 September 2012\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018| isbn = 9781475948813\n}}</ref><ref name=Meier>\n{{cite book\n  | first = Andrew\n  | last = Meier\n  | title = The Lost Spy: An American in Stalin's Secret Service\n  | publisher = W. W. Norton\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oVvLInX4fHcC\n  | date = August 11, 2008\n  | pages = 84 (Labor Defense Council), 247\u2013248 (bio), 349 (footnotes)\n  | isbn = 978-0-393-06097-3}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n  | title = Benjamin Mandel\n  | work = New York Times\n| url  = https://www.nytimes.com/1973/08/10/archives/benjamin-mandel.html\n  | page = 34\n  | date = 10 August 1973\n  | accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nBenjamin Mandel was born in on October 2, 1891, in New York City.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Career==\n\nMandel became a New York City schoolteacher and then organization secretary for the New York district of the [[Teachers Union]].<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Bert Miller===\n\n====Communist Party of the USA (CPUSA)====\n\nMandel used the name \"Bert Miller\" when he joined the [[Communist Party]] in the 1920s.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz /> On April 6, 1923, name appears in the letterhead of the 1922 [[Labor Defense Council]] in support of [[Bridgman Raid]] defendants (and forerunner of [[International Labor Defense]] or ILD) as a local committee member.  Other members included [[Elizabeth Gurley Flynn]], [[Freda Kirchwey]], [[Eugene V. Debs]], [[Norman Thomas]], Mary Heaton Vorse, [[J.B. Matthews]], and Nerma Berman (wife of Soviet spy [[Isaiah Oggins]]).<ref name=Meier /><ref name=RedNetwork>\n{{cite book\n| first = Elizabeth \n| last = Dilling\n| authorlink = Elizabeth Dilling\n| title = The Red Network: A Who's Who and Handbook of Radicalism for Patriots\n| publisher = (self-published)\n| location = Chicago\n| url = https://archive.org/details/rednetworkwhoswh00dillrich\n| pages = 181 (conference), 181 (Labor Defense Council), 276 (Debs), 296 (Kirchwey)\n| date = April 1934\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925 he resigned his position as a teacher to work full-time for the Party.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 7 Teachers Face Contempt Action in School\n| work = New York Times\n| url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20E1FF63C5B147B93C4A9178DD85F458485F9&scp=1&sq=%227%20Teachers%20Face%20Contempt%22&st=cse\n| accessdate = 22 October 2011\n| date=6 June 1941}}</ref>  [[Whittaker Chambers]] remembered that \"Bert Miller\" signed his Party card in 1925.<ref name=Witness /><ref name=Kienholz /><ref name=Meier /><ref name=Ryskind>\n{{cite book\n| first = Allan  \n| last = Ryskind\n| title = Hollywood Traitors: Blacklisted Screenwriters \u2013 Agents of Stalin, Allies of Hitler\n| publisher = Regnery\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K4-pBQAAQBAJ\n| pages = 170\n| date = 5 January 2015\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018| isbn = 9781621572060\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925\u201326, Bert Miller studied under Professor [[Scott Nearing]] in his Research Study Group for a forthcoming book called ''The Law of Social Revolution'' (1926).  Classmates included Whittaker Chambers, [[Dale Zysman]] (vice president of the Teachers' Union), [[Bertram Wolfe]], [[Ben Davidson (politician)|Ben Davidson]] (later co-founder of the [[Liberal Party of New York]]) and his wife Eve Dorf,<ref name=HUAC-1952>\n{{cite web\n| title = Subversive Influence in the Educational Process: Hearings Before the Subcommittee to Investigate the Administration of the Internal Security Act and Other Internal Security Laws to the Committee on the Judiciary\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://archive.org/stream/1952SubversiveInfluencesSchools/1952_Subversive_Influences_Schools\n| pages = 162 (Teachers' Union), 187 (Bernhard J. Stern), 343 (Scott Nearing)\n| date = 1953\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> [[Sam Krieger]],<ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Bruce\n| last = Lambert\n| title = Ben Davidson, 90, a Co-Founder Of the Liberal Party in New York\n| work = New York Times\n| date = 22 December 1991\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/22/nyregion/ben-davidson-90-a-co-founder-of-the-liberal-party-in-new-york.html\n| accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref> [[Alfred J. Brooks]], [[Myra Page]], and [[Rachel Ragozin]].<ref name=Witness /><ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Robert W.\n| last = Iversen\n| title = The Communists & the Schools\n| publisher = Harcourt, Brace\n| year = 1959\n| page = 21\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/22/nyregion/ben-davidson-90-a-co-founder-of-the-liberal-party-in-new-york.html\n| accessdate = 7 April 2013| newspaper = The New York Times\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926, Bert Miller ignited the [[1926 Passaic textile strike]], as related by [[Benjamin Gitlow]] in his 1939 memoir:  <blockquote><small>The man who started the ball rolling was Bert Miller, industrial organizer of District Two of the Party, which then included most of industrial New Jersey and Connecticut as well as New York City. Comrade Miller called to my attention the fact that the Botany Mills of Passaic had announced a wage cut of ten percent, beginning with October, 1925. I immediately instructed Miller to get in touch with our New Jersey comrades and explore the matter further, agreeing with him that on its face the situation seemed favorable enough for initiating agitation for a strike in retaliation for the wage cut. Miller was a veteran of the Party since its underground days and carried out his assignment expeditiously. His report convinced me that there was ample ground for developing a successful strike.<ref name=\"Gitlow\">\n{{cite book\n| first = Benjamin \n| last = Gitlow\n| title = I Confess: The Truth About American Communism\n| publisher = E.P. Dutton\n| url = https://archive.org/details/BenjaminGitlow\n| pages = 363 (Passaic), 575 (Lovestone split)\n| date = 1940\n| accessdate = 7 August 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>   [[Albert Weisbord]], main leader of the Passaic strike, recalled later and critically of both Miller (\"the innocent\") and the Communist Party:  <blockquote><small> In New York I contacted Bert Miller, a teacher made suddenly \"industrial\" organizer of the Party, who, as a newcomer in the office, tried to live up to a job he knew very little about... <br> I was just now, in 1924, that ignorant, unsuspicious me had to enter into that nest of intrigue, without the lightest inkling of the kind of leadership under which I was enlisting... <br> I soon found the approximately 400 strikers in meeting in a small hall near the mill... We built up a picket line, drew up our demands and created a semblance of organization. They no longer felt lost or abandoned... They wanted to see membership applications and membership dues books...  Back in New York I reported all this to Miller. This innocent agreed that I should get application and membership cards printed. He was not aware that on this matter he would be bitterly assailed by the Foster-Cannon leadership for dual unionism and would open up a major struggle with the Party... <br> The worthlessness of the C.P. leaders did not in the least make me undervalue the great worth of the tens of thousands of devoted foreign-born workers and militant American-born youth who were the members and followers of that party... At the moment for me the important link in the chain was the innocent Bert Miller, acting on this own while the \"bigs\" were tied up with other matters, especially the N.Y. District Organizer [[Willam Weinstone|Weinstone]] who was very busy intriguing with Cannon on how to form a new faction to end factions!  Weinstone\u2019s sloth and Miller\u2019s ignorance were to help me much.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| first = Albert\n| last = Weisbord\n| authorlink = Albert Weisbord\n| title = Passaic Review\n| publisher = Albert & Vera Weisbord Foundation\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/archive/weisbord/Reviewed.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref></small> </blockquote>     In 1926, Bert Miller also became business manager of the ''[[Daily Worker]]'' communist newspaper.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz /><ref name=Ryskind />  His name first appears on the masthead in the November 26, 1926 issue,<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Daily Worker\n| publisher = Daily Worker Publishing Co.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/dw-hr-1926/v3n264-nov-20-1926-TDW.pdf\n| location = Chicago\n| date = 26 November 1926\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> and appeared throughout 1926<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = The Daily Worker - 1926\n| publisher = Marxists.org\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/1926/index.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> and 1927<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = The Daily Worker - 1927\n| publisher = Marxists.org\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/1927/index.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> \u2013 the publication of \"business manager\" dropped from the masthead in 1928.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = The Daily Worker - 1928\n| publisher = Marxists.org\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/1927/index.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> Whittaker Chambers recalled:    <blockquote><small>In those days, Bert Miller was a harassed soul.  As business manager of the ''Daily Worker'', the future research director of the House Committee on Un-American Activities had to meet a weekly payroll and find money to pay the paper, print, and other bills.  Money was very hard to find, and his life was a weekly crisis.  Thus, my chief recollection of Bert Miller from the past is less than a face than as a weary plaint:  money. <br> Bert suffered other grievances, too.  In his business office, he presided over a number of young women Communists, one of whom was a remarkably pretty Hungarian girl.  He often protested that his girls were terrified towalk through the ''Daily Worker'' office (as they sometimes had to) because, while they wriggled their way past he crowded chairs, each of the editors in turn reached back and pinched them.<ref name=Witness /></small></blockquote>    In 1927, Mandel was elected to the Party's Central Committee at its fifth congress in 1927.  In 1929, he was re-elected as a \"candidate member\" at its sixth convention in March 1929. Later that year, he was expelled with followers of [[Jay Lovestone]] (known at the [[Lovestoneites]]) as an \"incurable right-wing deviationist\".<ref name=Witness /><ref name=Meier /><ref>\n{{cite book\n| last = Draper\n| first = Theodore\n| title = American Communism and Soviet Russia: The Formative Period\n| publisher = Viking Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9praAAAAMAAJ\n| pages =430, 531, 561\n| date = 1960\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Communist Party (Opposition) (CPO)====\n\nAs of the first issue (November 1, 1929), Bert Miller appeared on the editorial board of ''[[Revolutionary Age]]'', organ of the [[Lovestoneites|Communist Party (Majority)]] formed by Jay Lovestone, i.e., he joined Lovestone's Communist Party (Majority Group).  Other editors included: [[Benjamin Gitlow]], editor; [[Bertram Wolfe]], associate editor; and editorial board members J.O. Bixby, Ellen Dawson, Will Herberg, William Miller, R. Pires, Jack Rubinstein, Frank Vrataric, Ed Welsh, W.J. White, Herbert Zam, and Charles S. Zimmerman.<ref name=\"RA-19291101\">\n{{cite journal\n| title = Opening of Marx-Lenin School (ad)\n| journal = Revolutionary Age |volume=1 |issue=2\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n02-nov-15-1929.pdf\n| date = 15 November 1929\n| page = 6\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| first =  John Patrick Haithcox\n| last = Haithcox\n| title = Communism and Nationalism in India: M.N. Roy and Comintern Policy, 1920-1939\n| publisher = Princeton University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3d9BgAAQBAJ\n| pages= 320 (fn92)\n| date = 8 March 2015\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018| isbn = 9781400869329\n}}</ref>\n\nMiller was also one of the original teachers at the New Workers School of the Lovestoneites, as advertised in the November 15 issue<ref name=\"Ad\">\n{{cite journal\n| title = Opening of Marx-Lenin School! (ad)\n| journal = Revolutionary Age |volume=1 |issue=2\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n02-nov-15-1929.pdf\n| date = 15 November 1929\n| page = 11\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref> and detailed in a December 15 article.<ref name=\"Build\">\n{{cite journal\n| title = Build the Marx-Lenin School!\n| journal = Revolutionary Age |volume=1 |issue=7\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n07-feb-01-1930.pdf\n| date = 1 February 1930\n| page = 9\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1930, Miller spoke in Philadelphia to some 300 workers regarding \"The Crisis in the Communist Party of the USA.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Miller Speaks in Philadelphia\n| journal = Revolutionary Age\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n12-apr-21-1930.pdf\n| date = 15 August 1931\n| page = 11\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1930, Miller joined the [[Conference for Progressive Labor Action]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last = Alexander\n| first = Robert J \n| title = The Right Opposition: The Lovestoneites and the International Communist Opposition of the 1930s\n| publisher = Greenwood Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MnoEAQAAIAAJ&q\n| isbn = 0-313-22070-0\n| pages= 63\u201369\n| date = 1981\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1931, the Communist League of Struggle (Adhering to the International Left Opposition), attached Miller as a Lovestone leader:  <blockquote><small>Do you think that it is an accident that out of your ranks, trained by Lovestone, have sprung OPEN RENEGADES from Communism, Bert Miller and Company? Can you not see that Bert Miller but does what Lovestone is planning to do -- later, that Miller is but the vanguard of Lovestone himself?<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Where Are You Going?\n| journal = Class Struggle\n| url = http://www.weisbord.org/OneTwo.htm\n| date = June 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref> <br> ... In spite of intrigue on the part of the official Communist Party, the Lovestone group and its allies, Bert Miller and [[Ludwig Lore]] -- about 250 attended the [[Albert Weisbord]]-[[Louis F. Budenz]] debate at the Labor Temple, Saturday, May 2. The topic was \"Shall the Workers Support the Conference for Progressive Labor Action in Preference to the Communists?\"... After the posters, leaflets and advertisements announcing the debate were released, pressure to kill the debate opened. According to reports, [[William Z. Foster]] who was scheduled to debate Muste a week later, threatened to withdraw if Muste debated Weisbord first. Under the Party's pressure, Muste decided not to debate Weisbord and assigned Budenz in his stead. This was the time for Miller, the \"communist\" watch-dog and advisor to the C.P.L.A. to step in with his \"expert\" advice. Lore also advised Budenz not to go through with the arrangements.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = Sylvan A.\n| last = Pollack\n| title = Current Comments\n| journal = Class Struggle\n| url = http://www.weisbord.org/OneTwo.htm\n| date = June 1931\n| page = 2\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>  By August 1931, the Lovestoneites were commenting angrily in ''Revolutionary Age'': \"As soon as this group of comrades entered the CPLA<ref>Conference for Progressive Labor Action</ref> and began to function, a differentiation began to take place:  Bert Miller, Levich, and Lawrence began to move rapidly to the extreme right, while the rest of the comrades under the leadership of Comrade Benjamin, took up a sharp struggle against social reformism and against Miller and his friends as well.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Communists and the C.P.L.A.\n| journal = Revolutionary Age\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v2n37-aug-15-1931.pdf\n| date = 15 August 1931\n| page = 4\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref>  Miller's push for this group caused Benjamin Gitlow to split with the [[Lovestoneites]], who insisted that \"Stalin's policies were a hundred percent correct.\"<ref name=\"Gitlow\"/>\n\nBy October 1931, ''Revolutionary Age'' was calling Miller, Gitlow, and others \"traitors\":  <blockquote><small>'''ON WORKERS SOLIDARITY'''<br> A fine day of celebration for these traitors, who, together with Gitlow, [[Louis F. Budenz|Budenz]], Bert Miller and Zimmerman and the smaller fry of Lovestone renegades, are trying to break the strike of the textile workers. Labor Day is a day that symbolizes the attempted sell-out of their militant struggles. It is a day of hatred of the system that makes use of such scum from Green, Woll to Gitlow, Budenz, [[A.J. Muste|Muste]] and the smaller gang of pickpockets, who pose as \"labor leaders.\" <br>August 22, 1931 , [[Israel Amter|I. Amter]]<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = On Workers Solidarity\n| journal = Revolutionary Age\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v2n44-oct-03-1931.pdf\n| date = April 1930\n| page = 2\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>     In 1931, Miller's name appeared as a national officer of the Joint Committee on Unemployment, headed by [[John Dewey]].<ref name=RedNetwork />  On November 19, 1931, \"Benjamin Mandel\" attended a protest against Italian foreign minister [[Dino Grandi]], a \"Fascist diplomat\":  as part of deputation from the Committee for International Anti-Fascist Protest, Mandel joined [[A.J. Muste]], [[Roger Nash Baldwin|Roger Baldwin]], and several Italian-Americans.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Bomb Guard Alert for Visit of Grandi\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1931/11/20/archives/bomb-guard-alert-for-visit-of-grandi-report-of-plot-on-morgan.html\n| date = 20 November 1931\n| page = 12\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>  On December 2, 1931, \"Benjamin Mandel\" as \"organizer for the Brotherhood of Brooklyn Edison Employees\" as well as observer for the [[Conference for Progressive Labor Action]], joined a group of nine led by Rev. Eliot White, formerly of the [[Grace Church (Manhattan)|Grace Episcopal Church]], to distribute union literature, when they found themselves attacked by hundreds of people.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Thugs Beat Minister in Edison Union Row\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1931/12/03/archives/thugs-beat-minister-in-edison-union-row-hundreds-set-upon-rev-eliot.html\n| date = 3 December 1931\n| page = 1\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Accuse Edison Men of Striking Pastor\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1931/12/09/archives/accuse-edison-men-of-striking-pastor-but-witnesses-fail-to-identify.html\n| date = 9 December 1931\n| page = 2\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>  In its December 1931 issue, ''Labor Age'' described Mandel as \"labor organizer and writer... active in the White Plains Road Laborers Strike last summer... now helping the Brooklyn Edison Employes organization campaign.\"<ref name=LA1931Dec>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = American Welcomes Grandi\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n12-dec-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = December 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Mandel had called for a bar to admittance of communists during a meeting to discuss the ongoing [[Harlan County, Kentucky|Harlan County]] coal strike that had started in 1931 (see [[Harlan County War]]): <blockquote><small>\"No communists are admitted here\", was the greeting at the door, which met the delegate of the C.L.S., who tried to attend the \"broad united front of labor\", called by the I.W.W. General Defense Committee for the Harlan Kentucky miners on January 6. Of course it had to be the unspeakable Bert Miller, who handed out this information. All sorts of liberals, anarchists, and what not were gathered together, but the Communists were not even allowed to enter the hall!\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Current Comment: No Communist Admitted\n| publisher = Class Struggle: Official Organ of the Communist League of Struggle\n| url = http://www.weisbord.org/TwoOne.htm\n| date = 1981\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>  On March 6, 1932, Mandel joined a committee that supported the $375 million Costigan-La Follettee-Lewis relief bill, itself part of a $3 billion federal bill to provide housing credit, end sales taxes, and increases surtaxes and estate taxes.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 3 Billions Urged for Public Works\n| work = Washington Post\n| url =\n| date = 7 March 1932\n| page = 5\n| accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n===Benjamin Mandel===\n\nOn July 17, 1932, a new joint committee on unemployment in New York state formed under Bishop Francis J. McConnell of the Methodist Baptist Church in Manhattan.  Committee members included: Sidney E. Goldstein, [[Stephen S. Wise]], Mary Fox, Alfred Bernheim, Darwin J. Meserole, Howard Y. Williams, [[A.J. Muste]], [[J.B. Matthews]], William Spofford, Winifred Chappell, [[Abraham Lefkowitz]], [[Sidney Hillman]], [[Paul Blanshard]], Jack Altman, Helen Alfred, [[Walter Francis White|Walter White]], and LeRoy E. Bowman.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = State Drive Opened for Jobless Relief\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/18/archives/state-drive-opened-for-jobless-relief-bishop-mcconnell-heads-new.html\n| date = 18 July 1932\n| page =15\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Dies Committee and Rapp Coudert====\n\nBy the later 1930s, \"Bert Miller\" the former communist had become a dedicated anti-communist and by 1939 had resurfaced fully as \"Benjamin Mandel\" to help [[J.B. Matthews]] as a researcher for the [[Dies Committee]] until 1945. He also worked with the New York legislature during the [[Rapp-Coudert Committee|Rapp-Courdert inquiry]] into the presence of Communist teachers in New York schools.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz /><ref name=Meier /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n(In 1939, after [[Isaac Don Levine]] had introduced them, [[Walter Krivitsky]] told Chambers that \"Ben Mandel\" of the [[Dies Committee]] was \"Bert Miller\" of the Communist Party.<ref name=Witness />)\n\nIn 1940 during Rapp-Coudert Committee investigations, \"Benjamin Mandel\" became connected with Communist activities under the name \"Bert Miller.\"<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Legislative Document, Volume 10\n| publisher = J.B. Lyon Company\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H8StmFlH0uEC\n| pages = 180, 305, 315\n| date = 1942\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Report of the subcommittee of the Joint legislative committee to investigate procedures and methods of allocating state moneys for public school purposes and subversive activities\n| publisher = New York (State) Legislature - Joint Committee on the State Education System\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=UxRKAAAAMAAJ\n| pages = 180, 305, 315\n| date = 1942\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref>  The same year, Matthews connected \"Benjamin Mandel\" with \"Bert Miller\" during the testimony of [[Leonard Emil Mins]] before the Dies Committee.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Investigation of Un-American Propaganda Activities in the United States\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=SAugbQDPbK4C\n| page = 3428\n| date = 1940\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 1941, Mandel himself testified before Dies Committee regarding the China Aid Council, a subsidiary of the [[American League for Peace and Democracy]].  He named Dr. [[Owen Lattimore]], [[Frederick V. Field]], and others.<ref name=Kienholz />\n\nFrom 1945 to 1947, Mandel worked for the [[U.S. Department of State]] in handling \"security.\"<ref name=WPobit />\n\n====HUAC====\n\nIn 1947, Mandel returned to former Dies Committee, now renamed the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC), \"to assist the committee in the [[Alger Hiss|Hiss]]-[[Whittaker Chambers|Chambers]] case.\"<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz />  He has been characterized, along with U.S. Representative [[J. Parnell Thomas]] and HUAC chief investigator [[Robert E. Stripling]] as one of the \"choreographers of the hearings.\"<ref name=Ryskind />\n\nDuring the Hiss Case, Mandel participated in questioning during hearings.  Mandel stated \"A picture of Hiss shows his hand cupped to his ear,\" to which Chambers replied, \"He is deaf in one ear.\"  Mandel asked, \"How is it that he (Hiss) never wrote anything publicly,\" to which Chambers answered, \"He was never in the open Communist Party.\"  Mandel checked for \"George Crosley\" as a government employee and received the negative findings from one Ernest S. Griffith, director of Legislative Reference Service.  He also partook in the search for the Ford car sold by Hiss to William Rosen.<ref name=Witness /><ref name=Kienholz />\n\nOn May 2, 1949, Steele spoke with Congressman [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Walter S. Steele]] (publisher of ''The National Republic'' magazine and member of the American Coalition of Patriotic, Civic and Fraternal Societies, founded by [[John B. Trevor Sr.]])) at a [[Knights of Columbus]] annual town hall.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 3 to speak at anti-Red rally here: Sponsored by KC\n| work = Washington Post\n| page = M20\n| date = 1 May 1949}}</ref>\n\n====SISS====\n\nIn 1951, Mandel left HUAC<ref name=NYTobit/> and became research director in the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee, and stayed in that position until his retirement in 1967.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news\n| title = Senators Oppose White House Curb: Senate Investigator Retires\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1967/11/02/archives/senators-oppose-white-house-curb-balk-at-limiting-authority-to-make.html\n| date = 2 November 1967\n| page = 9\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref> During his SIS years, he took an active role in connect the influence of the Communist Party and communist-influenced labor unions (e.g., [[Congress of Industrial Organizations|CIO]]) in the Teachers' Union and among teachers (e.g., see \"Mandel\" in 1952 hearings<ref name=HUAC-1952 />).<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn May 1951, [[Benjamin Gitlow]] told the Senate's Subversive Activities Control Board that he had \"repeatedly discussed\" the board with its research director Mandel as well as another former Communist associate [[Joseph Zack Kornfeder]]. Gitlow said, \"I discussed the conduct of this case.  I discussed the attorneys in the case.  I discussed the members of the panel.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = McCarran's Reds\n| journal = The New Republic\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=eSDIsytObNsC\n| page = 7\n| date = 28 May 1951\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019| last1 = Croly\n| first1 = Herbert David\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] criticized Mandel in her column:     <blockquote> <small> I was sent a column the other day by a gentleman which he had clipped from a paper and felt was very convincing. The column was written by Benjamin Mandel, a former research director of the House Un-American Activities Committee and at present a member of the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee. Mr. Mandel was writing as a guest columnist for Mr. C. Brown. <br> Mr. Mandel in his column took all liberals and intellectuals to task for sitting in judgment on Congressional committees investigating Communist activities. Most of the column pointed out the \"faults of liberals\" and of course, being human beings, I don't suppose they are perfect but it seemed to me this column was very slanted in its reasoning. <br> Unquestionably, critical self-examination should be of value to liberals and intellectuals, but I have no doubt it would be of value to those who conduct Congressional investigations also. <ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = My Day\n| publisher = The Eleanor Roosevelt Papers Project\n| url = https://www2.gwu.edu/~erpapers/myday/displaydoc.cfm?_y=1953&_f=md002679\n| date = 23 May 1953\n| accessdate = 28 January 2020}}</ref> </small> </blockquote>    In 1956, [[TASS]] deputy bureau chief [[Harry Freeman (journalist)|Harry Freeman]] testified before SISS. Mandel read a passage from Whittaker Chambers' 1952 memoir ''Witness'' about Freeman at the ''Daily Worker''.  In retort, Freeman reminded SISS that Mandel was there, too, as business manager.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Ed \n| last = Creagh\n| title = Top Tass Official in U.S. Dodges Red Spy Quiz\n| work = New York Times\n| url =\n| date = 22 February 1956\n| page = 11\n| accessdate = }}</ref>  On October 25, 1967, lawyers for the [[National Conference for New Politics]] (NCNP) and the [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]] (MFDP) filed an order to take immediate sworn statements about documents from Senator [[James O. Eastland]] and subcommittee staffers, J.G. Sourwine and Mandel to enjoin any further distribution or use of the files.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Senators Oppose White House Curb: Senate Investigator Retires\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1967/10/29/archives/dissenters-and-foes-eastland-on-a-new-subversive-hunt.html\n| date = 29 October 1967\n| page = 9\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>  In 1959, [[I.F. Stone]] named Mandel as \"another powerful Lovestoneite,\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = I.F.\n| last = Stone\n| authorlink = I.F. Stone\n| title = I.F. Stone's Weekly\n| publisher = Kraus Reprint Co.\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=I99JAQAAIAAJ\n| page = 70\n| date = 1959\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref> while researcher [[Robert W. Iversen]] noted Mandel in his book ''The Communists & the Schools'',<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Robert W.\n| last = Iversen\n| authorlink = Robert W. Iversen\n| title = The Communists & the Schools\n| publisher = Harcourt, Brace\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=s3CcAAAAMAAJ\n| pages = 21\n| date = 1959\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref> and [[Theodore Draper]] consulted him for his book ''American Communism and Soviet Russia''.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Theodore\n| last = Draper\n| authorlink = Theodore Draper\n| title = American Communism and Soviet Russia\n| publisher = Viking Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JGdZJPEh_LsC\n| pages = 525\n| date = 1960\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 1967, Mandel announced his retirement.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=\"New York Times\"/>  He continued to consult to that subcommittee for some years.<ref name=WPobit />\n\nMandel, following Matthews before him, supplied information about \"suspect clergy\" to [[Carl McIntire]] (1906&ndash;2002), a founder and minister in the [[Bible Presbyterian Church]], founder and long-time president of the [[International Council of Christian Churches]] and the [[American Council of Christian Churches]], and a popular religious radio broadcaster, who proudly identified himself as a [[Christian fundamentalist|fundamentalist]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Markku \n| last = Ruotsila\n| title = Fighting Fundamentalist: Carl McIntire and the Politicization of American Fundamentalism\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uCygCgAAQBAJ\n| pages = 117\n| date = 2016\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019| isbn = 9780199372997\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal and death==\n\nMandel married Margaret Rees.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nHe believed in exposing the Communist Party in the U.S. and explained in 1951:  <blockquote><small>You've got to assume there is a present communist conspiracy, and it is obvious the communists want every additional scrap of atomic information they can lay hands on.  <br>  There are two ways to meet this conspiracy.  One is to have a secret polic.  The other is to develop the evidence in the American way, in open hearings and with sworn testimony.  The goal should never be to railroad the people; always to respect civil liberties.<ref name=WPobit /></small></blockquote>\n\nMandel died age 82 on August 8, 1973, at the Mar-Salle Convalescent Home at 2131 O Street NW, Washington, DC.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Works==\n\nAccording to his ''Washington Post'' obituary, Mandel was co-author of the book ''I Was a Soviet Worker'', published in the U.S. in 1936 and in the U.K. in 1937, but neither \"Mandel\" nor \"Miller\" appears in the book.<ref name=WPobit />\n\n'''As Bert Miller:'''\n* \"Giant Power,\" ''The Communist'' (August 1928)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first1=Bert \n| last1=Miller\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Giant Power\n| publisher = The Communist\n| url = http://www.unz.com/print/Communist-1928aug-00473/\n| date = August 1928\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref>\n* \"Gandhi Betrays,\" ''Labor Age'' (May 1931)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Bert \n| last1=Miller\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Gandhi Betrays\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n05-May-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = May 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* \"Book Review:  Kautsky at the Crossroads\" ''Labor Age'' (July 1932)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Bert \n| last1=Miller\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Book Review: Kautsky at the Crossroads\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n07-Jul-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = July 1932\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* ''I Was a Soviet Worker'' (1936)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first1=Andrew \n| last1=Smith\n| first2=Maria \n| last2=Kiraly Smith\n| title = I Was a Soviet Worker\n| publisher = E.P. Dutton\n| url = https://books.google.com/books/about/I_was_a_soviet_worker.html?id=uYY1AQAAIAAJ\n| date = 1936\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n** ''I Was a Soviet Worker'' (1937)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first1=Andrew \n| last1=Smith\n| first2=Maria \n| last2=Kiraly Smith\n| title = I Was a Soviet Worker\n| publisher = Hale\n| url = https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/009980583\n| date = 1937\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''As Benjamin Mandel:'''\n* \"The Battle of White Plains,\" ''Labor Age'' (August 1931)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = The Battle of White Plains\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n08-Aug-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = August 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n* \"And These Are Our Rulers,\" ''Labor Age'' (September 1931)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = And These Are Our Rulers\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n09-Sep-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = September 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* \"America Welcomes Grandi,\" ''Labor Age'' (December 1931)<ref name=LA1931Dec/>\n* \"Roosevelt: Jingo-Liberal,\" ''Labor Age'' (June 1932)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Roosevelt: Jingo-Liberal\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v21n06-jun-1932-labor-age.pdf\n| date = June 1932\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* \"After Roosevelt - What?\" ''Colliers'' (~1932-1934)<ref>\n{{cite web\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = After Roosevelt - What?\n| publisher = (unknown)\n| url = http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf629004p8/entire_text/\n| date = August 1928\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref>\n* \"Evaluation of the World Trade Union Federation\" (1946?)<ref>\n{{cite web\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Evaluation of the World Trade Union Federation\n| publisher = (unknown)\n| url = https://oac.cdlib.org/view?docId=c8jw8d64;view=dsc;style=oac4;doc.view=entire_text;dsc.position=10001;dsc.position=5001\n| date = 2018\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref>\n* \"A Handbook for Americans:  The Communist Party:  What It Is, How It Works\" (1955)<ref name=WPobit /><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = A Handbook for Americans: The Communist Party: What It Is, How It Works\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://archive.org/details/communistpartyof1955unit\n| date = 1955\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Communist Party of the United States of America]]\n* [[Jay Lovestone]]\n* [[Teachers Union]]\n* [[J.B. Matthews]]\n* [[House Un-American Activities Committee]]\n* [[United States Senate Subcommittee on Internal Security|Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]]\n* [[Whittaker Chambers]]\n* [[Alger Hiss]]\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandel, Benjamin}}\n[[Category:Right Opposition]]\n[[Category:American communists]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n[[Category:1891 births]]\n[[Category:1973 deaths]]\n[[Category:McCarthyism]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:Members of the Communist Party USA]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Benjamin Mandel\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1891|10|2}}\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1973|8|8|1891|10|2}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, DC]]\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = Bert Miller\n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = 1923\u20131967\n| known_for     = [[Communist Party of the USA|CPUSA]] functionary, [[HUAC]] research director\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Benjamin Mandel''' (1887\u20131973) {{aka}} \"Bert Miller\" was a New York city school teacher and communist activist who later became an ex-communist director of research for the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) and the [[United States Senate Subcommittee on Internal Security|Senate Internal Security Subcommittee]] (SIS).<ref name=WPobit>\n{{cite news\n  | title = Communist Prober Benjamin Mandel\n  | work = Washington Post\n| url  = http://jfk.hood.edu/Collection/Weisberg%20Subject%20Index%20Files/N%20Disk/Nixon%20Richard%20M%20President%20Watergate%20Files/Past%20Records%20Hiss/Item%2003.pdf\n  | page = C4\n  | date = 10 August 1973\n  | accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=Witness>\n  {{Cite book\n  | last = Chambers\n  | first = Whittaker\n  | authorlink = Whittaker Chambers\n  | title = Witness\n  | publisher = Random House\n  | year = 1952\n  | location = New York\n  | pages = 207, 536, 558, 563\u2013564, 566\u2013568, 571, 600, 628, 647, 663, 665\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=WIkNAAAAIAAJ\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 978-0-8488-0958-4}}</ref><ref name=Kienholz>\n{{cite book\n| first = M.  \n| last = Kienholz\n| title = The Canwell Files: Murder, Arson and Intrigue in the Evergreen State\n| publisher = iUniverse\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7XJjhezDH1EC\n| pages = 174\n| date = 21 September 2012\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018| isbn = 9781475948813\n}}</ref><ref name=Meier>\n{{cite book\n  | first = Andrew\n  | last = Meier\n  | title = The Lost Spy: An American in Stalin's Secret Service\n  | publisher = W. W. Norton\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oVvLInX4fHcC\n  | date = August 11, 2008\n  | pages = 84 (Labor Defense Council), 247\u2013248 (bio), 349 (footnotes)\n  | isbn = 978-0-393-06097-3}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n  | title = Benjamin Mandel\n  | work = New York Times\n| url  = https://www.nytimes.com/1973/08/10/archives/benjamin-mandel.html\n  | page = 34\n  | date = 10 August 1973\n  | accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nBenjamin Mandel was born in on October 2, 1891, in New York City.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Career==\n\nMandel became a New York City schoolteacher and then organization secretary for the New York district of the [[Teachers Union]].<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n===Bert Miller===\n\n====Communist Party of the USA (CPUSA)====\n\nMandel used the name \"Bert Miller\" when he joined the [[Communist Party]] in the 1920s.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz /> On April 6, 1923, name appears in the letterhead of the 1922 [[Labor Defense Council]] in support of [[Bridgman Raid]] defendants (and forerunner of [[International Labor Defense]] or ILD) as a local committee member.  Other members included [[Elizabeth Gurley Flynn]], [[Freda Kirchwey]], [[Eugene V. Debs]], [[Norman Thomas]], Mary Heaton Vorse, [[J.B. Matthews]], and Nerma Berman (wife of Soviet spy [[Isaiah Oggins]]).<ref name=Meier /><ref name=RedNetwork>\n{{cite book\n| first = Elizabeth \n| last = Dilling\n| authorlink = Elizabeth Dilling\n| title = The Red Network: A Who's Who and Handbook of Radicalism for Patriots\n| publisher = (self-published)\n| location = Chicago\n| url = https://archive.org/details/rednetworkwhoswh00dillrich\n| pages = 181 (conference), 181 (Labor Defense Council), 276 (Debs), 296 (Kirchwey)\n| date = April 1934\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925 he resigned his position as a teacher to work full-time for the Party.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 7 Teachers Face Contempt Action in School\n| work = New York Times\n| url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20E1FF63C5B147B93C4A9178DD85F458485F9&scp=1&sq=%227%20Teachers%20Face%20Contempt%22&st=cse\n| accessdate = 22 October 2011\n| date=6 June 1941}}</ref>  [[Whittaker Chambers]] remembered that \"Bert Miller\" signed his Party card in 1925.<ref name=Witness /><ref name=Kienholz /><ref name=Meier /><ref name=Ryskind>\n{{cite book\n| first = Allan  \n| last = Ryskind\n| title = Hollywood Traitors: Blacklisted Screenwriters \u2013 Agents of Stalin, Allies of Hitler\n| publisher = Regnery\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=K4-pBQAAQBAJ\n| pages = 170\n| date = 5 January 2015\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018| isbn = 9781621572060\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1925\u201326, Bert Miller studied under Professor [[Scott Nearing]] in his Research Study Group for a forthcoming book called ''The Law of Social Revolution'' (1926).  Classmates included Whittaker Chambers, [[Dale Zysman]] (vice president of the Teachers' Union), [[Bertram Wolfe]], [[Ben Davidson (politician)|Ben Davidson]] (later co-founder of the [[Liberal Party of New York]]) and his wife Eve Dorf,<ref name=HUAC-1952>\n{{cite web\n| title = Subversive Influence in the Educational Process: Hearings Before the Subcommittee to Investigate the Administration of the Internal Security Act and Other Internal Security Laws to the Committee on the Judiciary\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://archive.org/stream/1952SubversiveInfluencesSchools/1952_Subversive_Influences_Schools\n| pages = 162 (Teachers' Union), 187 (Bernhard J. Stern), 343 (Scott Nearing)\n| date = 1953\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> [[Sam Krieger]],<ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Bruce\n| last = Lambert\n| title = Ben Davidson, 90, a Co-Founder Of the Liberal Party in New York\n| work = New York Times\n| date = 22 December 1991\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/22/nyregion/ben-davidson-90-a-co-founder-of-the-liberal-party-in-new-york.html\n| accessdate = 7 April 2013}}</ref> [[Alfred J. Brooks]], [[Myra Page]], and [[Rachel Ragozin]].<ref name=Witness /><ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Robert W.\n| last = Iversen\n| title = The Communists & the Schools\n| publisher = Harcourt, Brace\n| year = 1959\n| page = 21\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1991/12/22/nyregion/ben-davidson-90-a-co-founder-of-the-liberal-party-in-new-york.html\n| accessdate = 7 April 2013| newspaper = The New York Times\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1926, Bert Miller ignited the [[1926 Passaic textile strike]], as related by [[Benjamin Gitlow]] in his 1939 memoir:  <blockquote><small>The man who started the ball rolling was Bert Miller, industrial organizer of District Two of the Party, which then included most of industrial New Jersey and Connecticut as well as New York City. Comrade Miller called to my attention the fact that the Botany Mills of Passaic had announced a wage cut of ten percent, beginning with October, 1925. I immediately instructed Miller to get in touch with our New Jersey comrades and explore the matter further, agreeing with him that on its face the situation seemed favorable enough for initiating agitation for a strike in retaliation for the wage cut. Miller was a veteran of the Party since its underground days and carried out his assignment expeditiously. His report convinced me that there was ample ground for developing a successful strike.<ref name=\"Gitlow\">\n{{cite book\n| first = Benjamin \n| last = Gitlow\n| title = I Confess: The Truth About American Communism\n| publisher = E.P. Dutton\n| url = https://archive.org/details/BenjaminGitlow\n| pages = 363 (Passaic), 575 (Lovestone split)\n| date = 1940\n| accessdate = 7 August 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>   [[Albert Weisbord]], main leader of the Passaic strike, recalled later and critically of both Miller (\"the innocent\") and the Communist Party:  <blockquote><small> In New York I contacted Bert Miller, a teacher made suddenly \"industrial\" organizer of the Party, who, as a newcomer in the office, tried to live up to a job he knew very little about... <br> I was just now, in 1924, that ignorant, unsuspicious me had to enter into that nest of intrigue, without the lightest inkling of the kind of leadership under which I was enlisting... <br> I soon found the approximately 400 strikers in meeting in a small hall near the mill... We built up a picket line, drew up our demands and created a semblance of organization. They no longer felt lost or abandoned... They wanted to see membership applications and membership dues books...  Back in New York I reported all this to Miller. This innocent agreed that I should get application and membership cards printed. He was not aware that on this matter he would be bitterly assailed by the Foster-Cannon leadership for dual unionism and would open up a major struggle with the Party... <br> The worthlessness of the C.P. leaders did not in the least make me undervalue the great worth of the tens of thousands of devoted foreign-born workers and militant American-born youth who were the members and followers of that party... At the moment for me the important link in the chain was the innocent Bert Miller, acting on this own while the \"bigs\" were tied up with other matters, especially the N.Y. District Organizer [[Willam Weinstone|Weinstone]] who was very busy intriguing with Cannon on how to form a new faction to end factions!  Weinstone\u2019s sloth and Miller\u2019s ignorance were to help me much.<ref>\n{{cite web\n| first = Albert\n| last = Weisbord\n| authorlink = Albert Weisbord\n| title = Passaic Review\n| publisher = Albert & Vera Weisbord Foundation\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/archive/weisbord/Reviewed.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref></small> </blockquote>     In 1926, Bert Miller also became business manager of the ''[[Daily Worker]]'' communist newspaper.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz /><ref name=Ryskind />  His name first appears on the masthead in the November 26, 1926 issue,<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Daily Worker\n| publisher = Daily Worker Publishing Co.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/dw-hr-1926/v3n264-nov-20-1926-TDW.pdf\n| location = Chicago\n| date = 26 November 1926\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> and appeared throughout 1926<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = The Daily Worker - 1926\n| publisher = Marxists.org\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/1926/index.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> and 1927<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = The Daily Worker - 1927\n| publisher = Marxists.org\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/1927/index.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> \u2013 the publication of \"business manager\" dropped from the masthead in 1928.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = The Daily Worker - 1928\n| publisher = Marxists.org\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/dailyworker/1927/index.htm\n| date = \n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref> Whittaker Chambers recalled:    <blockquote><small>In those days, Bert Miller was a harassed soul.  As business manager of the ''Daily Worker'', the future research director of the House Committee on Un-American Activities had to meet a weekly payroll and find money to pay the paper, print, and other bills.  Money was very hard to find, and his life was a weekly crisis.  Thus, my chief recollection of Bert Miller from the past is less than a face than as a weary plaint:  money. <br> Bert suffered other grievances, too.  In his business office, he presided over a number of young women Communists, one of whom was a remarkably pretty Hungarian girl.  He often protested that his girls were terrified towalk through the ''Daily Worker'' office (as they sometimes had to) because, while they wriggled their way past he crowded chairs, each of the editors in turn reached back and pinched them.<ref name=Witness /></small></blockquote>    In 1927, Mandel was elected to the Party's Central Committee at its fifth congress in 1927.  In 1929, he was re-elected as a \"candidate member\" at its sixth convention in March 1929. Later that year, he was expelled with followers of [[Jay Lovestone]] (known at the [[Lovestoneites]]) as an \"incurable right-wing deviationist\".<ref name=Witness /><ref name=Meier /><ref>\n{{cite book\n| last = Draper\n| first = Theodore\n| title = American Communism and Soviet Russia: The Formative Period\n| publisher = Viking Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9praAAAAMAAJ\n| pages =430, 531, 561\n| date = 1960\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Communist Party (Opposition) (CPO)====\n\nAs of the first issue (November 1, 1929), Bert Miller appeared on the editorial board of ''[[Revolutionary Age]]'', organ of the [[Lovestoneites|Communist Party (Majority)]] formed by Jay Lovestone, i.e., he joined Lovestone's Communist Party (Majority Group).  Other editors included: [[Benjamin Gitlow]], editor; [[Bertram Wolfe]], associate editor; and editorial board members J.O. Bixby, Ellen Dawson, Will Herberg, William Miller, R. Pires, Jack Rubinstein, Frank Vrataric, Ed Welsh, W.J. White, Herbert Zam, and Charles S. Zimmerman.<ref name=\"RA-19291101\">\n{{cite journal\n| title = Opening of Marx-Lenin School (ad)\n| journal = Revolutionary Age |volume=1 |issue=2\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n02-nov-15-1929.pdf\n| date = 15 November 1929\n| page = 6\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| first =  John Patrick Haithcox\n| last = Haithcox\n| title = Communism and Nationalism in India: M.N. Roy and Comintern Policy, 1920-1939\n| publisher = Princeton University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Y3d9BgAAQBAJ\n| pages= 320 (fn92)\n| date = 8 March 2015\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018| isbn = 9781400869329\n}}</ref>\n\nMiller was also one of the original teachers at the New Workers School of the Lovestoneites, as advertised in the November 15 issue<ref name=\"Ad\">\n{{cite journal\n| title = Opening of Marx-Lenin School! (ad)\n| journal = Revolutionary Age |volume=1 |issue=2\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n02-nov-15-1929.pdf\n| date = 15 November 1929\n| page = 11\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref> and detailed in a December 15 article.<ref name=\"Build\">\n{{cite journal\n| title = Build the Marx-Lenin School!\n| journal = Revolutionary Age |volume=1 |issue=7\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n07-feb-01-1930.pdf\n| date = 1 February 1930\n| page = 9\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1930, Miller spoke in Philadelphia to some 300 workers regarding \"The Crisis in the Communist Party of the USA.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Miller Speaks in Philadelphia\n| journal = Revolutionary Age\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v1n12-apr-21-1930.pdf\n| date = 15 August 1931\n| page = 11\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring 1930, Miller joined the [[Conference for Progressive Labor Action]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last = Alexander\n| first = Robert J \n| title = The Right Opposition: The Lovestoneites and the International Communist Opposition of the 1930s\n| publisher = Greenwood Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=MnoEAQAAIAAJ&q\n| isbn = 0-313-22070-0\n| pages= 63\u201369\n| date = 1981\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1931, the Communist League of Struggle (Adhering to the International Left Opposition), attached Miller as a Lovestone leader:  <blockquote><small>Do you think that it is an accident that out of your ranks, trained by Lovestone, have sprung OPEN RENEGADES from Communism, Bert Miller and Company? Can you not see that Bert Miller but does what Lovestone is planning to do -- later, that Miller is but the vanguard of Lovestone himself?<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Where Are You Going?\n| journal = Class Struggle\n| url = http://www.weisbord.org/OneTwo.htm\n| date = June 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref> <br> ... In spite of intrigue on the part of the official Communist Party, the Lovestone group and its allies, Bert Miller and [[Ludwig Lore]] -- about 250 attended the [[Albert Weisbord]]-[[Louis F. Budenz]] debate at the Labor Temple, Saturday, May 2. The topic was \"Shall the Workers Support the Conference for Progressive Labor Action in Preference to the Communists?\"... After the posters, leaflets and advertisements announcing the debate were released, pressure to kill the debate opened. According to reports, [[William Z. Foster]] who was scheduled to debate Muste a week later, threatened to withdraw if Muste debated Weisbord first. Under the Party's pressure, Muste decided not to debate Weisbord and assigned Budenz in his stead. This was the time for Miller, the \"communist\" watch-dog and advisor to the C.P.L.A. to step in with his \"expert\" advice. Lore also advised Budenz not to go through with the arrangements.<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = Sylvan A.\n| last = Pollack\n| title = Current Comments\n| journal = Class Struggle\n| url = http://www.weisbord.org/OneTwo.htm\n| date = June 1931\n| page = 2\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>  By August 1931, the Lovestoneites were commenting angrily in ''Revolutionary Age'': \"As soon as this group of comrades entered the CPLA<ref>Conference for Progressive Labor Action</ref> and began to function, a differentiation began to take place:  Bert Miller, Levich, and Lawrence began to move rapidly to the extreme right, while the rest of the comrades under the leadeship of Comrade Benjamin, took up a sharp struggle against social reformism and against Miller and his friends as well.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Communists and the C.P.L.A.\n| journal = Revolutionary Age\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v2n37-aug-15-1931.pdf\n| date = 15 August 1931\n| page = 4\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref>  Miller's push for this group caused Benjamin Gitlow to split with the [[Lovestoneites]], who insisted that \"Stalin's policies were a hundred percent correct.\"<ref name=\"Gitlow\"/>\n\nBy October 1931, ''Revolutionary Age'' was calling Miller, Gitlow, and others \"traitors\":  <blockquote><small>'''ON WORKERS SOLIDARITY'''<br> A fine day of celebration for these traitors, who, together with Gitlow, [[Louis F. Budenz|Budenz]], Bert Miller and Zimmerman and the smaller fry of Lovestone renegades, are trying to break the strike of the textile workers. Labor Day is a day that symbolizes the attempted sell-out of their militant struggles. It is a day of hatred of the system that makes use of such scum from Green, Woll to Gitlow, Budenz, [[A.J. Muste|Muste]] and the smaller gang of pickpockets, who pose as \"labor leaders.\" <br>August 22, 1931 , [[Israel Amter|I. Amter]]<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = On Workers Solidarity\n| journal = Revolutionary Age\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/revolutionary-age/v2n44-oct-03-1931.pdf\n| date = April 1930\n| page = 2\n| accessdate = 24 October 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>     In 1931, Miller's name appeared as a national officer of the Joint Committee on Unemployment, headed by [[John Dewey]].<ref name=RedNetwork />  On November 19, 1931, \"Benjamin Mandel\" attended a protest against Italian foreign minister [[Dino Grandi]], a \"Fascist diplomat\":  as part of deputation from the Committee for International Anti-Fascist Protest, Mandel joined [[A.J. Muste]], [[Roger Nash Baldwin|Roger Baldwin]], and several Italian-Americans.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Bomb Guard Alert for Visit of Grandi\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1931/11/20/archives/bomb-guard-alert-for-visit-of-grandi-report-of-plot-on-morgan.html\n| date = 20 November 1931\n| page = 12\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>  On December 2, 1931, \"Benjamin Mandel\" as \"organizer for the Brotherhood of Brooklyn Edison Employees\" as well as observer for the [[Conference for Progressive Labor Action]], joined a group of nine led by Rev. Eliot White, formerly of the [[Grace Church (Manhattan)|Grace Episcopal Church]], to distribute union literature, when they found themselves attacked by hundreds of people.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Thugs Beat Minister in Edison Union Row\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1931/12/03/archives/thugs-beat-minister-in-edison-union-row-hundreds-set-upon-rev-eliot.html\n| date = 3 December 1931\n| page = 1\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Accuse Edison Men of Striking Pastor\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1931/12/09/archives/accuse-edison-men-of-striking-pastor-but-witnesses-fail-to-identify.html\n| date = 9 December 1931\n| page = 2\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>  In its December 1931 issue, ''Labor Age'' described Mandel as \"labor organizer and writer... active in the White Plains Road Laborers Strike last summer... now helping the Brooklyn Edison Employes organization campaign.\"<ref name=LA1931Dec>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Benjamin \n| last1=Mandel\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = American Welcomes Grandi\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n12-dec-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = December 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1932, Mandel had called for a bar to admittance of communists during a meeting to discuss the ongoing [[Harlan County, Kentucky|Harlan County]] coal strike that had started in 1931 (see [[Harlan County War]]): <blockquote><small>\"No communists are admitted here\", was the greeting at the door, which met the delegate of the C.L.S., who tried to attend the \"broad united front of labor\", called by the I.W.W. General Defense Committee for the Harlan Kentucky miners on January 6. Of course it had to be the unspeakable Bert Miller, who handed out this information. All sorts of liberals, anarchists, and what not were gathered together, but the Communists were not even allowed to enter the hall!\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = Current Comment: No Communist Admitted\n| publisher = Class Struggle: Official Organ of the Communist League of Struggle\n| url = http://www.weisbord.org/TwoOne.htm\n| date = 1981\n| accessdate = 3 March 2018}}</ref></small></blockquote>  On March 6, 1932, Mandel joined a committee that supported the $375 million Costigan-La Follettee-Lewis relief bill, itself part of a $3 billion federal bill to provide housing credit, end sales taxes, and increases surtaxes and estate taxes.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 3 Billions Urged for Public Works\n| work = Washington Post\n| url =\n| date = 7 March 1932\n| page = 5\n| accessdate = }}</ref>\n\n===Benjamin Mandel===\n\nOn July 17, 1932, a new joint committee on unemployment in New York state formed under Bishop Francis J. McConnell of the Methodist Baptist Church in Manhattan.  Committee members included: Sidney E. Goldstein, [[Stephen S. Wise]], Mary Fox, Alfred Bernheim, Darwin J. Meserole, Howard Y. Williams, [[A.J. Muste]], [[J.B. Matthews]], William Spofford, Winifred Chappell, [[Abraham Lefkowitz]], [[Sidney Hillman]], [[Paul Blanshard]], Jack Altman, Helen Alfred, [[Walter Francis White|Walter White]], and LeRoy E. Bowman.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = State Drive Opened for Jobless Relief\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1932/07/18/archives/state-drive-opened-for-jobless-relief-bishop-mcconnell-heads-new.html\n| date = 18 July 1932\n| page =15\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Dies Committee and Rapp Coudert====\n\nBy the later 1930s, \"Bert Miller\" the former communist had become a dedicated anti-communist and by 1939 had resurfaced fully as \"Benjamin Mandel\" to help [[J.B. Matthews]] as a researcher for the [[Dies Committee]] until 1945. He also worked with the New York legislature during the [[Rapp-Coudert Committee|Rapp-Courdert inquiry]] into the presence of Communist teachers in New York schools.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz /><ref name=Meier /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n(In 1939, after [[Isaac Don Levine]] had introduced them, [[Walter Krivitsky]] told Chambers that \"Ben Mandel\" of the [[Dies Committee]] was \"Bert Miller\" of the Communist Party.<ref name=Witness />)\n\nIn 1940 during Rapp-Coudert Committee investigations, \"Benjamin Mandel\" became connected with Communist activities under the name \"Bert Miller.\"<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Legislative Document, Volume 10\n| publisher = J.B. Lyon Company\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H8StmFlH0uEC\n| pages = 180, 305, 315\n| date = 1942\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Report of the subcommittee of the Joint legislative committee to investigate procedures and methods of allocating state moneys for public school purposes and subversive activities\n| publisher = New York (State) Legislature - Joint Committee on the State Education System\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=UxRKAAAAMAAJ\n| pages = 180, 305, 315\n| date = 1942\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref>  The same year, Matthews connected \"Benjamin Mandel\" with \"Bert Miller\" during the testimony of [[Leonard Emil Mins]] before the Dies Committee.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Investigation of Un-American Propaganda Activities in the United States\n| publisher = US GPO\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=SAugbQDPbK4C\n| page = 3428\n| date = 1940\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 7, 1941, Mandel himself testified before Dies Committee regarding the China Aid Council, a subsidiary of the [[American League for Peace and Democracy]].  He named Dr. [[Owen Lattimore]], [[Frederick V. Field]], and others.<ref name=Kienholz />\n\nFrom 1945 to 1947, Mandel worked for the [[U.S. Department of State]] in handling \"security.\"<ref name=WPobit />\n\n====HUAC====\n\nIn 1947, Mandel returned to former Dies Committee, now renamed the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC), \"to assist the committee in the [[Alger Hiss|Hiss]]-[[Whittaker Chambers|Chambers]] case.\"<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=Kienholz />  He has been characterized, along with U.S. Representative [[J. Parnell Thomas]] and HUAC chief investigator [[Robert E. Stripling]] as one of the \"choreographers of the hearings.\"<ref name=Ryskind />\n\nDuring the Hiss Case, Mandel participated in questioning during hearings.  Mandel stated \"A picture of Hiss shows his hand cupped to his ear,\" to which Chambers replied, \"He is deaf in one ear.\"  Mandel asked, \"How is it that he (Hiss) never wrote anything publicly,\" to which Chambers answered, \"He was never in the open Communist Party.\"  Mandel checked for \"George Crosley\" as a government employee and received the negative findings from one Ernest S. Griffith, director of Legislative Reference Service.  He also partook in the search for the Ford car sold by Hiss to William Rosen.<ref name=Witness /><ref name=Kienholz />\n\nOn May 2, 1949, Steele spoke with Congressman [[Richard Nixon]] and [[Walter S. Steele]] (publisher of ''The National Republic'' magazine and member of the American Coalition of Patriotic, Civic and Fraternal Societies, founded by [[John B. Trevor Sr.]])) at a [[Knights of Columbus]] annual town hall.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = 3 to speak at anti-Red rally here: Sponsored by KC\n| work = Washington Post\n| page = M20\n| date = 1 May 1949}}</ref>\n\n====SISS====\n\nIn 1951, Mandel left HUAC<ref name=NYTobit/> and became research director in the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee, and stayed in that position until his retirement in 1967.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news\n| title = Senators Oppose White House Curb: Senate Investigator Retires\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1967/11/02/archives/senators-oppose-white-house-curb-balk-at-limiting-authority-to-make.html\n| date = 2 November 1967\n| page = 9\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref> During his SIS years, he took an active role in connect the influence of the Communist Party and communist-influenced labor unions (e.g., [[Congress of Industrial Organizations|CIO]]) in the Teachers' Union and among teachers (e.g., see \"Mandel\" in 1952 hearings<ref name=HUAC-1952 />).<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nIn May 1951, [[Benjamin Gitlow]] told the Senate's Subversive Activities Control Board that he had \"repeatedly discussed\" the board with its research director Mandel as well as another former Communist associate [[Joseph Zack Kornfeder]]. Gitlow said, \"I discussed the conduct of this case.  I discussed the attorneys in the case.  I discussed the members of the panel.\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| title = McCarran's Reds\n| journal = The New Republic\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=eSDIsytObNsC\n| page = 7\n| date = 28 May 1951\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019| last1 = Croly\n| first1 = Herbert David\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] criticized Mandel in her column:     <blockquote> <small> I was sent a column the other day by a gentleman which he had clipped from a paper and felt was very convincing. The column was written by Benjamin Mandel, a former research director of the House Un-American Activities Committee and at present a member of the Senate Internal Security Subcommittee. Mr. Mandel was writing as a guest columnist for Mr. C. Brown. <br> Mr. Mandel in his column took all liberals and intellectuals to task for sitting in judgment on Congressional committees investigating Communist activities. Most of the column pointed out the \"faults of liberals\" and of course, being human beings, I don't suppose they are perfect but it seemed to me this column was very slanted in its reasoning. <br> Unquestionably, critical self-examination should be of value to liberals and intellectuals, but I have no doubt it would be of value to those who conduct Congressional investigations also. <ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = My Day\n| publisher = The Eleanor Roosevelt Papers Project\n| url = https://www2.gwu.edu/~erpapers/myday/displaydoc.cfm?_y=1953&_f=md002679\n| date = 23 May 1953\n| accessdate = 28 January 2020}}</ref> </small> </blockquote>    In 1956, [[TASS]] deputy bureau chief [[Harry Freeman (journalist)|Harry Freeman]] testified before SISS. Mandel read a passage from Whittaker Chambers' 1952 memoir ''Witness'' about Freeman at the ''Daily Worker''.  In retort, Freeman reminded SISS that Mandel was there, too, as business manager.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| first = Ed \n| last = Creagh\n| title = Top Tass Official in U.S. Dodges Red Spy Quiz\n| work = New York Times\n| url =\n| date = 22 February 1956\n| page = 11\n| accessdate = }}</ref>  On October 25, 1967, lawyers for the [[National Conference for New Politics]] (NCNP) and the [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]] (MFDP) filed an order to take immediate sworn statements about documents from Senator [[James O. Eastland]] and subcommittee staffers, J.G. Sourwine and Mandel to enjoin any further distribution or use of the files.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Senators Oppose White House Curb: Senate Investigator Retires\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1967/10/29/archives/dissenters-and-foes-eastland-on-a-new-subversive-hunt.html\n| date = 29 October 1967\n| page = 9\n| accessdate = 16 January 2019}}</ref>  In 1959, [[I.F. Stone]] named Mandel as \"another powerful Lovestoneite,\"<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = I.F.\n| last = Stone\n| authorlink = I.F. Stone\n| title = I.F. Stone's Weekly\n| publisher = Kraus Reprint Co.\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=I99JAQAAIAAJ\n| page = 70\n| date = 1959\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref> while researcher [[Robert W. Iversen]] noted Mandel in his book ''The Communists & the Schools'',<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Robert W.\n| last = Iversen\n| authorlink = Robert W. Iversen\n| title = The Communists & the Schools\n| publisher = Harcourt, Brace\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=s3CcAAAAMAAJ\n| pages = 21\n| date = 1959\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref> and [[Theodore Draper]] consulted him for his book ''American Communism and Soviet Russia''.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Theodore\n| last = Draper\n| authorlink = Theodore Draper\n| title = American Communism and Soviet Russia\n| publisher = Viking Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=JGdZJPEh_LsC\n| pages = 525\n| date = 1960\n| accessdate = 27 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 1967, Mandel announced his retirement.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=\"New York Times\"/>  He continued to consult to that subcommittee for some years.<ref name=WPobit />\n\nMandel, following Matthews before him, supplied information about \"suspect clergy\" to [[Carl McIntire]] (1906&ndash;2002), a founder and minister in the [[Bible Presbyterian Church]], founder and long-time president of the [[International Council of Christian Churches]] and the [[American Council of Christian Churches]], and a popular religious radio broadcaster, who proudly identified himself as a [[Christian fundamentalist|fundamentalist]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Markku \n| last = Ruotsila\n| title = Fighting Fundamentalist: Carl McIntire and the Politicization of American Fundamentalism\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=uCygCgAAQBAJ\n| pages = 117\n| date = 2016\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019| isbn = 9780199372997\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal and death==\n\nMandel married Margaret Rees.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nHe believed in exposing the Communist Party in the U.S. and explained in 1951:  <blockquote><small>You've got to assume there is a present communist conspiracy, and it is obvious the communists want every additional scrap of atomic information they can lay hands on.  <br>  There are two ways to meet this conspiracy.  One is to have a secret polic.  The other is to develop the evidence in the American way, in open hearings and with sworn testimony.  The goal should never be to railroad the people; always to respect civil liberties.<ref name=WPobit /></small></blockquote>\n\nMandel died age 82 on August 8, 1973, at the Mar-Salle Convalescent Home at 2131 O Street NW, Washington, DC.<ref name=WPobit /><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Works==\n\nAccording to his ''Washington Post'' obituary, Mandel was co-author of the book ''I Was a Soviet Worker'', published in the U.S. in 1936 and in the U.K. in 1937, but neither \"Mandel\" nor \"Miller\" appears in the book.<ref name=WPobit />\n\n'''As Bert Miller:'''\n* \"Giant Power,\" ''The Communist'' (August 1928)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first1=Bert \n| last1=Miller\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Giant Power\n| publisher = The Communist\n| url = http://www.unz.com/print/Communist-1928aug-00473/\n| date = August 1928\n| accessdate = 4 March 2018}}</ref>\n* \"Gandhi Betrays,\" ''Labor Age'' (May 1931)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Bert \n| last1=Miller\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Gandhi Betrays\n| journal = Labor Age\n| publisher = Labor Publication Society, Inc.\n| url = https://www.marxists.org/history/usa/pubs/laborage/v20n05-May-1931-Labor%20Age.pdf\n| date = May 1931\n| accessdate = 29 June 2019}}</ref>\n* \"Book Review:  Kautsky at the Crossroads\" ''Labor Age'' (July 1932)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first1=Bert \n| last1=Miller\n| authorlink = Benjamin Mandel\n| title = Book Review: Kautsky at the Crossroads\n| journal 